record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1026,
  "cap": "SSRF",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos/test",
  "rationale": "test_repo_connectivity for source_kind in {git, github, gitlab} hands req.source_url_or_path straight to git_ls_remote_probe → `git -c credential.helper= ls-remote --exit-code <url>` (router.rs:1025-1042). No scheme allowlist, no host allowlist, no rejection of internal addresses. Two concrete primitives: (a) `ext::<command args>` — git's `ext` remote helper executes the command verbatim under the daemon UID (CVE-2017-1000117 family; still reachable today because the handler does not pass `-c protocol.ext.allow=never`), giving authenticated RCE; (b) `http://10.0.0.5/git/repo` or `http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/` — git speaks HTTP and the daemon makes the request, surfacing pass/fail and stderr back to the caller, yielding authenticated SSRF + content-length oracle on internal services. The probe is gated by the bearer token (route is auth-layered), but chains with finding #2 (pre-setup AUTH_BYPASS — note: test_repo_connectivity is not on the setup-open path so this chain requires post-setup auth) and finding #6 (DNS rebind → cross-origin authed access). Static pass missed because git's transport plug-in surface isn't modeled by typical exec-sink analyzers — the dangerous behavior is one binary's argument, not a shell metacharacter.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/projects/proj-x/repos/test {\"source_kind\":\"git\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"ext::sh -c id>/tmp/pwn\"} — observe /tmp/pwn appear. Mitigate by passing `-c protocol.ext.allow=never -c protocol.allow=never` and a scheme/host allowlist before spawn."
}

