record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 691,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (pre-HMAC Ping/Other 200-ack path)",
  "rationale": "webhook_git classifies the upstream event header and short-circuits with `200 OK` for `EventKind::Ping` (webhook.rs:694-704) and `EventKind::Other(name)` (:705-715) BEFORE invoking `verify_signature` (:741). The signature header is checked only for syntactic well-formedness (:681-683 — 64-char hex regex). Two distinct primitives emerge: (a) **per-IP rate-limit exhaustion** — each Ping/Other request consumes one token from `WebhookRateLimiter` (:631-639, default burst=30, refill=30/min) and one permit from `WebhookConcurrencyLimit` (:644-655, default 8) before the unauthenticated short-circuit fires. A single attacker IP firing `POST /webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=0000…0000' -H 'X-GitHub-Event: ping'` at ~1 req/2s pegs the per-IP bucket empty, blocking legitimate GitHub deliveries from that same IP (or any NAT'd-shared IP) with a 429. The rate-limit gate runs FIRST in the handler so mitigating one tier doesn't restore the other. (b) **provider fingerprint without auth** — Ping returns body `{\"triggered\":false,\"message\":\"ping event acknowledged\"}`; Other returns `{\"triggered\":false,\"message\":\"event `<name>` is not a push; ignored\"}` with the echoed event name. Rotating `X-GitHub-Event` / `X-Gitea-Event` / `X-Forgejo-Event` / `X-Gogs-Event` / `X-Gitlab-Event` headers and observing which yields a 200-with-ping-ack vs Unknown-fallthrough (which proceeds to HMAC and returns 401) tells the attacker which upstream provider the operator wired, narrowing the secret-source candidate set for later credential-phishing. Distinct from finding #15 (3-way 500/503/401 oracle on webhook posture): that one fingerprints whether the webhook is armed; this one fingerprints which provider is wired AND turns a single attacker IP into a DoS against deliveries from the same source. Static pass missed it because the dangerous behavior is the interaction between an admission-control gate (rate limiter, runs first) and an unauthenticated ack path (runs third) — taint analysis treats both as benign in isolation. Mitigation: move the rate-limit and concurrency gates AFTER `verify_signature` for Ping/Other branches, or require valid HMAC before any 200-ack regardless of declared event kind (the upstream-retry concern that motivated the early ack is moot when the signature is forged — the legitimate provider always carries valid HMAC).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "loop { curl -s -o/dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8088/webhook/git -H 'X-GitHub-Event: ping' -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256='$(printf '0%.0s' $(seq 1 64)) ; sleep 1.9 } — observe 200/200/200/.../429 cadence; concurrently real GitHub pushes from a colocated CI runner get 429. Then rotate -H 'X-GitHub-Event:' / 'X-Gitea-Event:' / etc. to fingerprint the wired provider via which header yields ping-ack vs 401."
}

