record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 737,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (pre-HMAC, slow-body permit pinning across `to_bytes` await)",
  "rationale": "Distinct primitive from finding #16 (which drains the per-IP token bucket via fast ping-acks). The new `WebhookConcurrencyLimit` permit is acquired at webhook.rs:644-655 BEFORE secret resolution, BEFORE the Push/Ping/Other event classifier (:691), and BEFORE the `to_bytes(body, MAX_WEBHOOK_BODY_BYTES).await` at :737. The permit is bound to `_permit` and lives across that await for the full handler scope (drop at end-of-fn). The body read has a 1 MiB byte cap but NO wall-clock / read-timeout: an attacker who advertises `Content-Length: 1048576` (or just relies on chunked encoding without a Content-Length header — `to_bytes` enforces the cap at the body layer either way) and trickles one byte every ~30s holds the permit for ~9 hours per connection. With the default 8 permits, 8 such connections from a single attacker IP exhaust the global gate. Per-IP rate limiter does NOT close this hole: it charges *one* token per request (not per byte / per second held), so 8 long-lived slow-body requests fit trivially under the 30/min burst, AND the limiter runs first so it cannot 'see' the cumulative residence-time cost. After the 8th permit is held, every legitimate signed delivery (regardless of source IP, because the concurrency gate is global) returns `429 webhook concurrency limit reached`. The very semaphore added in this session to *protect* against valid-HMAC floods becomes the chokepoint that any unauthenticated attacker can peg with 8 raw TCP connections. The rate limiter's per-IP budget separately drains for the attacker's IP — but that just means subsequent attacker requests from the same IP get 429'd; the existing 8 slow connections continue to hold their permits because permit-acquisition already happened. Static pass missed this because the bug is the *interaction* between (a) permit-held-across-await semantics (correct in isolation), (b) bounded body cap with no read deadline (correct in isolation, and necessary for handling slow legitimate HTTP/1.1 streamed bodies), and (c) a defense-in-depth gate that runs admission-side rather than residence-side. Mitigations (any one closes the primitive): (1) wrap the `to_bytes` call in `tokio::time::timeout(Duration::from_secs(5), …)` — a stalled body releases the permit; (2) hoist the permit acquisition to AFTER the Content-Length check and Push/Ping/Other classification but BEFORE `to_bytes`, paired with a read deadline; (3) bound per-permit residence-time independently of byte cap; (4) replace the global semaphore with a per-IP semaphore so single-IP exhaustion only DoSes that IP's own future deliveries.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "python3 -c 'import socket,time\\nfor _ in range(8):\\n  s=socket.socket();s.connect((\"127.0.0.1\",8088));s.send(b\"POST /webhook/git HTTP/1.1\\\\r\\\\nHost: x\\\\r\\\\nX-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=\"+b\"0\"*64+b\"\\\\r\\\\nContent-Type: application/json\\\\r\\\\nContent-Length: 1048576\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n\");time.sleep(0)\\nimport sys;sys.stdin.read()' — opens 8 sockets, sends headers + 0 body bytes, blocks. From a second shell `curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8088/webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=<valid>' -d @push.json` returns 429 immediately. Kill the python process and legitimate deliveries resume. The asymmetry between bearer-gated `/api/v1/scan` (still works) and HMAC-gated `/webhook/git` (429-locked) is the confirmation."
}

