record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/webhook.rs",
  "line": 612,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (per-IP token bucket keyed on TCP peer, not upstream client)",
  "rationale": "`peer_ip_from_request` (webhook.rs:612-614) reads the source address from `ConnectInfo<SocketAddr>`, which axum populates from the kernel-level TCP peer of the accepted connection — never from `X-Forwarded-For` / `Forwarded` / `X-Real-IP`. The rate-limiter wired in session-0020 (default 30/min per-IP, burst 30, max 1024 tracked IPs) is keyed on this address. Two pathological deployment shapes drop out, neither documented in the WebhookConfig doc-comment (which only warns about ConnectInfo being *absent*, not about it being *wrong*):\n\n(a) **Proxy-fronted shared-bucket DoS** — any operator who terminates TLS or pre-filters in front of nyctos (nginx, Caddy, Cloudflare Tunnel, Tailscale Funnel, ngrok, an ALB) presents one peer IP to nyctos for *all* upstream GitHub/Gitea/Gitlab deliveries. With the default 30/min cap, the entire fleet of monitored repos shares a single bucket; the 31st delivery per minute (from any provider, any repo, any region) hits `429 webhook rate limit exceeded`. Worse, an unauthenticated attacker who can route any request through the *same* proxy (a public Cloudflare zone, a shared ingress, a multi-tenant LB) lands their pre-HMAC ping-ack from finding #16 in the same bucket and DoSes legitimate deliveries. The doc-comment on `peer_ip_from_request` and on `WebhookConfig.rate_limit` says proxy-fronted deployments 'fall back to the global concurrency cap' — actually false: per-IP throttling fires, just keyed on the wrong identity.\n\n(b) **Direct-bind v6 sweep evades throttle** — without a proxy, the per-IP cap is real per-IP. An attacker with any /64 IPv6 prefix (commodity VPS provides one routed /64 free) has 2^64 source addresses; the limiter's 1024-IP eviction map churns continuously and never throttles the attacker (each fresh source IP gets a full bucket at `or_insert_with` — webhook.rs:528). The eviction step at :517-523 does a linear `g.iter().min_by_key(|(_, b)| b.last_refill)` under a synchronous `std::sync::Mutex` (:496) inside the async handler, so each unique-IPv6 admit takes O(1024) under the lock, head-of-line blocking every other concurrent webhook delivery in tokio's scheduler. The asymmetry is sharper than finding #16: there, the same IP drains over time; here, no IP ever drains because every request is a new IP, and the *throttle itself* turns into a lock-contention amplifier. Combined with finding #17 (slow-body permit pinning), an attacker can both peg the global semaphore AND saturate the limiter mutex from a single host.\n\nMitigations (orthogonal — pick by deployment shape): (1) parse the operator-trusted forwarded-for header through a `TrustedProxiesConfig` (allowlist of immediate-upstream IPs that are permitted to set X-Forwarded-For); (2) replace `std::sync::Mutex<HashMap>` with `dashmap::DashMap` or per-IP `AtomicU64` token counters so the limiter never serialises async tasks; (3) cap eviction at LRU-2 / sketch-based decay so the per-admit cost is O(log n) or O(1) rather than O(max_ips); (4) document that without a forwarded-for trust chain, operators MUST run nyctos as the public listener (no proxy), and have the wizard refuse a `[ui].listen_addr` of 127.0.0.1 when `[triggers].webhook_secret_ref` is set unless an explicit `webhook_trust_proxy_header` knob is present.\n\nStatic pass missed it because the dangerous behavior is the gap between *what the operator's deployment model assumes the throttle key means* and *what the code actually keys on* — there is no tainted-flow sink and the code in isolation is correct; the bug is a documentation/deployment-shape mismatch with two distinct exploitable consequences.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "(a) `for i in $(seq 1 60); do curl -s -o/dev/null -w '%{http_code}\\n' -X POST https://nyctos.example.tld/webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256='$(printf '0%.0s' $(seq 1 64)) -H 'X-GitHub-Event: ping'; done` from one host — when nyctos is behind any proxy, the 31st request returns 429 and *every legitimate GitHub push delivered through the same proxy returns 429 too*, regardless of GitHub's actual source IP set. (b) From an IPv6-routed VPS: `for i in $(seq 0 2000); do curl -6 --interface 2001:db8::$(printf '%x' $i) -X POST http://[v6host]:8088/webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256='$(printf '0%.0s' $(seq 1 64)) -H 'X-GitHub-Event: ping' & done; wait` — observe TCP RTT to a separately measured GET / endpoint climb proportional to the unique-IP churn, confirming the synchronous mutex serialises async tasks under load."
}

