record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2678,
  "cap": "SYMLINK_FOLLOW_TOCTOU",
  "endpoint": "<state>/traces/<run_id>/<task_id>.jsonl (audit log writer)",
  "rationale": "`write_exploration_audit_jsonl` opens the JSONL via `OpenOptions::new().write(true).create(true).truncate(true).open(&path)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2678-2682) with no `O_NOFOLLOW`, no `O_EXCL` / `create_new`, and no symlink_metadata check on either the `run_dir` or `path`. `create_dir_all(&run_dir)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2674) also follows symlinks for the intermediate components. On a multi-tenant host (or any host where another local process can race to plant a symlink under `<state>/traces/<run_id>/` between two scan invocations), a pre-staged symlink at `<state>/traces/<run_id>/expl-<repo>.jsonl` → `/home/victim/.ssh/authorized_keys` causes the next scan's audit write to truncate and overwrite the target with attacker-influenced JSONL content (operator-visible exploration audit lines: `{\"action\":\"record_exploration_finding\",\"summary\":\"...\"}`). Even single-tenant, `<state>` is typically `~/.local/share/nyctos` (or wherever StateDir.ensure points) — group-or-world traversable if umask permits — so any local user who can read the traces directory tree can race the write. The `truncate(true)` makes this a *destructive* primitive, not just a confidentiality one: even if the attacker can't read the symlink target afterward, they can wipe arbitrary daemon-readable files (config, sqlite db at `<state>/runs/nyctos.db`, the operator's vouched-pubkey files in `<state>/secrets/`). Static pass missed it because (i) Rust's `OpenOptions` API hides the `O_NOFOLLOW` knob behind the `std::os::unix::fs::OpenOptionsExt::custom_flags` extension trait; the dataflow rule for File::create has no symlink awareness; (ii) the relevant secrets directory has 0700 (state.rs:secrets — confirmed elsewhere in the diff history) but the *new* `traces` SUBDIR has no analogous mode hardening — state.rs:11 just appends `\"traces\"` to SUBDIRS and inherits the default 0755 from `create_dir_all`. Fix: `OpenOptions::new().write(true).create_new(true).custom_flags(libc::O_NOFOLLOW | libc::O_CLOEXEC).open(&path)`; if the file legitimately needs to be overwritten across re-runs, `fs::remove_file(&path).ok()` first inside a directory whose metadata has been verified (open the run_dir with O_DIRECTORY|O_NOFOLLOW then `*at` syscalls). Pair with explicit 0700 on the `traces` SUBDIR in `StateDir::ensure`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "On a shared host, as a non-daemon UID, `mkdir -p <state>/traces/<predicted-run-id> && ln -s /home/daemon/.ssh/authorized_keys <state>/traces/<predicted-run-id>/expl-<predicted-repo>.jsonl`. Trigger a scan via the normal operator path. Post-run: `cat /home/daemon/.ssh/authorized_keys` shows JSONL audit lines, original key contents gone. For race-mode (no predictable id): inotify-watch `<state>/traces` and `ln -sfT /target <state>/traces/$NEW_RUN_ID/expl-<r>.jsonl` between `create_dir_all` and the open call. Verifier seed: pre-create a symlink at the expected JSONL path pointing to a tempfile, run the pass, assert the tempfile contents now match the audit log lines (proving symlink followed)."
}

