{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2681,
  "cap": "AUDIT_LOG_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "<state>/traces/<run_id>/<task_id>.jsonl (audit log writer)",
  "rationale": "`write_exploration_audit_jsonl` opens the JSONL with `.truncate(true)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2681). The (run_id, task_id) pair is not unique across re-invocations: `task_id = format!(\"expl-{repo}\")` (ai_pipeline.rs:2505) is deterministic on `repo`, and `bundle.run_id` is reused whenever the pass dispatches more than one repo with the same identifier in the same bundle — or, more importantly, whenever an operator re-runs the exploration pass against the same run row for retry / debugging / re-anchoring after a partial failure. Each new call truncates the prior audit log to zero bytes before writing the fresh entries; the parent `agent_traces.conversation_jsonl_path` column stamped by `apply_exploration_outcome` (ai_pipeline.rs:2642) now references a file whose *historical* content has been silently destroyed. Three concrete consequences: (a) **forensic loss** — when an operator discovers a quarantined finding from run N was discarded by the verifier and re-runs exploration to capture additional context, the audit trail of the original run is gone; the parent agent_traces row still exists but `conversation_jsonl_path` no longer matches the bytes the verifier saw. (b) **defender-side detection evasion** — an attacker who triggers a benign-looking re-run (e.g. by causing a transient network failure that the operator retries) wipes the audit trail of the prior, possibly-suspicious exploration without leaving a record of the wipe; the parent agent_traces row's `finished_at_ms` updates in place too. (c) **double-finding accounting drift** — successful findings persist as `findings` table rows on each successful invocation, but the audit log only reflects the most recent one; a finding-row's `created_at_ms` may predate every line of the audit log it's nominally tied to. Distinct from #22 (which is the symlink-follow concern on the same `truncate(true)` flag): #22 is about *where* the truncate lands; this finding is about *what* truncate wipes when the path is correct. Static pass missed it because `OpenOptions.truncate(true)` is the documented-correct pattern for 'open for write, replace contents' — the bug is the semantic mismatch between 'audit log' (append-only, immutable history) and 'write-truncate' (last-writer-wins). Fix (any one closes the primitive): (1) replace `truncate(true)` with `append(true)` and emit a per-run JSON header line as the first record so consumers can split runs; (2) include a high-resolution timestamp suffix in the filename (`<task_id>-<unix_nanos>.jsonl`) so each call writes a distinct artefact and the parent agent_traces row stamps the specific one; (3) `create_new(true)` and refuse to run when the path already exists, surfacing the duplicate as a hard error to the operator; (4) hash-suffix the filename on collisions and stamp the resolved path on the trace row.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: prime `<state>/traces/run-X/expl-repo.jsonl` with sentinel content `{\"action\":\"prior\",\"summary\":\"existing\"}\\n`; dispatch a fresh exploration pass with `bundle.run_id = \"run-X\"` and a repo named `repo`; post-run assert the sentinel is gone (`!std::fs::read_to_string(&path).unwrap().contains(\"prior\")`). Real-world trigger: operator issues `nyctos scan` twice against the same run row (e.g. after a network blip caused the first call to surface zero findings); the second call's audit log replaces the first without leaving a record."
}

