  "rationale": "`build_exploration_scope` hard-codes `scope.allowed_hosts = Vec::new()` (ai_pipeline.rs:2511) with a comment that 'operators wire real hosts through the settings page once it ships' — but the prompt template at `exploration.rs:334-337` only renders the empty-list branch as the human-language string `(none; refuse any HTTP probe)` and still advertises `\"http.probe\"` to the agent loop (exploration.rs:69, DEFAULT_EXPLORATION_TOOL_NAMES). A workspace-wide grep confirms NO `http.probe` adapter implementation exists in the in-tree crates (only the constant, doc-comments, and a test assertion mentioning the name). That means: (i) the *only* host-restriction enforcement on `http.probe` is the model's voluntary compliance with the prompt's English-language `refuse any HTTP probe` instruction; (ii) any kernel-side denylist / allowlist / sandbox-netfilter gate lives entirely outside this workspace, in whatever agent-loop runtime the ClaudeCodeAdapter binds — a surface the static pass does not see and that the threat model documents as 'sandbox-enforced'. Three failure modes drop out: (a) **prompt-jailbreak host probe** — a finding-rationale injection or a tool-result reflection that gets the model to call `http.probe('http://169.254.169.254/...')` is one prompt away from probing IMDS / RFC1918 / loopback from the daemon-side runtime, because the in-tree code asserts no host check. (b) **runtime-swap silent escalation** — if an operator wires a different `AiRuntime` impl (the SDK / ClaudeCode picker is config-driven at config.ai.runtime; the local-llm and the not-yet-shipped-but-typed alternates are in tree), the new runtime inherits the tool-name list verbatim with no Rust-side guarantee that it enforces host scope. The compile-time tool-name list is the agent's API contract; absence of an in-tree adapter means there is no compile-time invariant binding 'http.probe is advertised' to 'http.probe is gated'. (c) **scope-drift under future endpoint discovery** — the same comment refers to env-builder endpoint discovery 'until that wiring lands'; the moment endpoint discovery populates `target_endpoints` (and, implicitly, `allowed_hosts`) the host gate becomes operator-config-driven, and there is no in-tree validator that rejects loopback / link-local / metadata-service addresses at the boundary where the wizard writes them (mirroring the open #6/#15-correction shape for `local_llm_url`). Distinct from finding #6 / #15-correction (SSRF via AI base_url; downgraded to no-impl): that one targets a runtime adapter; this targets the agent's own tool surface. Static pass missed it because the bug is the *gap* between an advertised tool name (constant in source) and an enforcing adapter (absent from source) — taint analysis has no signal for 'declared capability with no implementation'. Fix (orthogonal, pick two): (1) refuse to start an exploration pass when `runtime.advertised_tools().contains(\"http.probe\")` is true and no in-tree `HttpProbeGate` is constructed; (2) split `DEFAULT_EXPLORATION_TOOL_NAMES` into `read_only_tools` and `network_tools` and refuse to include the latter unless `scope.allowed_hosts.is_empty() == false` AND every host parses as non-loopback non-link-local non-RFC1918; (3) add a `chain_lane.allow_network: false` knob on the sandbox config that the runtime adapter must honor, and assert it at agent-loop dispatch; (4) at minimum, change the empty-list prompt branch to *omit* `http.probe` from the tools list entirely rather than advertising it with an English-language refusal.",
