  "endpoint": "FindingStore::set_spec / FindingStore::set_attack_provenance (public helpers on a foundational crate)",
  "rationale": "Session-0029 establishes the writer-ladder invariant in two places — spec.rs:91-95 enforces COALESCE on the SpecDerivation transactional path, and ai_pipeline.rs:1069-1086 documents the PS > SD > ChainReasoning priority on `apply_chain_outcome`. The new tests at spec.rs:183-260 lock in the expected behavior for the SD writer. BUT the sibling helpers `FindingStore::set_spec` (finding.rs:408-426) and `FindingStore::set_attack_provenance` (finding.rs:435-448) still issue raw `UPDATE findings SET attack_provenance = ?, prompt_version = ? WHERE id = ?` with no COALESCE — they unconditionally overwrite whatever stamp is on the row. A workspace-wide `grep -rn '\\.set_spec\\b|\\.set_attack_provenance\\b' --include='*.rs'` returns zero callers, and the FindingRecord doc at finding.rs:170-176 explicitly calls `set_spec` 'historical'. So this is not a *live* exploit — but it is a fully-functional, public, exported API on `nyctos-core` (a foundational crate) that contradicts the invariant the rest of the codebase now enforces. Three concrete regression vectors: (a) **silent ladder break on revival** — a future contributor reading the FindingStore impl finds `set_spec` as a one-line helper that does what its name says, calls it from a new pass (verifier retry, chain-reasoning rerank, an experimental triage path), and silently clobbers the PS stamp the new COALESCE-based path was added to protect. The new spec.rs tests do not catch this because they exercise the transactional helper, not the standalone setter. (b) **provenance laundering on a future caller** — the helper accepts an arbitrary `attack_provenance: &str`; if a future pass surfaces a `set_attack_provenance` call from operator-influenced input (verifier retry hint, chain-rerank override, triage UI write-through), an attacker reaching that input plane can flip an LLM-synthesised row to `ManualPromote` without going through the audited `set_promote_manual` path (finding.rs:498-507). (c) **doc-rot reinforcement** — the doc-comment on `spec_id` at finding.rs:170-176 still positively references `set_spec` as a co-writer, suggesting the contract is current; a reader reasonably concludes the helper is part of the supported surface. Distinct from a dead-code style nit because the API is `pub` on the public crate boundary, not `pub(crate)` — the regression risk crosses the crate seam, where the workspace's dead-code lint does not fire. Static pass missed it because dead code is by definition unreachable, and `dead_code` does not fire on a `pub` method whose only required reachability is across the crate boundary. The novel-finding heuristic pass missed it because there is no current-call-graph anomaly to anchor on — the hazard is latent and lives in the *gap* between the new invariant and the old API surface. Fix (any one closes the regression surface; recommend 1+2): (1) delete `FindingStore::set_spec` and `FindingStore::set_attack_provenance` outright — they have no callers and the transactional helpers (`HarnessSpecStore::insert_with_finding_spec_link`, `PayloadStore::insert_with_finding_provenance`) supersede them; (2) update the `spec_id` doc at finding.rs:170-176 to remove the 'historical `set_spec`' reference; (3) if deletion is undesirable, mark both with `#[deprecated(note = \"violates provenance ladder; use insert_with_finding_{spec_link,provenance} which COALESCE\")]` AND rewrite their bodies to use the same COALESCE pattern so the ladder holds even on revival; (4) add a doc-test on FindingStore that demonstrates the COALESCE behavior so future contributors who do not read spec.rs's tests still see the invariant.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: add a regression test on `nyctos-core` that constructs a finding, calls `payloads().insert_with_finding_provenance(_, _, \"LlmSynthesised\", \"phase14.payload.v1\")`, then calls `findings().set_attack_provenance(&id, \"ManualPromote\", \"phase99.unverified.v1\")`, and asserts the post-state is *still* `(LlmSynthesised, phase14.payload.v1)`. Currently fails — the helper overwrites unconditionally. Real-world trigger: a future pass that surfaces a quick `set_spec` call to back-link a late-arriving spec to a payload-stamped finding silently downgrades the row's attack_provenance, and the verifier-side UI renders the wrong synthesis attribution."
}

