{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/store/finding.rs",
  "line": 454,
  "cap": "PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "FindingStore::set_verify_result (called once per verifier dispatch from ai_pipeline.rs:2296)",
  "rationale": "Session-0031 documents a provenance ladder (spec.rs:55-66 + ai_pipeline.rs:1072-1086) declaring `findings.attack_provenance` / `findings.prompt_version` are PayloadSynthesis-canonical: the verifier reads the payload (not the spec, not the chain) so the payload-side stamp is the canonical attribution. The COALESCE clauses on the SD writer (spec.rs:89-94) and the no-touch policy on the ChainReasoning writer (apply_chain_outcome:1087 onward) enforce this against future revivals on those two paths. But `FindingStore::set_verify_result` (finding.rs:454-472) is a LIVE writer — `persist_finding_verdict` at ai_pipeline.rs:2271-2299 calls it on EVERY verifier dispatch — and it unconditionally `UPDATE findings SET status = ?, verdict_blob = ?, attack_provenance = ?` (finding.rs:461-464). Three distinct breaks from the ladder drop out:\n\n(a) **silent attack_provenance overwrite on the verifier echo path** — `attack_provenance = result.attack_provenance.as_str()` (ai_pipeline.rs:2293) where `result.attack_provenance` is the verifier's echo of the payload-row's provenance. payload_runner.rs at :529, :556, :601, :636, :684, :716 emits `AttackProvenance::Curated` on multiple fallback branches (no-payload-found, error-path verifier wrap, sandbox-side default-stub paths). When a PayloadSynthesis-stamped row (`LlmSynthesised + phase14.payload.v1`) is verified via any of those fallback shapes, the verifier writes back `Curated`, silently downgrading the PS-canonical stamp. The post-verify `findings` row reports `Curated` even though PS actually ran — defeating the entire reason the ladder doc-comment was added in this session.\n\n(b) **structural desync — prompt_version left stale post-verify** — `set_verify_result` writes `attack_provenance` but NOT `prompt_version` (finding.rs:461-464). After PS+verify the row carries `(attack_provenance: verifier-echoed-value, prompt_version: PS's phase14.payload.v1)` — two columns from two different runs. Steady-state echo (`LlmSynthesised`+`LlmSynthesised`) hides this, but on the (a) fallback path the pair becomes `(Curated, phase14.payload.v1)` — `Curated` provenance can never have come from `phase14.payload.v1` (which is the PS prompt), so the pair is impossible-on-paper but is what the UI / API / forensic export will surface. Operator reading the findings detail view sees `Curated + phase14.payload.v1` and reasonably concludes either the prompt registry was bypassed or the row predates the new ladder — neither is true; the row simply carries a desynced pair the schema does not constrain.\n\n(c) **manual_promote / manual_dismiss precedent compounds the omission** — finding.rs:493-509 (`manual_promote`) and :517 onward (`manual_dismiss`) ALSO overwrite `attack_provenance` unconditionally (to `'ManualPromote'` / `'ManualDismiss'`). These are intentional operator-asserted overrides — they SHOULD overwrite. But that means three live writers on `findings.attack_provenance` (`set_verify_result`, `manual_promote`, `manual_dismiss`) bypass the ladder doc, and the ladder doc-comments make no mention of any of them. Future contributors reading spec.rs:55-66 reasonably conclude the ladder is comprehensive; it is not.\n\nDistinct from finding #27 (which targets the DEAD-CODE `set_spec` / `set_attack_provenance` helpers): #27 is a regression-surface against future revival; this finding is an ACTIVE break on every verifier dispatch in production right now. Static pass missed it because the bug is a *semantic mismatch* between a newly-documented invariant (spec.rs ladder doc-comment) and a long-standing live writer (set_verify_result) — taint analysis has no signal that crosses doc-comment to code-behavior, and there is no tainted-flow sink anywhere; the bug is the absence of COALESCE on a writer the new docs claim is governed by the ladder.\n\nMitigations (any one + (3) closes the primitive):\n  (1) Switch `set_verify_result` to `UPDATE findings SET status = ?, verdict_blob = ?, attack_provenance = COALESCE(attack_provenance, ?) WHERE id = ?` — preserves any PS-canonical stamp when the verifier echo would overwrite with a different value (e.g. Curated fallback).\n  (2) Extend `set_verify_result` to also stamp `prompt_version` from the verifier side (add an explicit `verifier_prompt_version` parameter), so the (attack_provenance, prompt_version) pair stays internally consistent.\n  (3) Update the ladder doc-comment at spec.rs:55-66 to enumerate ALL live writers on `attack_provenance` (PS, SD, ChainReasoning, set_verify_result, manual_promote, manual_dismiss) and document the priority + COALESCE / unconditional-overwrite policy for each. Current narrative omits three of six writers.\n  (4) Add a regression test mirroring the new spec.rs tests: PS stamps LlmSynthesised+phase14.payload.v1, then `set_verify_result` is called with a `Curated`-shaped `VerifyResult` — assert the post-state preserves PS's stamp under COALESCE, or assert the documented overwrite policy if (3) is chosen instead.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: regression test on `nyctos-core` — `s.payloads().insert_with_finding_provenance(&p, &fid, \"LlmSynthesised\", \"phase14.payload.v1\").await?; s.findings().set_verify_result(&fid, \"Verified\", \"{\\\"kind\\\":\\\"VerifyResult\\\",\\\"verdict\\\":\\\"Confirmed\\\"}\", \"Curated\").await?;` then assert `attack_provenance == Some(\"LlmSynthesised\") && prompt_version == Some(\"phase14.payload.v1\")` — currently fails because set_verify_result overwrites attack_provenance to `Curated` while leaving prompt_version stale. Real-world trigger: any verifier dispatch where payload_runner takes a Curated-fallback path (per payload_runner.rs:529/:556/:601/:636/:684/:716) downgrades the row's attack_provenance silently. Adversary angle: same payload_runner Curated paths are easier to force than `LlmSynthesised` (they are the default branches), so a flaky verifier run can systematically scrub LLM attribution off real findings — useful both for an operator looking at attribution metrics (deflated LlmSynthesised count) and for an attacker who poisoned PS to plant a payload they want recorded as Curated."
}

Inventory: 28.

