record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1376,
  "cap": "DOS_AMPLIFICATION",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/{run_id}/findings (Closed-row enumeration loop)",
  "rationale": "The Closed-row branch (router.rs:1376-1387) computes `closed_ids` (the prior_membership keys not in the current rowset, minus those whose prior_status was already Closed) and then loops `for fid in closed_ids { s.store.findings().get(fid).await? }` — one sequential SQLite SELECT per absent finding, awaited inside the request handler. There is no batching (no `WHERE id IN (?, ?, ...)`), no `LIMIT`, no upper bound on `closed_ids.len()`, and the only filter that could prune before the per-id fetch is `prior_status.eq_ignore_ascii_case(\"Closed\")` which excludes ONLY the already-closed prior rows — a prior run with N Open findings, none of which are touched by the current run, produces N sequential round-trips. Three concrete amplifiers: (a) **operator-driven cardinality** — exploration / chain-reasoning / novel-discovery passes routinely emit dozens to hundreds of findings per run on a real codebase; a prior run with 500 Open findings + a current run that discovered a different surface = 500 sequential SELECTs per request; (b) **chronological prior_run_id is global, not per-project** (see finding #29) — the chronologically prior run handed to the classifier may belong to a different project entirely, so the N is bounded by the LARGEST recent run in the entire daemon, not by anything the current request scoped; (c) **bearer-token gate is shared across the daemon** — every authenticated client (CI scripts, the UI, the agent loop, watch-poll loops) can drive the endpoint, and the operator-facing UI typically polls `/runs/{latest}/findings` on a short interval to refresh diff badges. Combined: a single client looping `while true; do curl /api/v1/runs/{X}/findings; done` against a daemon with a 1000-finding prior run produces ~1000 SQLite round-trips per iteration, blocking the request thread on `await?` for the full sequential walk and starving every other API surface that contends for the same SqlitePool (the pool is shared across the router state per `ServerState`). Static pass missed it because the loop body is a single async fetch, the iterator is bounded by a DB-derived collection (not by operator input), and the dataflow rule for `async fn ... await` inside a `for` loop has no signal for N+1 patterns — that's a SemGrep-class rule, not a taint rule. Distinct from generic loop-perf nits because the request handler runs under the API auth surface; bearer-gated DoS is still DoS if the authorised clients include CI / agent-loop / UI poll cadence that adversarial control or just buggy retry-on-timeout traffic can amplify. Fix (any one closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) replace the per-id loop with a single batched fetch — add `FindingStore::list_by_ids(ids: &[&str]) -> Vec<FindingRecord>` that runs one `WHERE id IN (...)` SELECT (sqlx supports `QueryBuilder::push_bind_unseparated` for IN clauses), then filter in-memory with `row_passes_filter`; (2) cap `closed_ids.len()` to a hard maximum (e.g. 200) and surface a `closed_truncated: bool` flag in `RunFindingsResponse` so the UI can fetch additional pages; (3) compose the Closed branch as a single SQL: `SELECT f.* FROM findings f JOIN run_findings rf ON rf.finding_id = f.id WHERE rf.run_id = ? AND rf.status != 'Closed' AND f.id NOT IN (SELECT finding_id FROM run_findings WHERE run_id = ?)` — one round-trip end-to-end, repo-scopable via an additional `AND f.repo = ?` clause that also closes finding #29; (4) add a unit test that asserts the request handler issues O(1) (not O(N)) DB calls for the Closed path on a 1000-finding prior run — `s.store.findings().query_count()` instrumentation or a query log decoder around `SqlitePool::acquire`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Seed a prior run with 1000 distinct findings via a loop: `for i in 0..1000 { let mut f = sample_finding(\"run-prior\", \"repo-x\", &format!(\"src/{}.rs\", i), &format!(\"rule-{}\", i)); s.store.findings().upsert(&f).await.unwrap(); }`. Insert a `run-current` row with no findings. Time `GET /api/v1/runs/run-current/findings` — expect ~1000x the latency of the single-finding case (each request issues N SELECTs sequentially). Verifier-side regression: stand up the existing TestServer, instrument the SqlitePool with a query counter (sqlx `Pool::size` is not sufficient; use `sqlx_core::pool::PoolOptions::connect_with` and wrap with a counting layer, or just instrument `FindingStore::get` to bump an atomic), seed 100 prior-only findings, hit the endpoint, assert counter <= 5 (one for runs.get, one for prior_run_id, one for list_filtered, one for list_run_membership, one for the batched Closed fetch — NOT 100+). Real-world trigger: a UI poll loop or an agent-loop's diff-watcher hitting a daemon where the recent runs span large codebases monopolises the SqlitePool for several seconds per request."
}

