record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1328,
  "cap": "DETECTION_BLINDSPOT",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/{run_id}/findings (current-row selection)",
  "rationale": "`findings_for_run` selects the current-row set with `FindingFilter { run_id: Some(&run_id), .. }` against `FindingStore::list_filtered` (router.rs:1328) — a filter that joins `findings.run_id == ?`. `findings.run_id` is the COLLAPSED column: `FindingStore::upsert`'s `ON CONFLICT(id) DO UPDATE SET run_id = excluded.run_id` (finding.rs:198-211) overwrites it on every re-observation, so only ONE run at a time owns any given finding-id in the `findings` table. The new `run_findings` join table records the per-run snapshot — but the current-row reader does NOT consult it. Result: a finding observed during run X AND re-observed during a later run Y is invisible to `GET /runs/X/findings` even though `run_findings(X, fid)` exists and faithfully records X's observation. Three concrete consequences drop out:\n\n(a) **historical run views are incomplete** — an operator clicking 'view run X' in the UI sees a strict subset of what X actually observed; the missing rows are precisely those most likely to be regressions or chronic findings (re-observed in later runs). The UI's run-detail page surfaces a finding count that mismatches the run's `findings_count` summary stat (which is typically computed at scan-end from a different code path that does count all observations).\n\n(b) **diff classifier degrades to one-sided** — the new diff classifier compares 'current_rows (from collapsed findings)' against 'prior_membership (from run_findings)'. A finding observed in BOTH X and the prior of X is correctly identified as Unchanged when X is the latest run that observed it (collapsed findings.run_id == X), but is INVISIBLE entirely once any later run observes it — even though semantically it's still part of X's history. The classifier never reports a `New`/`Unchanged`/`Regressed` chip for the finding under X; the finding simply disappears from the response.\n\n(c) **migration backfill compounds the asymmetry** — the migration seeds one `run_findings` row per finding at the LATEST run_id (`INSERT INTO run_findings SELECT run_id, id, status FROM findings`, migration 0004:37-38). Older runs that observed the same finding-id get no backfilled row. So even the new join table can only ever report 'one canonical run per finding-id' until the system has had time to accumulate post-migration upserts. The very test `list_run_membership_scopes_to_run_id` (finding.rs:973-993) demonstrates the intended behavior (multi-run snapshots) but exercises ONLY freshly-inserted findings — never the backfilled hole.\n\n(d) **defender uses the endpoint as a detection surface** — the wallpapered semantics ('this is the list of findings observed in run X') is the natural defender contract; an attacker who wants to evade detection of a finding F under run X just needs to trigger ANY subsequent run that re-observes F (e.g. via a CI-triggered scan, or via a publicly-exposed webhook that auto-scans on push). The re-observation collapses findings.run_id off X; X's findings response no longer surfaces F. Even though run_findings(X, F) still records the original observation, no API endpoint surfaces it. Compounds with finding #31 (the diff classifier reads collapsed findings.status, so even when F IS visible the comparison is wrong) and finding #29 (Closed rows leak across repos).\n\nDistinct from finding #29 (which is about the Closed-injection branch leaking cross-repo rows IN) and finding #31 (which is about the Unchanged/Regressed comparison being against wrong column). #32 is about the CURRENT-row enumeration itself being structurally incomplete — every other finding on the run_findings path is downstream of this gap. Static pass missed it because the bug is a *structural omission* — the new join table exists, the writer writes it, the prior-run reader reads it, but the current-run reader was left on the legacy `findings.run_id` filter. The diff is HALF-WIRED. A taint rule has no signal for 'newly-introduced index/table that should have been consulted at a sibling code path'; this is a schema-evolution review-class catch. Fix (any one closes the primitive; recommend 1+4): (1) rewrite `list_filtered` (or add a parallel `list_for_run`) to join `run_findings` rather than filter on `findings.run_id`: `SELECT f.* FROM findings f JOIN run_findings rf ON rf.finding_id = f.id WHERE rf.run_id = ? AND ...other facets...` — source-of-truth becomes the per-run snapshot; (2) at minimum, in `findings_for_run`, after fetching `current_rows`, also fetch `list_run_membership(&run_id)` and union in any finding-ids in the membership set that the collapsed query missed (`for (fid, status) in current_membership { if !current_ids.contains(fid) { let row = findings.get(fid)?; ... } }`) — same N+1 hazard as the Closed branch but now spread across two loops; (3) deprecate `findings.run_id` as a meaningful column entirely (rename to `latest_observed_run_id` and update the doc-comment at finding.rs to mark it as a denormalised cache, never the primary key for per-run views); (4) add a regression test that exercises the missing case: seed run-A with F=Open, run-B with F=Open, then issue `GET /runs/run-A/findings` and assert items.len() == 1 and items[0].id matches F — currently fails (items.len() == 0) because findings.run_id was collapsed to run-B.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: regression test on `nyctos-api/tests/api.rs` — seed two runs (run-old started_at=1000, run-new started_at=5000); upsert ONE finding under each run with the SAME (repo, path, rule) so the id collides; `GET /api/v1/runs/run-old/findings`; assert items.len() == 1 (the finding observed under run-old, surfaced via run_findings join). Currently fails — items is empty because `FindingFilter { run_id: \"run-old\" }` reads collapsed `findings.run_id` which is now \"run-new\". Real-world trigger: any nightly cron that re-scans the same repo nightly silently disappears every prior-night's finding from that night's run view; the operator-side 'compare last night vs tonight' workflow loses its anchor, and the diff classifier built on top of this gap silently mislabels findings that should be Unchanged as effectively missing."
}

