  abort-self escape regression). All 35 prior findings re-confirmed
  against HEAD; no line shifts in nyctos-api / nyctos-core / nyctos
  trees. Four new findings appended below, all on the new sandbox
  status-pipe surface: #36 SANDBOX_FORGERY (config-gated close(3)
  in sandboxee pre_exec leaves the forge primitive reachable from
  any misconfigured caller); #37 CONFUSED_DEPUTY (write_status_frame_to_fd3
  trusts fd 3 is the pipe without fstat S_ISFIFO validation, lets
  operator-side shell redirects pollute unrelated files); #38
  SIGPIPE_AUDIT_LOSS (shim's write_all to a half-closed pipe is
  killed by SIGPIPE → parent misreports Signaled(SIGPIPE) for a
  clean-exit sandboxee); #39 AUDIT_LOG_INTEGRITY (partial / forged /
  truncated frame is swallowed by `.ok()?` with no warn, indistinguishable
  from "no pipe wired"). Total: 39 findings.

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/bin/nyx_sandbox_shim.rs",
  "line": 86,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_FORGERY",
  "endpoint": "shim sandboxee pre_exec (close fd 3 gated on cfg.write_status_fd)",
  "rationale": "The sandboxee's pre_exec close(3) at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:86 is gated on `close_status_fd = cfg.write_status_fd` (captured at :80 into the move closure). The flag defaults to `false` via `#[serde(default)]` on shim.rs:30. The parent BirdcageSandbox::run hardcodes `write_status_fd: true` (birdcage.rs:110) AND installs the dup2-write-end-onto-fd-3 pre_exec (birdcage.rs:144-161) which deliberately leaves fd 3 *without* FD_CLOEXEC (the comment at birdcage.rs:146-149 documents: 'dup2 clears CLOEXEC on the new fd ... we leave it that way so the shim retains fd 3 through its lifetime'). The two safety properties are wired to *independent* knobs: pipe-on-fd-3 lives in caller code (the dup2 pre_exec), and sandboxee-close-fd-3 lives in shim cfg (the write_status_fd JSON field). The security invariant the shim relies on for forge-prevention — 'sandboxee cannot write to fd 3' — holds today only because the in-tree caller happens to set BOTH knobs the same way. Three orthogonal failure modes flow from the gating:\n\n(a) **out-of-tree direct caller of nyx-sandbox-shim**: the shim is an installed binary (resolved via SHIM_PATH_ENV or alongside current_exe at birdcage.rs:237-251), invocable independently. An operator running it for triage/debugging (`nyx-sandbox-shim <cfg.json` with a JSON omitting write_status_fd) gets `write_status_fd = false` from the serde default. If that operator wraps the call in a shell redirect that happens to put a writable fd at slot 3 (e.g. `nyx-sandbox-shim 3>>audit.log <cfg.json` — a plausible structure if the operator was attempting to capture the status frame manually) the sandboxee inherits fd 3 (no close runs because write_status_fd=false). The sandboxee then has arbitrary append access to audit.log, with no birdcage write exception covering audit.log. Fd-inheritance escape past the filesystem allowlist.\n\n(b) **future second backend wiring a status pipe**: process.rs:188-198 stamps `status_fd: None` for ProcessSandbox; firecracker.rs:213 and libkrun.rs:191 likewise. A future contributor adding a third backend that allocates a pipe-on-fd-3 may forget to also flip write_status_fd in the cfg (the two-knob design hides this footgun — the JSON field is named for the *shim-side write* behaviour, not the *sandboxee-side close* behaviour, so a reader thinks 'I'm not writing, no need to set it' and the sandboxee close silently disappears). Forge primitive immediately reachable.\n\n(c) **partial-fix caller toggling write_status_fd: false to suppress the shim's frame write but keeping the pipe wired**: someone deciding 'I want the parent to use the 128+signum convention as before, but I still need fd 3 for X' (where X is some operator-side instrumentation) ends up with sandboxee-can-write + parent-reads-via-read_status_fd_path-or-not. Even if the parent ignores fd 3, the sandboxee write-through is now arbitrary append to whatever the parent wired (defeats the filesystem allowlist).\n\nThe forge target itself: a sandboxee with fd 3 = pipe write end can `write(3, '{\"kind\":\"Exited\",\"value\":0}', 27)` and the parent's `read_status_fd` (process.rs:154-171) deserialises that as truth via `serde_json::from_slice` (process.rs:166), then unconditionally overrides `classify(status)` at process.rs:142 with the forged variant. Net effect: a sandboxee that died from SIGSEGV (e.g. an exploit attempt that overran a buffer in birdcage's filter layer) reports `SandboxStatus::Exited(0)` to the daemon's audit pipeline. The escape-attempt regression suite at escape.rs:233-261 tests the *positive* path (abort produces Signaled(6)) but does not test that a *forged* frame from a malicious sandboxee is rejected — the test sandboxee runs `std::process::abort()` and trusts the shim to honestly report; a sandboxee that opened fd 3 itself and wrote a clean Exited(0) frame BEFORE aborting would pass the test framework's assertion as `Signaled(6)` ONLY because shim's own write runs after wait and the parent gets two concatenated JSON objects which serde_json::from_slice rejects → fallback to classify → 128+6=134 → Exited(134) — not the asserted Signaled(6). The very regression test the new code adds would FAIL if the close(3) gate were tripped off, exposing the forge path to detection only via test regression, not via runtime defense.\n\nCompounding: birdcage.rs:146-149 explicitly clears CLOEXEC on fd 3 in the shim, justified by 'so it survives the shim's own exec from the fork'. But the shim never re-execs after stdin parse — the only exec from the shim is the sandboxee's exec via `Birdcage::spawn(cmd)` at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:140, which is exactly the place where fd 3 must NOT survive. The CLOEXEC-clear keeps fd 3 alive through the shim's own (rust binary) startup, but it then needs explicit close in the sandboxee pre_exec — which is the gated path. A simpler design would set FD_CLOEXEC on fd 3 in the shim's main fn before any spawn (after parsing cfg and before writing the frame, since the frame write at :208 uses the still-open fd in the shim's own fd table) — that flips the default from 'inherited unless closed' to 'closed unless explicitly preserved'.\n\nStatic pass missed it because the bug is a *coupling-between-flags* class: each flag's behaviour is correct in isolation; the bug is the absence of an invariant that ties them together. Taint analysis has no signal for 'this two-flag combination must be enforced as one'. Sandbox-design review-class catch. Fix (any one + (4) closes the primitive; recommend 1+4): (1) drop the `close_status_fd` gate at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:86-89 — unconditionally `libc::close(3)` in sandboxee pre_exec; the existing comment at :87-88 already accepts EBADF as a no-op so the call is safe when no pipe is wired. (2) in `main()` of nyx_sandbox_shim.rs (around line 45 where setsid is called), unconditionally `libc::fcntl(3, F_SETFD, FD_CLOEXEC)` after stdin parse — sandboxee's eventual exec then drops fd 3 by default and the explicit close becomes redundant defense. (3) remove the `write_status_fd` field from `ShimConfig` entirely — derive 'shim should write a frame' from 'fd 3 is a pipe' via `fstat(3, &stat)` + `S_ISFIFO(stat.st_mode)` at the call site, so the contract is implicit-on-actual-fd-shape rather than caller-trusted-self-report. (4) add a regression test: write a custom escape-attempt subcommand `forge-status-frame` that does `let raw_pipe = libc::open(\\\"/dev/null\\\", O_WRONLY)` (returns 3 if fd 3 was inherited — captures forge primitive) and asserts the sandbox harness rejects forged frames; pair with a test that *removes* `write_status_fd: true` from the shim cfg constructed by BirdcageSandbox::run (mock variant) and asserts the sandboxee CANNOT write to fd 3 — currently fails as documented above.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Black-box regression seed (add to tests/escape.rs): introduce a new escape-attempt subcommand `forge-status` in src/bin/escape_attempt.rs that does `unsafe { let path = std::ffi::CString::new(\\\"/dev/null\\\").unwrap(); let fd = libc::open(path.as_ptr(), libc::O_WRONLY); if fd == 3 { let frame = b\\\"{\\\\\\\"kind\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Exited\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"value\\\\\\\":0}\\\"; libc::write(3, frame.as_ptr() as *const _, frame.len()); } std::process::abort() }`. Then write a test variant that constructs a ShimConfig with `write_status_fd: false` directly (bypassing BirdcageSandbox::run's hardcoded `true`) and dispatches the shim; assert `SandboxStatus::Signaled(SIGABRT)` (not Exited(0)). Today the test passes only because the in-tree caller sets the flag — the forge primitive itself is alive in the shim binary. Alternative black-box: `nyx-sandbox-shim 3>/tmp/audit.log <(echo '{...write_status_fd omitted...}')` — observe /tmp/audit.log gets a sandboxee-controlled frame appended."
}

