record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/bin/nyx_sandbox_shim.rs",
  "line": 208,
  "cap": "CONFUSED_DEPUTY",
  "endpoint": "nyx-sandbox-shim (operator-invokable installed binary; status frame writer)",
  "rationale": "`write_status_frame_to_fd3` at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:188-211 does `let mut file = unsafe { std::fs::File::from_raw_fd(3) }; let _ = file.write_all(&json);` unconditionally trusting that fd 3 is the pipe write end the parent dup2'd. The shim has no validation — no `fstat(3, &stat)` to check `S_ISFIFO(stat.st_mode)`, no kernel-side or filesystem-side handshake to confirm 'fd 3 is actually the pipe BirdcageSandbox opened in this process's parent'. The trust chain is purely caller-controlled: parent sets `write_status_fd: true` in cfg JSON → shim believes the parent also wired a pipe on fd 3 → shim writes JSON into whatever fd 3 happens to be.\n\nThe shim binary is installed (operator-invokable via SHIM_PATH_ENV or `nyx-sandbox-shim` on PATH; see birdcage.rs:237-251 for resolution semantics; the binary is shipped alongside the daemon and is a stable name that ends up on $PATH for operator triage). Three concrete misdirection vectors:\n\n(a) **shell redirect at operator invocation**: an operator running `nyx-sandbox-shim 3>>/var/log/nyctos-shim.log <cfg.json` (a plausible triage incantation if they were trying to capture the status frame manually for debugging) gets the JSON frame appended to /var/log/nyctos-shim.log — log injection. If `/var/log/nyctos-shim.log` is consumed by an external log shipper / SIEM that parses JSON-lines, the shim's frame becomes a synthetic log record from no apparent source. Inverse: `nyx-sandbox-shim 3>>/etc/cron.d/something <cfg.json` — the frame `{\\\"kind\\\":\\\"Exited\\\",\\\"value\\\":0}` is appended to a cron file; cron parses it as a malformed entry, may skip the file or alert. Mostly availability, but the operator's mental model is 'this binary reads stdin and writes stdout/stderr' — fd 3 as a side channel is undocumented in --help.\n\n(b) **fd 3 inherited from an ancestor process**: any ancestor process (the daemon's parent shell, systemd, launchctl) that happens to leave fd 3 open without CLOEXEC propagates it through `tokio::process::Command::spawn` (which only sets up stdin/stdout/stderr; fd 3+ inherit by default unless the parent's pre_exec closes them). If the daemon was launched via `nyctos &3>&1` or similar, fd 3 in the daemon = stdout; the daemon then dup2s the pipe write end onto fd 3 in the shim's pre_exec (overriding stdout)? No — the dup2 is in the SHIM's fd table, not the daemon's, so the daemon's stdout is unaffected. But: if the daemon ITSELF has fd 3 open to something sensitive (e.g. a credentials socket inherited from systemd's socket activation), the pipe pre_exec dup2 in the shim's fd table replaces fd 3 cleanly; the issue is only for the *out-of-tree direct caller* case where the dup2 isn't installed.\n\n(c) **shim's File::from_raw_fd(3) drops at end-of-fn → close(3) in shim's fd table**: the comment at :210 says 'file dropped here -> close(3) -> parent's read end EOFs'. Correct when fd 3 is the pipe. When fd 3 is anything else (per (a) or (b) above), the drop closes that other fd, which may disrupt the rest of the shim's lifetime — but the shim is about to exit after the function returns, so this is benign for the shim. Less benign: any operator-side instrumentation that relied on fd 3 being open at shim exit (e.g. `LD_PRELOAD` hook with an fd 3 pipe to a trace consumer) gets EOF mid-trace.\n\nThe operator-triage scenario is the most realistic exposure: the shim is a debugging tool the operator runs to validate sandbox config, and the shell redirect `3>file` is a common pattern when the operator was told 'fd 3 carries the status frame'. The fix is two-line: fstat fd 3 and bail if it's not a fifo. Static pass missed it because the bug is the *absence* of an `fstat`/`S_ISFIFO` validation in safety-critical FFI code; taint analysis sees the unsafe block but has no signal for 'this raw_fd should be a pipe and the code does not check'. Sandbox-design review-class catch.\n\nDistinct from #36: that finding is about the sandboxee-side forge primitive when the close gate is off. This finding is about the shim-side write target when the dup2 is off — symmetric attack surface, different attacker (shim binary's operator-invoker vs sandboxee).\n\nFix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) in `write_status_frame_to_fd3`, prepend `unsafe { let mut stat: libc::stat = std::mem::zeroed(); if libc::fstat(3, &mut stat) != 0 { return; } if (stat.st_mode & libc::S_IFMT) != libc::S_IFIFO { return; } }` — silently bails when fd 3 is not a pipe. (2) better: pass the fd number via env var `NYX_SHIM_STATUS_FD` (parent sets it before spawn; shim reads it in main; absence = no frame to write); makes the contract explicit and removes the magic-number 3. (3) document the contract in shim.rs:23-31's doc-comment that the shim WILL write to fd 3 unconditionally when write_status_fd=true, regardless of what fd 3 is — operators reading the field name today reasonably assume 'the parent allocated a pipe, the shim writes to it, end of story'; the actual contract is weaker and footgun-shaped. (4) regression test: invoke `nyx-sandbox-shim 3>/tmp/forge.bin <cfg-with-write_status_fd-true.json` with a sandboxee that exits cleanly; assert /tmp/forge.bin remains empty (i.e. shim DID NOT write); today the file contains the JSON frame.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Operator-reproduction recipe: `mkdir -p /tmp/forge && nyx-sandbox-shim 3>/tmp/forge/out.bin <<EOF\\n{\\\"program\\\":\\\"/bin/true\\\",\\\"args\\\":[],\\\"cwd\\\":\\\"/tmp\\\",\\\"env\\\":[],\\\"allow_read\\\":[],\\\"allow_write\\\":[],\\\"allow_env\\\":[],\\\"allow_network\\\":false,\\\"write_status_fd\\\":true}\\nEOF\\n# observe `cat /tmp/forge/out.bin` is `{\\\"kind\\\":\\\"Exited\\\",\\\"value\\\":0}` (29 bytes). Validates the shim trusts fd 3 = pipe without checking. Regression test that exposes the issue: in tests/escape.rs add `async fn shim_does_not_write_frame_to_regular_file()` that spawns nyx-sandbox-shim with stdin = cfg JSON and fd 3 pointing to `tempfile()` via `unsafe { libc::dup2(file.as_raw_fd(), 3) }` in a `pre_exec` on the cmd; assert the tempfile is empty after the shim exits — currently fails (frame is written)."
}

