record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/process.rs",
  "line": 166,
  "cap": "AUDIT_LOG_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "read_status_fd parser (out-of-band status frame; only sink for sandbox audit category)",
  "rationale": "`read_status_fd` (process.rs:154-171) consumes the pipe with `file.read_to_end(&mut buf).ok()?` (:162) then `serde_json::from_slice(&buf).ok()?` (:166), with the outer call site `.unwrap_or_else(|| classify(status))` at process.rs:142. The four possible read+parse outcomes collapse into TWO observable states from the caller's POV:\n\n  read_ok + parse_ok    → return Some(forged-or-real status)\n  read_ok + buf_empty   → return None → fallback to classify(shim ExitStatus)\n  read_ok + parse_err   → return None → fallback to classify(shim ExitStatus)\n  read_err              → return None → fallback to classify(shim ExitStatus)\n\nThree of the four outcomes are indistinguishable downstream: 'no pipe wired' (None expected and benign), 'pipe wired but read interrupted by EIO/EBADF/ENOMEM' (tampering or kernel issue), and 'pipe wired and bytes arrived but JSON didn't parse' (partial write / sandboxee-forge attempt that wrote garbage / shim killed mid-write / forging sandboxee wrote a frame and then the shim wrote its real frame, producing two concatenated JSON objects which serde_json::from_slice rejects with 'trailing characters' Err). All three reach `classify(status)` with no warn-log, no metric, no audit trail.\n\nFour failure modes flow from this:\n\n(a) **forge-detection silence**: a sandboxee that forged a partial frame (per #36's mechanism, when the close gate is off) produces 'read_ok + parse_err' since the shim's write appends a second JSON object after the sandboxee's. The parent silently falls back to classify, which for a Birdcage-via-shim path encodes signal status as Exited(128+signum). Audit log records Exited(134) instead of Signaled(6); operator triage cannot tell 'this sandboxee tried to forge its exit' apart from 'this sandboxee exited cleanly with code 134'. The very security-relevant signal (forge attempt detected) is dropped on the floor.\n\n(b) **transient-corruption indistinguishable from missing-pipe**: any disk/memory pressure that causes read_to_end to error returns Err which `.ok()?` swallows. The parent has no signal that the audit channel failed; the fallback path produces a status that may be plausibly wrong by one category (Signaled vs Exited), and the operator's runbook for 'unexpected Exited(134)' has no entry pointing at 'status pipe was corrupted, real signal was different'.\n\n(c) **regression test masks the issue**: `abort_sandboxee_surfaces_signaled_through_shim` (escape.rs:233-261) panics with the expected/actual mismatch on a clean test environment. But the test does not assert 'parse path was exercised'; if a future change broke the parse and the fallback happened to produce Signaled(6) anyway (e.g. someone changed exit_code_from at :169-179 to preserve signal info), the test would pass while the entire status-pipe path was bypassed. The test confirms end-to-end behaviour, not which code path produced it. **A second assertion is needed**: an instrumentation point (counter, debug log, return-value channel) in read_status_fd that the test inspects, to confirm the parse path actually ran for this sandboxee.\n\n(d) **inconsistency with classify's signed-vs-unsigned semantics**: classify on Birdcage path can produce Exited(128+sig) — but classify is called on the SHIM's ExitStatus, and the shim's exit_code_from at :171-176 clamps `raw as u8` with min(127) on the signum. So classify(shim_exit_status) on a SIGABRT-killed sandboxee → shim exits with code 134 → ExitStatus.code() = Some(134) → ExitStatus.signal() = None → classify returns SandboxStatus::Exited(134). That's the lossy encoding the entire status-pipe design exists to fix. When parse fails, the lossiness reappears AND the audit log doesn't say 'parse failed, fallback engaged'. Effectively the new feature's reliability is invisible — operators cannot tell if the fix is working without manual SQL inspection of the audit blob and cross-referencing with the shim's stderr (which the parent does capture, but doesn't correlate).\n\n**Fix (1+2 recommended)**: (1) split the fallback paths in read_status_fd: log at warn level when `buf.is_empty()` AND there was an OwnedFd (i.e. pipe was wired but no bytes arrived — indicates shim crashed before write or parent closed read end mid-life), and log at error level when parse failed on non-empty buf (indicates forge attempt or partial write). Both events go to tracing::warn!/error! with the buf prefix (first 64 bytes hex-encoded for forensic visibility); the parent's caller can then forward to its existing log sink. (2) add an observability counter (or a field on SandboxOutcome — e.g. `status_source: enum { OutOfBand, Fallback, KilledByOperator, Timeout }`) that the daemon can surface in metrics. (3) reject the parse on first sign of trailing bytes: serde_json::from_slice already does this — so the forge-then-real-frame case IS parse_err today; the gap is the silence, not the detection. (4) for the regression test: add a `status_pipe_used` test-only flag the read_status_fd sets, so `abort_sandboxee_surfaces_signaled_through_shim` can assert both `outcome.status == Signaled(6)` AND `status_pipe_used == true` — distinguishes 'feature worked' from 'fallback happened to coincide'.\n\nStatic pass missed it because the bug is the absence of logging on a fallback path — taint analysis has no signal for 'this Option-chained discard should be a noisy error'. Audit-design review-class catch.\n\nDistinct from #38 (the parent-side SIGPIPE that causes write to die — that finding is about *availability* of the channel; this finding is about *silence* when the channel fails). Both share the underlying property that the new out-of-band status frame is a fragile single-shot with no observability.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (extend escape.rs): add `async fn parse_error_in_status_pipe_does_not_silently_misreport()`. Spawn a sandboxee via a modified shim binary (test-only build flag) that writes `b\\\"INVALID-JSON-BYTES\\\"` to fd 3 instead of a real frame, then exits with code 7. Assert `outcome.status == SandboxStatus::Exited(7)` (the fallback's correct answer for non-signal exit) AND assert a warning was logged matching `'status frame parse failed'`. Currently the second assertion fails (no log). Real-world repro: `RUST_LOG=nyctos_sandbox=debug` during any normal run, observe NO log entry distinguishing 'status pipe used' from 'status pipe fallback' — the path is completely opaque to operator instrumentation. Compound with #36's forge seed: inject a forged frame, then assert that the shim's stderr (captured in SandboxOutcome.stderr) AND the parent's tracing output BOTH carry a forge-detection event; today neither does."
}

