record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/process.rs",
  "line": 152,
  "cap": "RESOURCE_EXHAUSTION",
  "endpoint": "read_report_fd (parent-side status+refusals reader; only sink for the new ShimReport envelope)",
  "rationale": "`read_report_fd` (process.rs:139-181 in the uncommitted diff) consumes the pipe with `file.read_to_end(&mut buf)` (process.rs:152) with NO size cap, NO max_output_bytes, and NO timeout. The buffer starts with `Vec::with_capacity(128)` but `read_to_end` grows it without bound: the only termination condition is EOF on the pipe. The wire schema is `ShimReport { status: ShimStatus, refusals: Vec<String> }` (shim.rs:60-63) — `refusals` is an unconstrained `Vec<String>` over the JSON wire format.\n\nThree compounding hazards make this an unbounded-RAM primitive for the daemon process:\n\n(a) **chain with #36's forge primitive**: when `write_status_fd` is true (the in-tree BirdcageSandbox default at birdcage.rs:110) the sandboxee's pre_exec close(3) runs and forge is gated off. But #36 documents that the gate is independently controlled from the parent's dup2-onto-fd-3, and any out-of-tree caller (or future second backend that wires a pipe but forgets to flip write_status_fd) leaves fd 3 open in the sandboxee. A sandboxee with write access to fd 3 can `write(3, ...)` a multi-gigabyte JSON object — e.g. one refusal string of N gigabytes — and then exit. The shim is unaware (its own write happens after the sandboxee exits via `child.wait()` at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:147; the sandboxee's bytes are already in the kernel's pipe buffer waiting to be drained). Parent's `read_to_end` after `child.wait().await` drains the pipe into a Vec<u8> in the daemon's process — the daemon OOMs or hits its cgroup memory limit and gets killed by the kernel OOM-killer.\n\n(b) **even WITHOUT forge access, a misconfigured shim is unbounded**: the shim's own write at write_report_to_fd3 (nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:188-210 in the diff) serializes `refusals: refusals.to_vec()` (:201) where `refused` is built from `cfg.allow_read.len() + cfg.allow_write.len() + cfg.allow_env.len() + 1` candidate exceptions (nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:108-128). A caller that allocates 10^7 allow_read paths produces 10^7 refusal lines, each up to PATH_MAX bytes + ExecuteAndRead overhead. The shim itself materialises that Vec<String> (also bad — DoS-on-shim) but the parent's read_to_end then doubles the RAM footprint into the daemon. The Birdcage backend has no allowance-count validation at SandboxOpts ingestion (search confirms: SandboxOpts at lib.rs has no len-cap on allow_read/allow_write).\n\n(c) **read_to_end on a Unix pipe blocks until EOF; the parent's read happens on a tokio runtime thread under await of the synchronous std::fs::File**: process.rs:152's `file.read_to_end(&mut buf)` is std::io::Read, not tokio::io::AsyncRead, executed inside an async fn that has already awaited `child.wait()`. While drive_to_completion is `async`, the read itself is BLOCKING — it occupies a tokio worker thread until the pipe EOFs. If the pipe never EOFs (per finding #42 fd-leak hang) AND the buf grows without bound until the daemon's process memory is exhausted, the daemon is killed; if it EOFs in finite time but the buf is huge, the daemon goes near-OOM and may swap-thrash. Either way the daemon is unresponsive for the duration of the read.\n\n**Net effect**: chain with #36 → an in-band exit-status forge becomes an out-of-band daemon OOM kill, escalating a forge primitive (audit confidentiality / integrity) into a DoS primitive (audit availability) against the whole nyctos process. The chain is not theoretical: the sandboxee-side write surface and the parent-side read surface meet at the same fd, and neither side caps bytes.\n\nStatic pass missed it because (i) `read_to_end` is a stdlib call without an associated lint for size caps, and the call site has no obvious user-input source — taint analysis on the path 'sandboxee fd 3 → kernel pipe buffer → parent read_to_end' is below tainted-flow tools' coverage of inter-process channels; (ii) the danger is the absence of a cap, not the presence of a sink; (iii) the chain with #36 requires cross-finding reasoning (forge primitive enables RAM blowup) that taint analysis does not perform.\n\n**Fix (1+2 recommended)**: (1) replace `read_to_end` with a bounded read: `let mut buf = vec![0u8; 64 * 1024]; let n = file.read(&mut buf)?; buf.truncate(n);` — refuse to parse and log warn if read fills the buffer (indicates either a runaway shim or a forge; ShimReport's legitimate envelope is <2KB for any realistic config). The Vec<String> refusals serialised as JSON for the in-tree max-config case is ~16KB; 64KB is comfortably 4x slack. (2) cap `refusals.len()` at 256 in ShimReport's serde deserialiser via `#[serde(deserialize_with = \"deserialize_capped_string_vec\")]` (custom deserializer that bails on len > 256) — covers the deserializer-side defense even if the read cap is lifted later. (3) at the source: validate `opts.allow_read.len() + opts.allow_write.len() + opts.allow_env.len() <= 1024` in SandboxOpts validation (lib.rs SandboxOpts builder), rejecting at the caller boundary. (4) for symmetry, similar caps on stdout/stderr already exist via opts.max_output_bytes (process.rs:118 — `read_capped`); apply the same shape to the status pipe.\n\nDistinct from #38 (SIGPIPE on the write side — that finding is the shim crashing mid-write) and #39 (silent fallback in the parser — that finding is detection silence). This finding is about *bytes-on-the-wire* exhaustion of the daemon's memory; the channel is reliable and observable, but the volume is unbounded.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Repro (requires the forge gate from #36 to be off, OR a misconfigured backend that wires fd 3 but sets write_status_fd:false): a sandboxee that does `let fd = unsafe { libc::open(\\\"/dev/null\\\", libc::O_WRONLY) }; if fd == 3 { /* fd 3 inherited - forge is live */ let blob = serde_json::to_vec(&ShimReport { status: ShimStatus::Exited(0), refusals: vec![\\\"X\\\".repeat(1 << 30); 4] }).unwrap(); libc::write(3, blob.as_ptr().cast(), blob.len()); } std::process::exit(0);` — 4 GB JSON over the pipe forces the daemon to allocate ~4 GB in `read_report_fd`'s Vec<u8>. Observability check: `ps -o rss= -p $(pgrep -f nyctos-daemon)` during the run jumps from baseline (~50MB) to multi-GB just before the sandbox outcome returns. Counter-test for the in-tree path: change BirdcageSandbox::run to set `write_status_fd: false` while keeping the dup2-pre_exec wired (one-line patch at birdcage.rs:110), rebuild the workspace, and run the existing escape suite's `abort_sandboxee_surfaces_signaled_through_shim` with a sandboxee that writes a 100 MB blob to fd 3 in `main()` before aborting — assert daemon RSS does not grow by 100MB."
}

