record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/shim.rs",
  "line": 60,
  "cap": "LOG_INJECTION",
  "endpoint": "ShimReport.refusals wire field → SandboxOutcome.refusals → operator UI/CLI/log surfaces",
  "rationale": "`ShimReport.refusals: Vec<String>` (shim.rs:60-63) is an unconstrained UTF-8 string list deserialised straight off the fd-3 pipe and stamped into `SandboxOutcome.refusals` (process.rs:181) which is publicly readable on every sandbox outcome (lib.rs:342-348 — the field's doc-comment frames it as `human-readable description` intended for the operator). The string content is constructed shim-side at nyx_sandbox_shim.rs:111-127 via `format!(\\\"ExecuteAndRead({}): {e}\\\", p.display())` etc. — the format embeds the **path** (`p`) and the **birdcage error** (`e`) verbatim with no sanitisation. Both fields are operator-controlled today but the threat model widens once #36's forge primitive is reachable: a sandboxee writing a synthetic ShimReport can set `refusals` to ANY UTF-8 (or invalid UTF-8 if the parent's serde_json doesn't validate — confirmed: serde_json::from_slice on a Vec<String> only requires valid UTF-8, but does not reject control chars).\n\nThree concrete injection surfaces flow from this:\n\n(a) **terminal-control-sequence injection into operator CLI**: nyctos ships an operator CLI (the `nyctos` binary in this crate) that displays scan outcomes. If the CLI ever surfaces SandboxOutcome.refusals to stderr/stdout (a natural triage feature: 'this sandbox declared 3 exceptions but birdcage refused 1 — here's the line'), a refusal string containing `\\x1b[2J\\x1b[Hpwned\\x1b[31m` clears the operator's terminal, repositions the cursor, and writes attacker-chosen red text. On terminals that honour OSC 8 hyperlinks, refusal strings can render as clickable links that resolve to attacker URLs. Operator-trust attack: the refusal text appears below the sandboxed run summary and the operator reads it as 'system diagnostics', not as 'sandboxee output' — the CLI's mental model is that fd-3 ShimReport content is SHIM-AUTHORED, not sandboxee-authored.\n\n(b) **HTML/JS injection into operator web UI**: nyctos has a daemon HTTP API (router.rs) that serves outcome data to the React UI (nyctos-ui crate, present in workspace). If any UI view ever renders `outcome.refusals` (today: no caller, but the field's doc-comment in lib.rs:342-347 explicitly invites display — `surface them on SandboxOutcome.refusals so callers can flag a sandbox`), the UI either escapes them (safe) or doesn't (XSS). The UI's existing pattern for outcome.stderr is to render as `<pre>` with HTML-escape — but a new field added in this diff has no established render path yet. A new contributor adding a 'Refusals' tab in the UI is likely to use the same default escape path, but: the field is also surfaced via the JSON API (whatever serves SandboxOutcome to the UI), and any third-party integration that parses the JSON without escaping (e.g. a Slack notification that includes `${outcome.refusals.join('\\n')}` as a webhook body) becomes an HTML or markdown injection sink.\n\n(c) **structured-log injection / JSON-line poisoning**: the daemon's logging stack (tracing-subscriber, per Cargo.toml dev deps) typically emits structured logs. If `SandboxOutcome.refusals` is ever included in a `tracing::warn!(refusals = ?outcome.refusals, ...)` call, an attacker-crafted refusal string `\\\"}\\n{\\\"level\\\":\\\"ERROR\\\",\\\"target\\\":\\\"security\\\",\\\"msg\\\":\\\"forged log line\\\",` injects a synthetic log entry. Log aggregators (SIEM, ELK, Datadog) ingest the line as a separate event. The operator's incident search for ERRORs now returns attacker-authored entries indistinguishable from real ones.\n\n**The reachability gate is exactly #36**: the close gate on fd 3 in the sandboxee's pre_exec. With the gate ON (today's in-tree default), the sandboxee cannot write to fd 3, so the only producer of refusals is the trusted shim. With the gate OFF (per #36's analysis: out-of-tree caller, future second backend, partial-fix toggle), the sandboxee writes attacker-controlled refusal text into the daemon's operator-visible state.\n\nStatic pass missed it because (i) the field is a `Vec<String>` with no obvious display sink in this crate — the static rule for 'unescaped operator-visible strings' has no anchor since the rendering happens downstream in nyctos-ui or in operator CLI code; (ii) the bug is the *absence* of a content restriction (charset, max-len, no-control-chars) on a field marked for human display; (iii) the cross-finding chain (#36 forge → #41 injection) requires reasoning across two distinct hazard categories which taint analysis does not connect.\n\n**Fix (1+2 recommended)**: (1) in shim.rs's `ShimReport` deserialiser, add `#[serde(deserialize_with = \\\"deserialize_safe_refusal_strings\\\")]` on the refusals field — the deserializer rejects any string containing control chars (`c.is_control() && c != '\\n'`), strips ANSI escape introducer bytes (\\x1b followed by [ or ]), and caps each string to PATH_MAX + 256 bytes. Same defense applies whether the producer is the legitimate shim or a forging sandboxee. (2) document in lib.rs:342-348 that refusal strings have been sanitised and operators can surface them directly; (3) for the UI/CLI display path: any code that renders `outcome.refusals` should do so via HTML-escape (UI) or `String::from_utf8_lossy` + control-char strip (CLI) — but the wire-level cap in (1) is the canonical defense.\n\nDistinct from #36 (forge primitive itself) and #40 (RAM exhaustion via refusal volume) — same wire channel, different impact category (this finding is about the *content* of refusal strings; #40 is about their *bytes-on-wire-volume*; #36 is about the *write capability*).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Repro (requires #36's forge gate off — same precondition as #40): sandboxee writes a synthetic ShimReport with `refusals: [\\\"\\\\x1b[2J\\\\x1b[Hyou have been pwned by the sandbox\\\\x1b[0m\\\"]`. The shim later writes its own (empty refusals) frame; serde_json::from_slice on the two concatenated objects rejects (today returns None via #39's silent fallback) — but a single-write forge (sandboxee writes, then `kill -9 $PPID` to abort the shim before its own write) leaves a single valid ShimReport on the wire. Parent surfaces refusals to whatever downstream code renders them. Verifier check: assert any rendering path (CLI / UI / logs) HTML-escapes or strip-controls the field. Today no such defense exists. Compound with #40: a single 2 GB refusal string both injects control chars AND exhausts daemon RAM — combined CVSS jumps from individual-finding scope to full-daemon DoS-plus-defacement."
}

