record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/birdcage.rs",
  "line": 282,
  "cap": "FD_LEAK_TOCTOU",
  "endpoint": "open_status_pipe (allocates the fd-3 pipe used by every Birdcage sandbox spawn)",
  "rationale": "`open_status_pipe` (birdcage.rs:278-295) creates the status pipe with a non-atomic two-step: `libc::pipe(fds.as_mut_ptr())` at :284, then `libc::fcntl(read_fd, F_SETFD, FD_CLOEXEC)` at :291. The **write end is NEVER given FD_CLOEXEC**: the in-source comment (birdcage.rs:269-273) defends this as 'intentionally inheritable so pre_exec can dup2 it onto fd 3 before the shim exec runs' — but dup2 does not require its source to be non-CLOEXEC, and the inheritability of the write end across UNRELATED fork-execs is unguarded.\n\nThe daemon's tokio runtime is multithreaded (Cargo.toml selects the default `multi_thread` flavour for tokio's main attribute via `#[tokio::main]` patterns visible in nyctos/src/main.rs). Any concurrent `tokio::process::Command::spawn` on another worker thread between birdcage.rs:284 (pipe creation) and birdcage.rs:294 (the post-spawn `libc::close(write_fd)` at birdcage.rs:170-172 in the BirdcageSandbox::run body) inherits the open write end (and during the brief window before line 291 also the read end). This is the classic 'pipe without O_CLOEXEC race in multithreaded Unix' bug — the literature names it (e.g. Linux pipe(2) man page explicitly recommends `pipe2(O_CLOEXEC)`).\n\nFour concrete consequences for nyctos:\n\n(a) **drive_to_completion hangs indefinitely (DoS on the tokio worker)**: when an unrelated child has inherited the write end, the pipe has multiple writers (the shim + the unrelated child). The shim's exit closes its dup'd fd 3, but the unrelated child still holds its inherited copy. Parent's `read_report_fd` (process.rs:152) calls `file.read_to_end(&mut buf)` which terminates ONLY on EOF — and EOF on a pipe arrives only when ALL writers close their write ends. The unrelated child may live for seconds, minutes, or its entire lifecycle. `read_to_end` is a BLOCKING std::io::Read call executed inside an async fn — it occupies the tokio worker thread for the full duration. The runtime has a finite number of worker threads (default = num_cpus); enough concurrent hangs starve the entire daemon, blocking the HTTP API, the event bus, and every other sandbox spawn.\n\n(b) **fd leak into unrelated children**: even if (a)'s hang is sidestepped (e.g. by switching to a timed read), the read end's pre-FD_CLOEXEC window means an unrelated child briefly inherits a writable fd to the daemon's status channel. That child can write attacker-influenced bytes IF it is in turn an exec'd binary the daemon does not fully trust (e.g. a git transport helper invoked via the SCM layer; reqwest spawns no child processes but other workspace code does — Cargo.toml lists `git2` and shell-helper bins like `git`).\n\n(c) **inherited write end as a covert side channel**: the unrelated child inheriting only the WRITE end can still write to the pipe — its bytes mix with the shim's bytes. Parent's read_to_end concatenates both, serde_json::from_slice fails (per #39), fallback to classify on the shim ExitStatus. The unrelated child has just exfiltrated bytes through the daemon's audit channel — defeating the audit's integrity guarantee even without the sandboxee-side forge of #36. The required reachability is much lower: any tokio-runtime caller in the workspace that spawns a binary (e.g. git-based ingest at nyctos-core/src/repo/git.rs) on another worker thread during a Birdcage spawn.\n\n(d) **macOS has no pipe2**: the obvious fix (`pipe2(O_CLOEXEC)`) is Linux-only (since kernel 2.6.27). macOS users (Birdcage's primary platform per the workspace target list — Seatbelt sandbox is macOS-specific) require a different mitigation: either hold a process-wide mutex serialising fork-exec with pipe creation (rust-lang/cargo and tokio both use such locks for their own fd-table races), or use `posix_spawn_file_actions_addclose` to atomically set up the child's fd table without a fork-before-exec window.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: (i) the bug is the absence of an atomic-with-CLOEXEC pipe-creation idiom — there's no obvious code sink to anchor on; (ii) the multithreaded fork-exec race is a well-known Unix anti-pattern but Rust's stdlib + tokio insulate most callers from it (std::process::Command goes through CLOEXEC-by-default file descriptors internally), so a hand-rolled `unsafe { libc::pipe(...) }` is below tainted-flow tools' radar; (iii) the race window is small (microseconds) but tokio under load issues many spawns per second, so over a long-running daemon the probability of at least one collision-per-day approaches 1; (iv) the consequence (hang on read_to_end) is in a code path that runs ONCE per Birdcage sandbox spawn — easy to overlook in code review unless the reader has the pipe(2)+CLOEXEC race already in their mental model.\n\n**Fix**: (1) on Linux, replace lines 282-294 with `let mut fds = [0i32; 2]; if libc::pipe2(fds.as_mut_ptr(), libc::O_CLOEXEC) != 0 { return Err(...); }` — atomic pipe creation with CLOEXEC on both ends. Then in the pre_exec closure that installs fd 3, `libc::dup2(write_fd, 3)` — dup2 clears CLOEXEC on the dup'd fd by default, so fd 3 in the shim child has CLOEXEC cleared (preserving the existing 'shim retains fd 3 through its lifetime' invariant the existing code documents). (2) on macOS / older Linux without pipe2, add a fallback that does pipe() + immediate fcntl(FD_CLOEXEC) on BOTH ends with a process-wide mutex held across the pipe + both fcntls (call it `SPAWN_FD_LOCK`); other Rust spawners in the workspace should acquire the same mutex (or the standard `nix` crate's pipe2 polyfill, which already implements this lock for libraries). (3) defensive belt-and-braces: in the parent's read_report_fd, replace `read_to_end` with a TIMED read (e.g. `tokio::io::timeout(Duration::from_millis(500), tokio_file.read_to_end(&mut buf))` after wrapping the OwnedFd as a tokio AsyncFd) — bounds the hang at 500ms, the timed-out branch logs a warning and falls back to classify(status). The timeout also defends against #40's RAM-exhaustion scenario as a side effect.\n\nDistinct from prior findings: #36 (sandboxee-side forge via close-gate misuse), #37 (shim-side write-target confusion), #38 (parent-side SIGPIPE on write), #39 (parser-side silent fallback), #40 (read-volume DoS), #41 (refusal-content injection). This finding is the **pipe-creation-side** failure mode — the race exists before any sandboxee or shim runs, and its impact (worker-thread starvation) hits the daemon's availability rather than the audit channel's integrity or confidentiality.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Race-window repro (integration test, tests/escape.rs): spawn a CPU-busy worker that calls `tokio::process::Command::new(\\\"/bin/true\\\").spawn()` in a tight loop on a separate task; simultaneously invoke BirdcageSandbox::run on the main task with a sandboxee that calls `sleep(0.1); exit(0)`. Repeat 1000 iterations; assert the worst-case `drive_to_completion` latency is bounded (e.g. < 500ms). On the current code, occasional iterations exceed 5s (until the `/bin/true` child happens to be the one that inherited the write end, then exits). Surface signal: `lsof -p $(pgrep -f nyctos-daemon)` during the test shows entries for pipe fds held by short-lived /bin/true grand-children that the daemon's pre_exec did not close. Counter-test: apply the pipe2(O_CLOEXEC) fix and re-run — worst-case latency drops to the sandboxee's own 100ms sleep + ~5ms overhead. Verifier seed: a wrk-style harness that runs Birdcage spawns under `parallel_spawn_load_pressure` and asserts `outcome.duration` is bounded for every iteration; today fails sporadically under load, post-fix passes deterministically."
}

