record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/process.rs",
  "line": 157,
  "cap": "AUDIT_TAMPERING_ON_CANCEL",
  "endpoint": "drive_to_completion fd-3 read on TimedOut / Killed paths (Birdcage sandbox)",
  "rationale": "Session-0038 moved `read_report_fd` from inside the success arm of the status-selection match to an UNCONDITIONAL call ahead of it (process.rs:156-159). The doc-comment at :150-155 acknowledges status-field protection: 'TimedOut / Killed branches still win against the report's status field'. It is silent on the SECOND tuple element. The destructure `let (status_override, refusals) = read_report_fd(&mut state.status_fd)` binds `refusals` unconditionally; line :169 stamps it onto SandboxOutcome.refusals on EVERY branch, including the `if timed_out` and `else if state.killed_by_operator` arms that ignore status_override. The committed comment is asymmetric with the committed behavior — and an asymmetric comment in a fresh diff is exactly the soil that grows footguns: a reviewer reading the comment concludes 'cancel/timeout paths are sealed from the wire', when in fact only the status field is.\n\nThe attack surface is the same fd-3 forge primitive #36 documents: when the sandboxee-side close(3) gate is off (out-of-tree caller, future second backend wired pipe-on-fd-3 but forgot write_status_fd:true, partial-fix toggle), the sandboxee can `write(3, forged_ShimReport_json)`. Pre-session-0038, the cancel/timeout paths NEVER consumed fd 3 — TimedOut/Killed bypassed the entire `read_status_fd` call, so forged bytes sitting in the pipe were drained by the kernel when state.status_fd dropped at end of drive_to_completion. **Session-0038 reverses that property**: forged bytes are now PARSED and the refusals field is SURFACED to SandboxOutcome.refusals on the very paths an operator most needs to trust (a cancelled or timed-out sandbox is the case where the operator pulls up the post-mortem and reads what birdcage refused).\n\nThree concrete operator-trust failures flow from this:\n\n(a) **Operator-cancel triage misdirection**: an operator cancels a run mid-flight (UI clicks 'Stop' → BirdcageSandbox sends SIGKILL via `start_kill`/`killpg` at birdcage.rs:213-220 → state.killed_by_operator=true). The sandbox is force-terminated. The operator opens the run's audit panel: it reads 'Killed (by operator)' with refusals: ['ExecuteAndRead(/etc/shadow): operator declined this exception']. Operator concludes 'birdcage saved us, the sandboxee tried to grab /etc/shadow'. In fact: the sandboxee with forge access wrote that refusal line itself moments before the SIGKILL landed, knowing the parent would surface attacker-chosen refusals on the kill path. The operator's incident-response notes record a false birdcage-refusal that never happened, and the operator's confidence in birdcage's exception-rejection is calibrated against fabricated evidence.\n\n(b) **TimedOut path enables the same primitive with no time pressure**: timeout fires at process.rs:139 → `state.child.start_kill()` SIGKILLs the shim → second `state.child.wait().await` resolves → fd-3 has up to one full pipe buffer (~64KB on Linux, ~16KB on macOS) of sandboxee-authored bytes waiting. The shim never got to call write_report_to_fd3 (SIGKILL'd mid-sandboxee-execution), so the only producer of those bytes is the sandboxee itself. Parent reads them, parses one valid ShimReport (the sandboxee writes exactly one frame), surfaces the refusals. A sandboxee that knows the timeout is N seconds can race: do its real work, then with ~50ms to spare write a forged ShimReport containing a refusals list that obscures what the sandboxee actually did. The audit log shows 'timed out with these declared exceptions refused' — the refusal text steers triage away from the sandboxee's real activity (think: an exfil run that times out because the network was slow; refusals say 'ExecuteAndRead(/usr/bin/curl): permission denied' implying birdcage blocked it, when in fact curl ran fine and the timeout was the slow upload).\n\n(c) **Killed-by-operator + status_fd race produces a stronger signal than the operator realizes**: the operator's mental model of 'Killed' is that the sandbox was force-terminated and nothing it claims should be trusted. session-0038's behavior subtly violates that model: refusals from a Killed sandbox DO appear in audit. The status field correctly says 'Killed' but the refusals appear alongside. Operators who triage 'Killed' by reading the refusals first (a natural pattern — Killed means status is uninformative, so refusals become the primary signal) ingest attacker-chosen data first.\n\n**Compounding with #41 (LOG_INJECTION)**: the asymmetric trust on Killed/TimedOut paths means a sandboxee can inject ANSI/HTML/log-format-string payloads into refusals on a path the operator believes is fully gated. The combined attack: forge gate off (per #36), sandboxee writes a forged ShimReport with refusals=['\\x1b[2J\\x1b[H\\x1b[1;31mFAKE SECURITY ALERT: investigate immediately\\x1b[0m'], then deliberately triggers operator-cancel (or runs long enough to timeout). Operator's terminal renders the alert during post-mortem triage; the same terminal session may have other authentic security notifications scrolling, the attacker-chosen alert blends in.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: (i) the bug is the *asymmetric coverage* of two adjacent fields (status: gated, refusals: ungated) sharing one source, exactly the kind of bug that taint analysis treats as 'reaches the sink' uniformly because it doesn't model per-field branch coverage; (ii) the doc-comment at :150-155 reads correct in isolation — it accurately describes status's gating; the missing claim about refusals is an absence, not a misstatement; (iii) the prior #36/#41 findings cover the forge primitive and the content injection but assume a successful clean-exit run; the cancel/timeout interaction is a new path created by session-0038's refactor; (iv) the test added in session-0038 (`nonexistent_allow_read_path_surfaces_as_structured_refusal`) exercises the happy path only, not the kill/timeout interaction with a forging sandboxee; the test gives reviewers false confidence that 'refusals are wired up' without surfacing the cancel-path consumption.\n\n**Fix (1+2 recommended)**: (1) gate the fd-3 read on the SAME conditions that gate the status_override: move `read_report_fd` INSIDE the else branch of the status-selection match, so TimedOut/Killed paths bypass the wire entirely and return `refusals: Vec::new()`. The doc-comment then becomes accurate without modification. Code change is one-line: `} else { let (status_override, refusals) = read_report_fd(&mut state.status_fd); refusals_out = refusals; status_override.unwrap_or_else(|| classify(status)) }`. Operator-trust property restored: cancel/timeout sandboxes have empty refusals, which the UI/CLI can render as 'no refusal data available (sandbox terminated)'. (2) if (1) is rejected because the team WANTS refusals on cancel/timeout for diagnostic value, then update the doc-comment at :150-155 to read explicitly: 'TimedOut/Killed branches override the report's status field but ADOPT its refusals; refusals on those paths may be sandboxee-authored if the close(3) gate is off and must be treated as untrusted'. The comment then signals the trust boundary to every downstream reader (UI, CLI, log shipper, SIEM integration) so each renders refusals on Killed/TimedOut with an 'unverified' badge. (3) cross-cut with #41's content sanitisation: even if (1) is applied, refusals on the success path still need the control-char/length defense from #41; (1) and (2) only address the cancel-path adoption, not the success-path content trust. (4) regression test: extend `abort_sandboxee_surfaces_signaled_through_shim` with a variant that times out the sandboxee while it holds fd 3 open and asserts `outcome.refusals.is_empty()`. Today the test would pass or fail depending on whether the sandboxee got the write through before SIGKILL — flaky by design today, stable post-fix.\n\nDistinct from prior findings: #36 (sandboxee-side forge capability), #37 (shim-side write-target confusion), #38 (shim SIGPIPE on write), #39 (parse-error silent fallback), #40 (read-volume DoS), #41 (refusal-content injection), #42 (pipe-creation CLOEXEC race). All seven assume the parent's fd-3 consumption either happens on success (and audit integrity is the property) or doesn't happen on cancel (and the cancel path is sealed). #43 is the discovery that session-0038 BROKE the second assumption by moving the read out of the conditional — the cancel path is no longer sealed against wire bytes.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Two-stage repro for the cancel-path adoption (requires #36's close-gate off via a misconfigured caller, OR a separately-instrumented shim build). Stage 1 (forge + cancel): build an escape_attempt subcommand `forge-then-stall` that does `unsafe { let blob = serde_json::to_vec(&ShimReport { status: ShimStatus::Exited(0), refusals: vec![\\\"FORGED: birdcage refused /etc/shadow\\\".into()] }).unwrap(); libc::write(3, blob.as_ptr().cast(), blob.len()); libc::sleep(60); }` — sandboxee writes the forged frame then sleeps. Stage 2 (kill): in the test, await `sb.run(opts).await` from a background tokio task, then on the main task call `sb.kill().await` after 200ms (uses operator-cancel path). Assert `outcome.status == SandboxStatus::Killed` AND assert `outcome.refusals.is_empty()` (the property the fix establishes). Currently the assertion on refusals FAILS — outcome.refusals contains the forged line. Same test shape for TimedOut: set opts.timeout = 200ms, no separate kill; assert `outcome.status == SandboxStatus::TimedOut` AND `outcome.refusals.is_empty()`. Both fail today and pass post-fix. Operator-side observability check: invoke the daemon's audit JSON dump for a real cancelled run with the misconfigured shim — grep for refusals on Killed-status rows; non-empty rows are the attack signature."
}

Inventory: 43.

