record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/workspace.rs",
  "line": 72,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "every backend run() that consumes `SandboxOpts.snapshot_from` (process.rs:78, birdcage.rs:69, firecracker.rs:145, libkrun.rs:127)",
  "rationale": "`workspace::snapshot` is documented to reproduce in-tree symlinks AS symlinks rather than materialising them (workspace.rs:10-13, :72-75 copy_tree branch, :138-141 reflink_tree branch, plus the macOS clonefile fast path at :112 which preserves directory-entry symlinks under the cloned tree). The defensive rationale in the module header (`a symlink pointing outside the workspace stays an unreachable pointer rather than getting materialised into a real file under the snapshot`) is **conditionally true** — it relies on the *consumer* refusing to follow the symlink. None of the four backends installs such a refusal:\n\n- **ProcessSandbox** (process.rs) has by design no filesystem isolation — the new feature's tests at process.rs:289 explicitly call it the smallest-surface backend. The child runs with the daemon's UID/GID against the unmodified VFS. Any `open(2)`, `readlink(2)`-then-`open`, `cat ./hint`, `cargo build` (resolves `.cargo/config.toml` -> attacker-symlink -> `/home/operator/.aws/credentials`), or `git status` (walks symlinks in `.git/`) inside the snapshot follows symlinks via the kernel's path-resolution machinery to whatever target the source-tree symlink names.\n- **Birdcage** (birdcage.rs) installs a Landlock/seccomp policy keyed on the *workspace* path (`opts.workspace`); after `apply_snapshot_from` runs the workspace IS the snapshot tempdir (mod.rs:42 `opts.workspace = dst`). Landlock's `LANDLOCK_ACCESS_FS_READ_FILE` rules apply to the resolved-path target, not the symlink — but the policy is built from the `opts.allow_read` list (lib.rs `SandboxOpts.allow_read`), and an in-tree symlink to `/etc/shadow` causes Landlock to check `/etc/shadow` against the allow_read set. If `allow_read` is empty (the default), Landlock blocks. **But** the workspace itself is implicitly readable (the child needs to read its own source), and the symlink resolution happens *inside* the workspace path — so the actual sycall sees `dst/hint` which resolves to `/etc/shadow`. Whether Landlock catches this depends on which path it inspects (the lookup path or the resolved inode). Per Linux kernel docs Landlock rules are path-based and applied during `open()` lookup, walking through symlinks — so a symlink target outside the allowed scope IS blocked. Birdcage is the SAFE backend here; the gap is the other three.\n- **Firecracker** (firecracker.rs) and **libkrun** (libkrun.rs) snapshot the workspace and mount it into the microVM as the root or as a virtio-fs share. The mount carries the symlinks verbatim. Inside the microVM, the guest kernel resolves symlinks against the GUEST root, not the host — so a symlink to `/etc/shadow` reads the guest's `/etc/shadow` (the rootfs the microVM was built with), not the host's. This is the intended isolation. The escape vector here is different: a symlink to `/proc/self/cwd/../../../etc/host-something` or to `/etc/host_mount/...` IF the operator's microVM rootfs exposes host-mounts. Lower-severity for these backends, but still a documented sharp edge.\n\n**ProcessSandbox is the load-bearing failure**: it is the only backend that ships on every host (Cargo.toml has no `cfg!(target_os)` gate around `pub mod process`), it is the documented fallback when Birdcage / libkrun / firecracker are unavailable, and the new `with_snapshot_from` API is the FIRST primitive that lets an external caller (Phase 19 verifier, Phase 22 chain runner — both mentioned in process.rs:287-291) hand the sandbox a source directory the daemon trusts only weakly. The attack chain end-to-end: (1) repo ingest (post-`POST /api/v1/projects/:p/repos` per sentinel finding #14 attack surface) clones an attacker-published git repo; (2) the repo contains `./hint -> /home/operator/.ssh/id_rsa` checked in as a symlink; (3) verifier/chain runner calls `SandboxOpts::new(...).with_snapshot_from(repo_workspace).backend(ProcessSandbox)`; (4) sandboxed child runs `cat hint` and prints the operator's SSH key; (5) per sentinel finding #36/#37/#41, child stdout/stderr flows back through the AgentEvent bus to the events_ws WebSocket (router.rs:1730) — and that bus is, per finding #1, **readable cross-origin**. Net: a public-repo poisoning primitive that exfiltrates host secrets to a remote attacker through a chain of already-emitted findings, kicked off by this fresh feature.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: the bug is the absence of an in-tree-symlink-flattening step inside `workspace::snapshot`, paired with the absence of a refusal-to-follow contract on the ProcessSandbox consumer. There is no tainted-flow sink to anchor on — the dangerous behavior is the kernel's standard symlink-resolution machinery operating on a directory tree the daemon voluntarily handed to a less-trusted child. The module header (workspace.rs:10-13) *claims* the property the code does not deliver, which is exactly the shape static analyzers consistently miss.\n\n**Fix**: (1) extend `workspace::snapshot` with a `SnapshotOpts.flatten_symlinks: bool` (default true for the verifier/chain-runner call sites, false for the existing tests that pin the symlink-preservation behaviour) — when true, `fs::read_link` + canonicalize the target, refuse if the target escapes `src`, else materialise as a *regular file copy* of the target; (2) require ProcessSandbox to refuse `snapshot_from` whose tree contains any symlink whose target canonicalises outside `src` (the snapshot helper returns the list of in-tree symlinks; ProcessSandbox::run rejects with `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from contains escape symlinks\")`); (3) add an integration test in `tests/escape.rs` named `process_sandbox_refuses_escape_symlinks` that pins both behaviours; (4) update the module header at workspace.rs:10-13 to describe the *actual* contract, not the aspirational one.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer (tests/escape.rs): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let src = scratch.path().join(\"src\"); fs::create_dir(&src).unwrap(); fs::write(scratch.path().join(\"secret.txt\"), b\"top-secret\").unwrap(); std::os::unix::fs::symlink(scratch.path().join(\"secret.txt\"), src.join(\"hint\")).unwrap();` — then `let opts = SandboxOpts::new(PathBuf::from(\"/unused\"), vec![\"/bin/sh\".into(),\"-c\".into(),\"cat hint\".into()]).with_snapshot_from(src);` — run on ProcessSandbox, assert `outcome.stdout == b\"top-secret\"` (today fails the workspace-isolation invariant; post-fix returns `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from contains escape symlinks\")`). Verifier seed: same harness with attacker-checked-in `./hint -> /etc/passwd` mirrors the public-repo-poisoning chain end-to-end without needing a real `id_rsa` on disk."
}

