record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/workspace.rs",
  "line": 70,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "every backend run() with `snapshot_from` on a non-COW filesystem (tmpfs, ext4 without reflink, non-APFS macOS volumes)",
  "rationale": "`workspace::snapshot` chooses between three implementations based on host: `clonefile(2)` on macOS (O(1) per file via APFS COW), `ioctl(FICLONE)` on Linux btrfs/xfs (O(1) per file), and `copy_tree` everywhere else (workspace.rs:63 fallback path). The `copy_tree` branch recursively walks the source tree with **no bounds** on (a) total bytes copied, (b) file count, (c) recursion depth, (d) wall-clock time, (e) per-entry inode count, or (f) filesystem-loop / hard-link-cycle detection. Three concrete consequences:\n\n**(a) Disk exhaustion DoS**: an authenticated caller (or, post chain with sentinel finding #2 pre-setup AUTH_BYPASS, an unauthenticated remote one) requests `snapshot_from = /var/lib/docker/overlay2` (or `/proc` if the daemon's TMPDIR happens to be on a tmpfs that can be exhausted, or any large directory the daemon UID can read). The `copy_tree` materialises gigabytes — or, on tmpfs-backed TMPDIR (common in container deployments — Docker's default is tmpfs-backed `/tmp`), exhausts RAM until OOM-killer fires against the daemon itself. The destination is `TempDir::new()` which honors `TMPDIR`; the operator has no easy way to bound the copy quota. Even on a disk-backed TMPDIR, an attacker with one bearer token can request 100 parallel sandbox runs each with `snapshot_from` pointing at a 10GB tree — disk fills in <60s.\n\n**(b) Worker-thread starvation**: `apply_snapshot_from` (mod.rs:31) is called from each backend's `async fn run` BEFORE any await point; `crate::workspace::snapshot` is a synchronous `io::Result<…>` (workspace.rs:33). On the `copy_tree` fallback, the synchronous recursion holds the tokio worker thread for the full duration of the copy (no `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` wrapper). A single 5GB-tree snapshot pegs one worker thread for tens of seconds; the default tokio runtime has `num_cpus()` workers, so `num_cpus()` concurrent slow snapshots block ALL other async tasks on the runtime — including the HTTP API, the event bus, and webhook delivery. This compounds with sentinel findings #16/#17/#18 (webhook concurrency / per-IP throttle / slow-body permit) — the same daemon now has TWO independent ways for a single attacker to peg every worker thread.\n\n**(c) Symlink-loop / hard-link-cycle infinite recursion**: `copy_tree` uses `fs::symlink_metadata` on each entry (workspace.rs:71) — it recurses into directories without following symlinks (the symlink branch at :72-76 returns before the dir branch), so symlink loops are fine. BUT: hard links creating a directory-as-its-own-child are forbidden by Linux/macOS kernels, so the literal `loop` case is unreachable. The remaining cycle vector is *bind-mounts*: if `snapshot_from` is `/`, the kernel exposes `/proc/<pid>` which contains symlinks but also `/proc/<pid>/root` which on Linux IS a special-case symlink to the process's chroot — `symlink_metadata` reports it as a symlink and copy_tree creates a symlink under the snapshot. But if the daemon process happens to have `/proc/<pid>/root` as a *bind mount* (containerised deployments often do this), some Linux configurations expose it as a directory. Recursion through `/proc` then walks every PID's mount namespace recursively. This is exotic; the primary DoS is (a) and (b).\n\n**(d) Hidden interaction with the clonefile/reflink fast-paths**: even the COW fast paths are not free of this — `clonefile` on macOS COW-clones the entire src tree at the filesystem layer, which IS O(1) in time but COW-allocates metadata blocks proportional to the inode count. A snapshot_from of `/Users` on a developer laptop COW-clones every Spotlight index, Time Machine snapshot, etc.; the metadata cost is real and shows up as APFS background work that contends for I/O bandwidth with other sandbox spawns. Lower-severity than (a)/(b) but documented for completeness.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: copy_tree is straightforward recursive Rust that passes every taint-flow check — there is no sink, no `unsafe`, no exec, no network. The DoS surface is the *unbounded resource consumption* itself, a category most static analyzers don't model. The synchronous-in-async hazard (b) is detectable by clippy's `tokio_blocking_in_async` lint IF enabled, but `fs::copy` is not on the lint's blocking-function list (the lint targets `std::thread::sleep` and explicit `tokio::task::block_in_place` misuse, not arbitrary FS recursion).\n\n**Fix**: (1) extend `SandboxOpts` with `snapshot_byte_budget: u64` and `snapshot_entry_budget: usize` (defaults: 1 GiB / 100k entries) — `copy_tree` carries a `Counter` ref that increments on each entry and returns `io::ErrorKind::FileTooLarge` past the cap; (2) wrap `crate::workspace::snapshot` in `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` at every backend's `apply_snapshot_from` call site so the synchronous recursion never pegs a tokio worker; (3) add a wall-clock timeout in `apply_snapshot_from` (e.g. 30s default; configurable per-backend); (4) for the production wiring (verifier / chain runner — sentinel session-0028 #26 notes the `build_exploration_scope` flow), ensure the `snapshot_from` source is constrained to a known-good subtree (the active repo ingest directory) — never an operator-supplied raw path through the API.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer (tests/escape.rs, requires non-APFS / non-btrfs / non-xfs target): `let big = tempdir().unwrap(); for i in 0..50_000 { fs::write(big.path().join(format!(\"f{i}\")), vec![0u8; 100_000]).unwrap(); }` (5 GB / 50k files); then `let opts = SandboxOpts::new(PathBuf::from(\"/unused\"), vec![\"/bin/true\".into()]).with_snapshot_from(big.path().into());` — run on ProcessSandbox, observe `apply_snapshot_from` block the tokio worker for tens of seconds, /tmp usage spike by 5 GB, and a concurrent `GET /api/v1/runs` from another connection time out / become unresponsive for the duration. Counter-test: apply the spawn_blocking + 30s timeout + 1 GiB budget fix and re-run — `apply_snapshot_from` returns `SandboxError::Workspace(io::Error { kind: FileTooLarge })` within ~5s, the tokio runtime stays responsive, the HTTP API continues serving."
}


