record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/birdcage.rs",
  "line": 100,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "BirdcageSandbox::run when `opts.snapshot_from` is set together with `opts.allow_write` / `opts.allow_read` entries keyed on the operator-supplied workspace path",
  "rationale": "`apply_snapshot_from` (backend/mod.rs:46) silently overwrites `opts.workspace` with the TempDir snapshot path BEFORE birdcage.rs reaches the policy-composition block at :94-102. The policy block then reads `opts.allow_read.clone()` (:94) and `opts.allow_write.clone()` (:100) — values the operator chose against the ORIGINAL workspace path — and concatenates the (now-different) `opts.workspace` only for the implicit workspace-write entry at :101. The operator-supplied allow_read / allow_write entries are NEVER rewritten to track the workspace override. Two concrete failure modes flow from this:\n\n**(a) Stale allow_write entries punch a hole BACK to the source tree.** The verifier / chain-runner mentioned at process.rs:287-291 will idiomatically configure a Birdcage run with both `snapshot_from = <repo_workspace>` (workspace isolation) AND `allow_write = [<repo_workspace>/out]` (let the sandboxee emit artifacts to a known directory). After apply_snapshot_from runs: opts.workspace = <tempdir>/workspace, but opts.allow_write still contains the literal PathBuf <repo_workspace>/out which is OUTSIDE the snapshot. Birdcage builds a Landlock ruleset that GRANTS LANDLOCK_ACCESS_FS_WRITE_FILE on the original `<repo_workspace>/out` directory. The sandboxee runs from <tempdir>/workspace with the kernel-installed ruleset; an `open(\"/abs/path/to/repo_workspace/out/x\", O_WRONLY|O_CREAT)` call from the sandboxee SUCCEEDS — Landlock checks the resolved-path target, sees a granted prefix, and lets the write through. The write lands in the OPERATOR's source tree, defeating the workspace write-isolation invariant the new feature was added to provide. The sandboxee can `cat secret_file > /abs/repo_workspace/out/leak.txt` and the leak persists past the TempDir drop because the destination is not in the snapshot.\n\n**(b) Stale allow_read entries open a parallel exfil channel.** Same flow with `allow_read = [<repo_workspace>/inputs]` — after override, the sandboxee retains permission to read from a path that is no longer 'inside' the workspace from its viewpoint, but is in the operator's source tree from the kernel's viewpoint. Combined with sentinel finding #36/#37/#41 (refusals & stdout flow back through the agent event bus to events_ws, which finding #1 documents as cross-origin readable), the sandboxee reads arbitrary files in <repo_workspace>/inputs (which may have been intentionally narrowed to a subset of the source) and prints them to stdout — but at the same time the sandboxee can now ALSO `open(/abs/path/to/repo_workspace/.git/config)` if the operator's policy was 'allow_read = [<repo_workspace>]' (a coarse-grain policy a real operator WILL write when the contract is 'workspace is isolated, the whole thing is readable'). Pre-snapshot that policy means 'whole workspace readable' — internally consistent. Post-override it means 'whole ORIGINAL workspace readable, including paths the snapshot was supposed to hide'.\n\n**The trigger that makes this load-bearing in production**: the static pass treats `allow_read` / `allow_write` as taint sources that are trusted by definition (operator-supplied), and `snapshot_from` as an *unrelated* configuration field. The cross-field interaction — that snapshot_from silently changes the meaning of every other path-typed field — is a STATE-MACHINE flaw: opts is a struct of disjoint fields the type system pretends are independent, but apply_snapshot_from's mutation creates an implicit invariant ('rewrite every path-typed field that was keyed on the old workspace') that no code enforces.\n\n**Why birdcage is the load-bearing case (and the other backends are partially mitigated)**: firecracker and libkrun mount opts.workspace into a microVM rootfs; allow_read / allow_write on those backends apply to the GUEST filesystem, not the host. A stale allow_write path keyed on the host's <repo_workspace>/out does nothing in the guest because that path does not exist there. ProcessSandbox has NO enforcement of allow_read / allow_write at all (it relies purely on the host UID), so the stale list is a no-op too. Birdcage is uniquely affected because (i) Landlock IS the enforcement primitive, (ii) Landlock keys on host paths the sandboxee sees through bind-resolution, (iii) the sandboxee inherits the daemon's UID and FS view so a host-relative path the daemon could write IS a path the sandboxee can write.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: this is the classic 'silent semantic-drift on mutation' bug. Taint analysis sees:\n  - tainted (operator) inputs flow into opts.allow_read/allow_write — this is OK by policy.\n  - opts.workspace is mutated mid-flow — but the analyzer doesn't model 'paths previously stored against the prior workspace are now stale'.\nThere is no sink that observes the staleness; the staleness IS the bug. Static pass also wouldn't catch it because the policy composition itself is correct given the bare opts struct — the bug is the prior history of opts, not the current state.\n\n**Fix (1 + 2 in tandem)**: (1) make `apply_snapshot_from` REFUSE the combination unless allow_read / allow_write are both empty OR the caller explicitly opts into 'do not rewrite' via a new field like `snapshot_from_rewrites_policy_paths: bool`. The default fail-closed: `if !opts.allow_read.is_empty() || !opts.allow_write.is_empty() { return Err(SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from cannot be combined with allow_read/allow_write entries pointing into the source workspace; either clear those lists or set snapshot_from_rewrites_policy_paths=true to opt into automatic rewrite\")); }`. (2) when the opt-in flag is set, walk every entry in opts.allow_read and opts.allow_write; if an entry has the ORIGINAL workspace as a prefix, rewrite it to use the NEW workspace as the prefix (the snapshot reproduces the same in-tree layout, so the relative paths are stable). Entries pointing OUTSIDE the original workspace are passed through unchanged (e.g. /etc/ssl/certs entries). (3) regression test: add `tests/escape.rs::birdcage_snapshot_from_blocks_stale_allow_write_to_source_tree` that sets snapshot_from + allow_write to an in-source path and asserts the open()-from-sandboxee fails with EACCES (post-fix) or succeeds (today). (4) update the doc-comment on `with_snapshot_from` (lib.rs:323-329) to spell out the contract: 'Setting snapshot_from voids any allow_read/allow_write entries that were keyed on the original workspace; either supply policy-relative paths (e.g. inside the snapshot subtree by relative name) or set the policy AFTER calling with_snapshot_from'.\n\nDistinct from prior findings: #2/#13/#16 (HTTP-tier policy), #36-#43 (sandbox-shim trust boundary), #42 (in-tree symlink escape — the symlink is INSIDE the snapshot tree; here the path is the original-workspace allow_write entry, a separate vector), #43 (DoS via copy_tree volume; orthogonal).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer (tests/escape.rs, Linux only — Landlock-gated): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let src = scratch.path().join(\"src\"); fs::create_dir(&src).unwrap(); fs::write(src.join(\"hello.txt\"), b\"hello\").unwrap(); let out_dir = src.join(\"out\"); fs::create_dir(&out_dir).unwrap();` then `let opts = SandboxOpts::new(PathBuf::from(\"/unused\"), vec![\"/bin/sh\".into(),\"-c\".into(),format!(\"printf POISONED > '{}'/leak.txt\", out_dir.display())]).with_snapshot_from(src.clone()).allow_write(vec![out_dir.clone()]);` — run on Birdcage backend, assert `outcome.status == SandboxStatus::Exited(0)` (today succeeds — the write went through because allow_write still names the host-side out_dir) AND assert `fs::read_to_string(out_dir.join(\"leak.txt\")).unwrap() == \"POISONED\"` (today the file exists in the OPERATOR'S source tree, post-snapshot, defeating isolation). Post-fix run returns `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from cannot be combined with allow_read/allow_write...\")` OR (with rewrite opt-in) the write lands in <tempdir>/workspace/out/leak.txt and src/out/leak.txt does NOT exist. Verifier seed: chain with sentinel finding #1 (events_ws cross-origin) to confirm the operator-tree leak is observable from a remote attacker."
}

