record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/mod.rs",
  "line": 37,
  "cap": "TOCTOU",
  "endpoint": "apply_snapshot_from helper invoked from every backend run() (process.rs:78, birdcage.rs:69, firecracker.rs:145, libkrun.rs:127)",
  "rationale": "Two interlocking gaps in `apply_snapshot_from` (mod.rs:31-48): (i) `src.exists()` (line 37) follows symlinks AND accepts any file type — regular files, FIFOs, character devices, root-of-tree symlinks all return true; (ii) between `src.exists()` and `crate::workspace::snapshot(&src, &dst)` (line 45) there is a TOCTOU window in which a concurrent process can mutate, rename, or replace the source tree. Combined with workspace::snapshot's tree-walk taking arbitrarily long (per prior finding #43), the window is wide enough to be reliably racy.\n\n**(a) File-type acceptance produces malformed workspaces.** A caller (verifier / chain runner / out-of-tree integrator) passes `snapshot_from = /var/lib/nyctos/active/symlink-to-repo` where the link target is currently `/path/to/repo-A`. `src.exists()` resolves the symlink and returns true. `workspace::snapshot(&src, &dst)` is then called with the symlink path; depending on which fast path activates, the symlink is followed differently:\n  - `clonefile(2)` on macOS: follows the symlink for a directory source and clones the resolved tree.\n  - `ioctl(FICLONE)` on Linux: same — operates on the resolved inode.\n  - `copy_tree` fallback: `fs::symlink_metadata(src)` is called at workspace.rs:71 on the ENTRY (a subentry, not src itself); for src itself, copy_tree is entered via the public `snapshot()` entry which calls `metadata()` (follows symlinks).\nSo a root symlink is silently followed in every backend. Prior #42 documented in-tree symlinks reproducing as symlinks; this is a different leg — the ROOT of the tree being a symlink is silently dereferenced, with no `is_dir()` check anywhere. A misconfigured caller (e.g. a chain runner that hands sandbox the path of a build-output symlink rather than the build root) silently snapshots the SYMLINK TARGET instead of erroring out. If the target is `/etc` (operator mistake or attacker-influenced env), the snapshot is a COW clone of `/etc`. Birdcage's policy then permits the sandboxee to read /etc/* from inside the snapshot, defeating the isolation the operator believed they had.\n\nWorse for FIFOs / character devices: `src.exists()` returns true for `/dev/zero`, `/dev/urandom`, named pipes. `workspace::snapshot` on a FIFO source: `fs::metadata(&src)` returns metadata claiming non-directory; copy_tree's outer entry is `snapshot(src, dst)` (workspace.rs:33) which assumes the input is a directory — passing a FIFO leads to either `read_dir` returning ENOTDIR (clean error) or, depending on the fast-path used, an indefinite block reading from the FIFO. A malicious or confused operator who passes `/dev/zero` as `snapshot_from` triggers an unbounded read inside `crate::workspace::snapshot`, hanging the tokio worker forever — a deterministic DoS distinct from #43's volume-based DoS.\n\n**(b) TOCTOU between exists() and snapshot().** The two filesystem reads are not synchronized. Three concrete races:\n  - **Race-to-replace**: process P holds the source path at `/run/nyctos/work/X`. Concurrently another process renames `/run/nyctos/work/X` to `/run/nyctos/work/X.evicted` and creates a new `/run/nyctos/work/X` pointing at a different tree. `exists()` saw the original; `workspace::snapshot` walks the replacement. Net: the sandboxee runs against a tree the operator did NOT intend, with no error signaled. Attack scenario: a previous sandboxee (or a co-tenant on a shared host) has write access to the parent of the source path; it swaps the tree mid-flight to inject a malicious workspace into the next sandbox run.\n  - **Race-to-grow**: a file appears under `src/` between `exists()` and the recursive walk; `copy_tree` snapshots it. Attack scenario: the source is the operator's repo-ingest staging directory; the ingest is still extracting when the sandbox starts; the ingest's late-appearing files leak into a sandbox run the operator believed had a stable snapshot.\n  - **Race-to-shrink**: a file in `src/` is unlinked mid-walk; `copy_tree` either skips it (if the entry was already enumerated but not yet copied — fs::copy fails with ENOENT) or includes a partial state. The snapshot is non-deterministic.\n\n**(c) The combination is sharp**: an attacker who controls the file-type of `src` AND has a small write capability in the parent directory can construct a snapshot_from path that is at exists()-time a benign file but at snapshot()-time a directory. Example: `src = /tmp/x` where `/tmp/x` is initially a file (exists()=true, passes the no-explicit-is_dir check, falls through to snapshot); the attacker, racing the apply_snapshot_from call, unlinks `/tmp/x` and creates `/tmp/x/` as a directory containing files of their choice. workspace::snapshot then walks the attacker's directory. The two-step check-then-act is exploitable because there is no canonicalize-then-fstatat lock on the inode.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: (i) the file-type omission is an *absent* check — taint analysis cannot anchor on what is not there; (ii) the TOCTOU is the canonical class of bug that requires understanding fs-call sequencing across two distinct syscalls referring to the same path, which most static analyzers do not model; (iii) the FIFO-hang vector requires reasoning about open() semantics on different file types, which is outside ordinary taint flow; (iv) workspace::snapshot is documented as 'COW snapshot of a tree' (workspace.rs:10) — the analyzer trusts the comment.\n\n**Fix**: (1) in `apply_snapshot_from`, replace `src.exists()` with `fs::symlink_metadata(&src)` plus an explicit `metadata.file_type().is_dir()` check that REFUSES symlinks at the root (`fs::symlink_metadata` does not follow the link, so a root symlink shows as is_symlink() == true and is_dir() == false — the check naturally refuses it). FIFO / device / file / socket roots all fail the is_dir() check. (2) open the source via `OpenOptions::new().read(true).custom_flags(libc::O_DIRECTORY | libc::O_NOFOLLOW).open(&src)` to lock the inode reference, then pass the FD (via `openat` on subentries) into a TOCTOU-safe variant of `workspace::snapshot` that uses `openat` rather than absolute path lookups. (3) regression test: `tests/escape.rs::apply_snapshot_from_refuses_root_symlink`, `apply_snapshot_from_refuses_fifo`, and a multi-threaded `apply_snapshot_from_resists_concurrent_replace` that races a rename against the snapshot call and asserts a deterministic Config error or a guaranteed-snapshot-of-original-tree.\n\nDistinct from prior findings: #42 (in-tree symlinks reproduced verbatim — affects subtree entries, NOT the root); #43 (unbounded copy_tree DoS — assumes a valid directory tree; this finding is about INVALID / mutated tree inputs); #36-#43 are all post-spawn trust-boundary bugs; this is pre-spawn input validation on the snapshot_from path itself.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer A (file-type): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let link_target = scratch.path().join(\"target\"); fs::create_dir(&link_target).unwrap(); std::os::unix::fs::symlink(&link_target, scratch.path().join(\"as_link\")).unwrap(); let mut opts = SandboxOpts::new(PathBuf::from(\"/unused\"), vec![\"/bin/true\".into()]).with_snapshot_from(scratch.path().join(\"as_link\"));` — call `apply_snapshot_from(&mut opts)` on the resulting opts; today returns Ok and snapshots the resolved target; post-fix returns `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from must be a directory, got symlink\")`. Reproducer B (FIFO hang): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let fifo = scratch.path().join(\"as_fifo\"); nix::unistd::mkfifo(&fifo, nix::sys::stat::Mode::from_bits(0o644).unwrap()).unwrap(); let mut opts = SandboxOpts::new(PathBuf::from(\"/unused\"), vec![\"/bin/true\".into()]).with_snapshot_from(fifo);` — `apply_snapshot_from(&mut opts)` blocks indefinitely today; post-fix returns `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from must be a directory, got fifo\")`. Reproducer C (TOCTOU): two-thread harness — thread T1 calls `apply_snapshot_from` in a loop with `snapshot_from = /tmp/race`; thread T2 alternates `fs::write(\"/tmp/race\", b\"file\")` and `fs::remove_file(\"/tmp/race\"); fs::create_dir(\"/tmp/race\");`. Today T1 occasionally observes a directory snapshot when it expected a file refusal (or vice-versa, depending on which fix is applied). Post-fix the TOCTOU-safe O_DIRECTORY|O_NOFOLLOW open returns ENOTDIR or success against a single locked inode; outcome is deterministic per race iteration."
}

