{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/backend/mod.rs",
  "line": 42,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "apply_snapshot_from (mod.rs:24-46) consumed by ProcessSandbox::run (process.rs:78), BirdcageSandbox::run (birdcage.rs:69), FirecrackerSandbox::run (firecracker.rs:145), LibkrunSandbox::run (libkrun.rs:127)",
  "rationale": "`apply_snapshot_from` performs ONE mutation on `opts`: `opts.workspace = dst` at mod.rs:42. The struct has SIX other fields that semantically reference workspace-relative paths and that this helper does NOT touch: `cwd: Option<PathBuf>` (lib.rs:264, defaults to workspace at backend/mod.rs:74), `allow_read: Vec<PathBuf>` (lib.rs:282), `allow_write: Vec<PathBuf>` (lib.rs:285), plus indirectly any env-var path (e.g. `CARGO_TARGET_DIR`, `RUST_LOG_FILE`) the caller already stamped from the source-workspace value. The `with_snapshot_from` docstring at lib.rs:323-326 says verbatim: 'Returns `self` so it composes with the other `SandboxOpts` setters.' — explicitly inviting callers to chain. A caller that follows that docstring naively:\n\n```rust\nlet ws = repo_workspace.clone();\nlet opts = SandboxOpts::new(ws.clone(), vec![\"cargo\".into(), \"build\".into()])\n    .with_allow_write(vec![ws.join(\"target\")])   // hypothetical chainable form\n    .with_snapshot_from(ws);\n// build_command does cmd.current_dir(opts.cwd.as_deref().unwrap_or(&opts.workspace))\n// — opts.cwd is None so cwd = opts.workspace = tempdir/workspace. OK.\n// But opts.allow_write = [repo_workspace/target] — the ORIGINAL location.\n```\n\nBirdcage's policy assembly (per `payload_runner` and the shim's ExceptionSet builder) takes `opts.allow_write` verbatim and adds a `LANDLOCK_ACCESS_FS_WRITE_FILE` rule on `repo_workspace/target`. The sandboxee `cd`'s into `tempdir/workspace`, runs `cargo build`, which resolves `CARGO_TARGET_DIR` (defaults to `./target`) — relative resolution gives `tempdir/workspace/target` and Birdcage blocks the write because nothing in the snapshot path is in allow_write. BUT cargo also honors absolute target paths; a build script with `println!(\"cargo:rerun-if-changed={}\", repo_workspace.join(\"target/marker\"))` or a custom `[build].target-dir` in `.cargo/config.toml` (which the snapshot reproduced from the source) can name the original `repo_workspace/target` absolutely. Birdcage's allow_write entry permits that absolute write. **The snapshot's whole purpose — isolating writes from the source — is silently defeated**. The same primitive applies to:\n\n- **`opts.cwd`**: a caller that set `cwd = ws.join(\"src/subcrate\")` before the snapshot setter ends up with cwd pointing at `repo_workspace/src/subcrate` (the source) while the snapshot at `tempdir/workspace/src/subcrate` sits unused; the sandboxed child runs against the unsnapshotted source.\n- **`opts.allow_read`**: a caller adding `ws.join(\".cargo\")` to `allow_read` for crates.io credential reuse points read access at the source's `.cargo/`; the sandboxee reads the operator's untouched `credentials.toml`, exfiltrates via stdout (which sentinel #1 / #37 / #41 already document as cross-origin-readable on the events_ws path).\n- **`opts.env`**: env values are byte-for-byte copied (lib.rs:267). A caller passing `(\"HOME\", ws.join(\"home\"))` ends up with the sandboxee's `$HOME` pointing at the source workspace; any tool that reads `$HOME/.netrc`, `$HOME/.aws/credentials`, `$HOME/.ssh/known_hosts` reads the operator's files.\n\nWhy the implementation has this gap: `apply_snapshot_from`'s contract is narrow (\"materialise a COW snapshot and override workspace\"), the docstring of `with_snapshot_from` is broad (\"composes with the other `SandboxOpts` setters\"). The narrow implementation and broad docstring meet at the caller site as a SILENT contract violation: the program type-checks, the unit tests at mod.rs:97-141 pass (they only verify workspace override and tempdir RAII, never inspect allow_read/allow_write retention), the chained builder reads naturally — and the security invariant is gone.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: the bug is structural — it's the *absence* of a rewrite pass over correlated fields after an override, paired with a misleading composition claim in a docstring. Taint analysis sees workspace-relative path construction happen at the call site (under the caller's domain, where the source workspace value is trusted), then the SandboxOpts struct ferries those paths into the backend (still trusted). The backend's policy assembly takes allow_read/allow_write at face value (correct under the prior contract where workspace was caller-supplied and consistent with the rest of the opts). No single sink looks wrong; the wrongness is the workspace value diverging from the other workspace-derived values mid-flight. Spec-level invariant check (`forall p in opts.allow_read ∪ opts.allow_write ∪ {opts.cwd}: p.starts_with(opts.workspace) || p is an explicitly-external path`) would catch it; no such invariant exists today.\n\n**Operator-side surface**: Phase 19 verifier and Phase 22 chain runner (named in process.rs:288-291 and the `with_snapshot_from` docstring rationale) are the first production consumers of this feature. Both are under active development with no public callers committed yet. Lands the fix before that wiring cements: every later caller that adopts a chained builder pattern carries this footgun.\n\n**Fix**: (1) inside `apply_snapshot_from`, after `opts.workspace = dst`, walk `opts.cwd`, `opts.allow_read`, `opts.allow_write` and for each entry that satisfies `entry.starts_with(&src_canonical)` (the ORIGINAL pre-override workspace value, captured before the swap), rewrite the prefix to `dst`. Entries that do NOT prefix-match the original workspace stay untouched (they're explicit external paths the caller wants regardless of the snapshot). Entries that prefix-match BUT canonicalise outside `src_canonical` (escape symlinks) return `SandboxError::Config(\"…\")`. (2) extend the docstring at lib.rs:323-326 to specify the rewrite semantics so a caller can reason about what `composes` means. (3) regression test in mod.rs::tests: `apply_snapshot_from_rewrites_workspace_relative_allow_lists` — stage src with `subdir/`, set `allow_write = vec![src.join(\"subdir/out\")]`, apply, assert `opts.allow_write[0]` now equals `dst.join(\"subdir/out\")`. (4) defensive sibling test: a caller-supplied external path (e.g. `/usr/local/share/foo`) is NOT rewritten. (5) cross-cut with #21's symlink finding: the prefix-match check uses canonicalised paths so a `src/escape -> /etc` symlink is rejected at apply time rather than reaching the backend.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer for the `allow_write` leak (no extra dependencies): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let src = scratch.path().join(\"src\"); fs::create_dir_all(src.join(\"out\")).unwrap(); fs::write(src.join(\"out/marker\"), b\"untouched\").unwrap();` — then `let mut opts = SandboxOpts::new(src.clone(), vec![\"/bin/sh\".into(),\"-c\".into(),format!(\"echo poisoned > {}/marker\", src.join(\"out\").display())]); opts.allow_write = vec![src.join(\"out\")]; opts.snapshot_from = Some(src.clone());` — run on BirdcageSandbox (the only backend that ENFORCES allow_write), `sb.wait().await` clean exit, then assert `fs::read(src.join(\"out/marker\")).unwrap() == b\"untouched\"` — today the assertion FAILS (the marker reads `poisoned\\n`) because allow_write[0] still names the source path post-override and Birdcage permits the absolute write back into the source. Post-fix the marker is untouched (allow_write was rewritten to dst.join(\"out\")). Parallel reproducer for `cwd` leak: same setup, `opts.cwd = Some(src.join(\"out\"));` — sandboxee's `pwd` reads the source path; post-fix reads tempdir/workspace/out."
}

