record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/workspace.rs",
  "line": 127,
  "cap": "SANDBOX_ESCAPE",
  "endpoint": "workspace::snapshot macOS fast-path clonefile() invoked from apply_snapshot_from (backend/mod.rs:41)",
  "rationale": "`workspace::snapshot` on macOS calls `clonefile(src_c.as_ptr(), dst_c.as_ptr(), 0)` at workspace.rs:127 — the third argument is the `flags` field and is hard-coded to 0. Per Apple's `man 2 clonefile`: 'If sourceFile is a symbolic link, the symbolic link is dereferenced. If CLONE_NOFOLLOW is passed in the `flags` parameter, then the symbolic link itself is cloned instead of the target.' Flags=0 therefore DEREFERENCES the top-level src symlink before cloning. The Linux reflink path at workspace.rs:136-141 correctly uses `fs::symlink_metadata(src)` and reproduces a top-level src symlink as a symlink (no dereference); the Copy fallback at workspace.rs:71-76 likewise uses `symlink_metadata`. The macOS clonefile path is the lone outlier.\n\nDistinct from prior #42 (in-tree nested symlinks reproduced as symlinks and then resolved at sandboxee open() time): #45 is the case where the TOP-LEVEL `snapshot_from` value IS the symlink. The operator (or an upstream caller in a future Phase 19/22 wiring) hands the API a path under their control — say `~/.nyctos/scratch/current-repo` — that they manage as a moving symlink to whichever repo is checked out. An attacker who can briefly swap that symlink (concurrent rename, hostile config-file write, or an admin-tool race) points it at `/private/etc` for the duration of one snapshot call; `clonefile(.../current-repo, tempdir/workspace, 0)` clones `/private/etc` into `tempdir/workspace`, then `opts.workspace = tempdir/workspace` and the sandboxed child operates on a writable clone of `/etc`. The Birdcage backend's allow_read/allow_write rules apply to the new workspace path, so the child can `cat tempdir/workspace/shadow` and exfiltrate via stdout → events_ws (sentinel #1 cross-origin readable).\n\n**Why this matters even when the operator-side workflow doesn't involve symlinks**: macOS `~/.Trash`, `~/Library/Application Support/...`, and several Apple-vended package managers stamp paths through symlinks (e.g. `/usr/local` is a symlink to `/opt/homebrew` on Apple Silicon hosts; `~/Library/Caches/<app>` is often a symlink under enterprise MDM). A user-supplied `snapshot_from` path that *traverses* such a symlink at any point — e.g. `~/code/myrepo` where `~/code` is an MDM-managed symlink to `/Volumes/EnterpriseShare/code` — invites a per-volume permission surprise (the EnterpriseShare may be NFS, where APFS clonefile fails over to its non-COW fallback, exposing the unbounded copy_tree DoS from #43 ALSO at sandbox-spawn time).\n\nThe more pernicious case is *attacker-supplied* `snapshot_from`. Once a Phase 19 verifier or Phase 22 chain runner calls `with_snapshot_from(<path derived from a finding's payload metadata>)` — and the system already converts payload-synthesis output into filesystem paths in adjacent code (see chain_runner.rs and payload_runner.rs) — the symlink-as-src primitive becomes a finding-poisoning sink. A finding's `path` field crafted as `/tmp/attacker/sym-to-etc` causes the verifier to snapshot `/etc` as the next sandbox's workspace; the verifier then reports 'the payload reproduces against /tmp/attacker/sym-to-etc' as evidence, when in fact it reproduced against /etc.\n\n**Why the static pass missed it**: clonefile's symlink semantics are documented in Apple's man page but not in the Rust `libc` crate's docs; static analyzers that flag missing CLOEXEC, missing O_NOFOLLOW, or missing AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW do not, in practice, ship a rule for clonefile's flags argument. The Rust binding here is also extern \"C\" with `flags: u32` typed positionally, so type checking finds nothing. The doc-comment at workspace.rs:10-13 promises 'a symlink pointing outside the workspace stays an unreachable pointer rather than getting materialised into a real file under the snapshot' — that statement is verified by the `snapshot_preserves_symlinks_without_following_them` test at workspace.rs:230-245, BUT the test stages a symlink INSIDE src, never a symlink AT src. The test passes; the docstring reads true; the macOS top-level case is uncovered.\n\n**Fix**: (1) workspace.rs:127 pass `CLONE_NOFOLLOW = 1` instead of 0; the kernel returns EINVAL if the src is a symlink that resolves to a directory and `CLONE_NOFOLLOW` is set with the no-dir-symlink edge case — wrap with a `fs::symlink_metadata(src)` precheck that detects the symlink-at-src case, reproduces it AS a symlink via `std::os::unix::fs::symlink(target, dst)` (mirroring the Linux reflink_tree behaviour at workspace.rs:138-141), and skips clonefile entirely. (2) extend `apply_snapshot_from` (backend/mod.rs:30-46) with a top-level `fs::symlink_metadata(&src)?.file_type().is_symlink()` check that REFUSES the snapshot with `SandboxError::Config(\"snapshot_from must not be a symlink; canonicalise the caller-supplied path first\")` — this is the safer-by-default choice for any new API. (3) add a regression test in workspace.rs::tests named `snapshot_refuses_top_level_symlink_src`: stage `src_dir/`, then `src_link -> src_dir`, call `snapshot(src_link, dst)`, assert `dst` is created as a symlink (NOT a copy of src_dir's contents). (4) cross-cut with #44: the prefix-match logic in #44's fix should operate on the CANONICALISED original src, so the rewrite is robust against this symlink case even if (1)/(2) are not applied.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Reproducer (workspace.rs unit test, macOS only — gated on `cfg!(target_os = \"macos\")`): `let scratch = tempdir().unwrap(); let src_dir = scratch.path().join(\"src\"); fs::create_dir(&src_dir).unwrap(); fs::write(src_dir.join(\"a.txt\"), b\"src-content\").unwrap(); let sensitive = scratch.path().join(\"sensitive\"); fs::create_dir(&sensitive).unwrap(); fs::write(sensitive.join(\"secret.txt\"), b\"top-secret\").unwrap(); let src_link = scratch.path().join(\"src_link\"); std::os::unix::fs::symlink(&sensitive, &src_link).unwrap();` — then `let dst = scratch.path().join(\"snapshot\"); let kind = snapshot(&src_link, &dst).unwrap();` — assert `kind == SnapshotKind::Clonefile`, then assert `fs::read(dst.join(\"secret.txt\")).unwrap() == b\"top-secret\"` and `fs::symlink_metadata(&dst).unwrap().file_type().is_symlink() == false` — today both hold (the test demonstrates the unsafe behaviour). Post-fix with the precheck: `snapshot(&src_link, &dst)` returns `Err(io::Error { kind: ErrorKind::InvalidInput, .. })` OR `fs::symlink_metadata(&dst).unwrap().file_type().is_symlink() == true` AND `fs::read_link(&dst).unwrap() == sensitive`. End-to-end repro: pair with #44's allow_write reproducer plus a runtime symlink swap (atomic rename of `src_link` between `apply_snapshot_from`'s `src.exists()` check at mod.rs:36 and the clonefile call inside `workspace::snapshot`) — surfaces the additional TOCTOU window."
}

