record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 485,
  "cap": "DOS_COMMENT_SUPPRESSION",
  "endpoint": "nyctos pr-comment (find_existing_comment + comment_owned_by_known_bot pair)",
  "rationale": "comment_owned_by_known_bot (pr_comment.rs:485-497) returns `true` for ANY comment whose author satisfies: (a) `performed_via_github_app.slug` is non-empty, OR (b) `user.type == \"Bot\"`, OR (c) `user.login` ends with `[bot]`. find_existing_comment (pr_comment.rs:504-543) iterates PR comments in GitHub's listing order (oldest first by default for the issues/comments endpoint) and returns the FIRST comment whose body contains the marker `<!-- nyctos:pr-comment v1 -->` AND that passes the bot-author check (pr_comment.rs:529-534). No verification that the comment was authored by THIS app/token. Any external bot identity that can comment on the PR — a tiny GitHub App the attacker installs on their fork, `dependabot[bot]`, any third-party CI bot subscribed to the repo's events, or even just a personal account on a self-hosted GHE with a `[bot]`-suffixed username — can drop a comment containing the literal marker string and lock nyctos's PATCH target onto that foreign comment. PATCH `/repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues/comments/{id}` requires the actor to OWN the comment; GitHub returns 403 because the foreign bot's app id ≠ the GITHUB_TOKEN's app id. `update_comment` (pr_comment.rs:561-576) surfaces `PrCommentError::GitHub(\"update comment returned 403\")`, the CLI returns exit code 1 (main.rs:1577), the CI step turns red, and the PR carries no nyctos summary AT ALL — the attacker has silenced the confirmed-finding surface for the lifetime of that PR (or until the foreign comment is manually deleted). Note: the doc comment at pr_comment.rs:478-484 explicitly anticipates the 403 outcome — 'A non-bot author cannot have written the agent's marker legitimately, so picking up its id would trigger a 403 on update and silence the agent on that PR' — but the implementation defends only against NON-bot authors, leaving the BOT-author case wide open. The marker is a public hardcoded constant (pr_comment.rs:23), so the attacker can read it from the open-source repo and reproduce it exactly. Distinct from sentinel #8 (DOS via dispatcher saturation): that DoSes the scan trigger; this DoSes the *reporting* surface on a per-PR basis without touching the daemon. Static pass missed because the check looks like a defence — the bot-author filter — and the failure mode (403 + silenced comment) requires modelling the GH API's authorship-vs-actor split.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "From any GitHub App the attacker controls (slug suffix immaterial; `user.type==Bot` is set by GH for app installations) post a comment on the target PR with body: `<!-- nyctos:pr-comment v1 -->\\n(intentional first marker)`. On the next nyctos pr-comment run, observe stderr: `pr-comment: github api error: update comment returned 403`. The legitimate nyctos comment never lands on the PR. Mitigation: (1) bind the marker to the actor — embed the GH App id of the writing token inside the marker comment (`<!-- nyctos:pr-comment v1 app=<our-app-id> -->`) and match on the suffix; (2) on PATCH 403, fall through to POST a new comment rather than failing the step; (3) optionally require the matched comment's `user.login` to equal the token's own `viewer.login` via a pre-flight `/user` lookup, cached for the run."
}

