record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 182,
  "cap": "MARKDOWN_INJECTION",
  "endpoint": "build_comment_body (since_ref + run_id + ui_url render into the PR comment body)",
  "rationale": "build_comment_body wraps operator-/attacker-derived strings inside single-backtick markdown code spans without the `code_safe` fence-extension helper that the same function uses (correctly) for `repo`, `path`, `rule`, finding `id`, and chain ids. Three concrete sinks: (a) `format!(\"Diff base: `{}`.\\n\\n\", since)` at pr_comment.rs:183 — `report.since_ref` is the literal `--since-ref` CLI arg, which CI workflows commonly source from `${{ github.head_ref }}` / `${{ github.base_ref }}`. Branch names accept many printable characters (git's check-ref-format only forbids a narrow set: space, `~^:?*[\\\\`, leading `-`, trailing `.`, `..`, `@{`); a backtick is NOT in that forbidden set and survives `--end-of-options`-guarded git diff (main.rs:1503). A fork PR named `\\`x\\`-evil` breaks out of the inline code span and lets the attacker inject arbitrary markdown — HTML `<details>`/`<img src=tracker>` for exfil of the reviewer's IP+UA via GitHub's image-proxy bypass, or a fake `## nyctos: NO findings on this PR` heading that overwrites the real summary visually. (b) `format!(\"Run ID `{}`. ...\", report.run_id)` at pr_comment.rs:187 — run_id is daemon-generated and presumed UUID-shaped today, but the type is `String` (scan_report.rs:19) with no shape enforcement; any future writer that hands an attacker-shaped run id (e.g. an externally-triggered run whose source labels the run) inherits the injection. (c) `format!(\" - [open run]({}/runs/{})\", trim_url(url), report.run_id)` at pr_comment.rs:189 — `ui_url` is the `--ui-url` CLI flag; a `)` in ui_url (or in run_id flowing into the link target) closes the markdown link prematurely and the remainder of the line becomes raw markdown — an `<img src=x onerror=…>` payload after the closing `)` renders on PR view. trim_url only strips trailing `/` (pr_comment.rs:331) and does NOT escape link-grammar metacharacters. Same workflow-interpolation realism as (a): `--ui-url ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.ref }}` in a misconfigured action. The `code_safe` helper (pr_comment.rs:311-329) is the right primitive — it picks a fence length > any backtick run in the input AND space-pads when the input starts/ends with a backtick — but it is not applied to since_ref, run_id, or ui_url. Static pass missed because the bug is heterogeneity (the same function correctly escapes 5 fields and skips 3) rather than absence (no escaping at all); a sink-coverage analyser sees 'this function escapes' and treats it as mitigated. Distinct from sentinel #13 (LOG_INJECTION on ShimReport.refusals) which targets sandbox audit, not the PR comment surface; the attacker model and the exfil channel are different (PR reviewers vs operator logs).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Fork the target repo; create a branch literally named `` `</code><details open><summary>nyctos: NO findings</summary> ``; open a PR against the upstream. In the upstream's `pull_request_target` workflow, nyctos scan runs with `--since-ref refs/heads/${{ github.head_ref }}` and writes report.json; nyctos pr-comment then renders `Diff base: ` then the branch backtick closes the inline code span and the rest of the branch name is interpreted as raw markdown, hiding the real findings table inside a collapsed <details>. Confirm by viewing the PR comment with reviewer eyes — the confirmed-finding count summary is correctly rendered (it sits ABOVE the since_ref line and uses code_safe-style numeric fields) but the per-file list under `### By file` is buried inside the attacker's <details> block. Mitigation: route since_ref / run_id / ui_url through `code_safe()` (for the code-span sinks) and through a URL-grammar sanitizer that rejects `)`/whitespace/control chars (for the link sink); add a property-style unit test that round-trips a corpus of '`', ')', '\\n', '<', '!' through build_comment_body and asserts the rendered output's markdown AST equals the expected AST."
}

