record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/chain_runner.rs",
  "line": 309,
  "cap": "REPLAY_ORACLE_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "ChainRunner::run with replay_stable_check=true (verifier replay-stability gate)",
  "rationale": "`execute_pass` opens each pass with `clear_sentinel(&run.workspace, &run.terminal_oracle)` (chain_runner.rs:309), which only `std::fs::remove_file`s the single `Oracle::SinkProbe.sentinel_path` (clear_sentinel at :477-485). Any OTHER file the pass-0 terminal step wrote to the parent workspace persists across passes. Session-0040 documented this trade-off in the module comment (:24-29: 'The terminal step deliberately runs against the parent workspace directly so its sink-probe sentinel write survives `Sandbox::wait`') but did not extend the between-pass reset to non-sentinel terminal-step side effects. Pass 1 then calls `run_step` for every non-terminal step with `opts.snapshot_from = Some(run.workspace.clone())` (:384), and the snapshot helper (`crate::workspace::snapshot`, workspace.rs:33) materialises a COW copy of the workspace AS IT IS AT SPAWN TIME — meaning pass-1 non-terminal steps see every pass-0 terminal-step artefact except `chain.sentinel`. An AI-generated terminal step can exploit this to game the `replay_stable` verdict three different ways: (a) `printf x > .pass0_marker; <real exploit>; printf x > chain.sentinel` — pass-1 non-terminal step's harness reads `.pass0_marker` and short-circuits to emit the expected `NYX_PREV_OUTPUT` regardless of whether the actual exploit chain still works on the now-mutated workspace state, deterministically matching pass-0's verdict; (b) the terminal step's non-sentinel writes can encode pass-0's full output state into the parent workspace (e.g. `printf '%s' \"$NYX_PREV_OUTPUT\" > .nyx_replay_cache`), then a pass-1 non-terminal step replays it directly into stdout, decoupling the replay-stability check from the chain's runtime behaviour entirely; (c) the symmetric *flake-suppression* direction — a chain that is genuinely non-deterministic (legitimate finding, flaky exploit) can be force-stabilised by the AI emitting marker-based determinism, causing the verifier to upgrade an Inconclusive/flaky chain to `replay_stable=Some(true)` and promote it through Quarantine on the basis of a forged stability signal. The semantic of `replay_stable` per the doc comment at :155-157 is 'second pass reaches the same verdict'; with a leaky parent workspace, that semantic degrades to 'the AI was willing to game it', which is the opposite of the property the verifier needs. Distinct from sentinel #21 (PATH_TRAVERSAL on Path::join) and #22 (SYMLINK_FOLLOW_TOCTOU) — those target the audit-trace writer, not the chain workspace. Distinct from sentinel #23/#24/#25 (file permissions / per-run subdir / audit-log truncate) — those target the traces tree, not chain replay. The new finding has no sibling in the existing 49-finding inventory because no prior session introduced a multi-pass workspace-shared oracle. Static pass missed it because the code is a single `remove_file` call that LOOKS like the right primitive (it does what the function name promises) — the bug is that the function's contract is narrower than the oracle's freshness requirement. Mitigation: between passes, either (1) `std::fs::remove_dir_all(&run.workspace)?; std::fs::create_dir_all(&run.workspace)?` plus re-materialise the chain's setup artefacts from `run.setup_inputs` (the cleanest fix; pairs with `with_snapshot_from(snapshot_root)` where `snapshot_root` is a separate read-only template, not the live workspace), or (2) capture a `WORKSPACE_DIGEST` (BLAKE3 of the workspace tree minus the sentinel) at start of pass 0, refuse to start pass 1 if the digest has changed, and on digest-mismatch report `replay_stable = Some(false)` with reason `WorkspaceDrift`, or (3) hard-code the terminal step to also run in a COW snapshot of the parent and arrange for the sink-probe to read its sentinel out of the snapshot path before teardown (requires a `Sandbox::keep_scratch_snapshot()` exit hook the API doesn't currently expose).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Construct a two-step chain where the terminal step writes BOTH the sentinel and a side-marker: invoke = `printf '%s' admin > chain.sentinel; printf 'pass0-was-here' > .nyx_replay_cache`. Construct the non-terminal step to read the marker and echo its contents as stdout when present: invoke = `if [ -f .nyx_replay_cache ]; then cat .nyx_replay_cache; else <real exploit chain>; fi`. Run with `ChainRunner { replay_stable_check: true, .. }`. Expected behavior: pass 0 hits the real-exploit branch, terminal writes sentinel+marker, verdict=Exploited. clear_sentinel removes the sentinel between passes. Pass 1 non-terminal step snapshot includes `.nyx_replay_cache`, harness short-circuits to emit `pass0-was-here`, terminal step (which gates on prev_output containing a specific token) is bypassed by AI-controlled chain logic, sentinel is re-written, pass 1 verdict=Exploited — `replay_stable=Some(true)` for a chain whose real exploit path never ran in pass 1. Confirm via `result.steps[1].stdout` in pass 1 being byte-identical to the marker contents."
}

