{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-ai/src/adapter/claude_code.rs",
  "line": 341,
  "cap": "BUDGET_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "ClaudeCodeAdapter::agent_loop (subprocess JSON-result event)",
  "rationale": "`cost_usd_micros = (c * 1_000_000.0).round() as i64` at claude_code.rs:341 casts an attacker- or bug-controlled f64 (`r.total_cost_usd` from the `claude --output-format stream-json` Result event) to i64 without validating finiteness or sign. Rust's `as` cast saturates on overflow (Inf -> i64::MAX, -Inf -> i64::MIN) but maps NaN -> 0. The budget pre-check at claude_code.rs:209-225 reads `spent_before` and compares against `cap`; on the post-call side this routine writes a per-call cost back to a budget ledger (TokenUsage path in runtime.rs). A compromised or buggy `claude` binary that emits `{\"total_cost_usd\": NaN}` records cost = 0 micros for the call -> unlimited subsequent calls regardless of true spend (NaN BYPASS). A negative cost (e.g. -1e18) saturates to i64::MIN -> arithmetic underflow on the subsequent `spent.saturating_add(cost)` path silently reduces apparent spend, also bypassing. No `is_finite()` / `>= 0.0` guard anywhere on the path. Static pass missed because the cast appears benign in isolation (`f64 as i64` is a common idiom) and the budget check itself is correct — the bug is that an untrusted external float reaches the cast without sanitization. Distinct from CRED_EXPOSURE / log-injection findings on the same file: this is a fiscal-integrity hole, not an auth or audit one. Compounds with line 238 env-leak (same call site) — a malicious claude binary loaded via PATH shadowing can both exfiltrate ANTHROPIC_API_KEY and report NaN cost to mask the burn.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Stage a shim binary `claude` on PATH ahead of the real one (or run the test fixture in tests/fixtures/claude_code/) that emits the stream-json event `{\"type\":\"result\",\"total_cost_usd\":NaN,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1000000,\"output_tokens\":1000000}}` followed by the normal completion frame. Drive ClaudeCodeAdapter::agent_loop with a tight cap (cap_usd_micros = 100). Observe that the in-process budget ledger advances by 0 micros per call rather than the true cost; loop 10x and confirm zero `BudgetExceeded` errors despite cumulative real cost > cap. Variant: emit `{\"total_cost_usd\": -1e18}` and confirm `cost_usd_micros` saturates to i64::MIN and that subsequent `saturating_add` underflows the running total. Mitigation: replace the as-cast with a checked path: reject when `!c.is_finite() || c < 0.0`, then `(c * 1_000_000.0).clamp(0.0, i64::MAX as f64) as i64`. Add a unit test in claude_code.rs that feeds NaN / -Inf / +Inf / -1.0 / 9.2e18 and asserts each produces either an explicit AiError or a safe-bounded i64 value."
}

