{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/store/run_repo_outcome.rs",
  "line": 53,
  "cap": "AUDIT_LOG_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "internal: store.run_repo_outcomes().upsert (called from persist_run_results at crates/nyctos/src/main.rs:1313)",
  "rationale": "`upsert` issues `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(run_id, repo) DO UPDATE SET outcome = excluded.outcome, reason = excluded.reason, elapsed_ms = excluded.elapsed_ms` (run_repo_outcome.rs:54-60). The migration documents the row as a per-run/per-repo *outcome history* observation captured at the moment the dispatcher finalised the bundle (0006_run_repo_outcomes.sql:11-13) — i.e. an audit signal an operator should later be able to inspect to see which repos timed out or failed for a historical run. The upsert path means a second persist_run_results call for the same (run_id, repo) silently overwrites the earlier outcome with no row-versioning, no append-only history, and no append to a sibling table. Concrete primitive: any dispatcher / scheduler retry path that re-emits the same RunBundle (e.g. operator-triggered re-scan with the same run_id, or a future per-repo retry-on-StaticPassTimeout flow) replaces an `Inconclusive { reason: StaticPassTimeout }` row with a `Success` row and the StaticPassTimeout evidence is unrecoverable. Same class as sentinel finding #25 (traces JSONL truncate(true) wipes prior audit on retry) but a structurally distinct sink — that one is filesystem-level, this one is SQLite-level, and the existing #25 mitigation does not patch this path. The `ON DELETE CASCADE` FK (0006_run_repo_outcomes.sql:26) also means deleting the parent run row erases the outcome history with no audit trail; combined with the upsert overwrite, two independent code paths can rewrite this audit observation. Static pass missed because the bug is a *semantic mismatch* between the table's stated purpose (historical observation) and the writer's chosen verb (idempotent upsert) — a static-data-flow tool sees parameterized SQL and clean Rust types and reports nothing. Mitigation options, pick one: (i) demote upsert to plain INSERT and surface the unique-constraint violation as a real error so the caller learns it tried to rewrite history; (ii) keep upsert but append the prior (outcome, reason, elapsed_ms, observed_at) to a sibling `run_repo_outcome_history` table inside the same transaction so the operator can recover the timeline; (iii) add an `observed_at INTEGER NOT NULL` column on the row and make the primary key `(run_id, repo, observed_at)` so retries record additional rows rather than overwriting; option (iii) preserves the original migration's `repo TEXT (no FK)` shape and adds the smallest schema delta.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Test rig: insert sample_run('run-a'); upsert `RunRepoOutcomeRecord { run_id: \"run-a\", repo: \"repo-1\", outcome: \"Inconclusive\", reason: Some(\"StaticPassTimeout\"), elapsed_ms: 60_000 }`; then upsert the same (run_id, repo) with `outcome: \"Success\", reason: None, elapsed_ms: 800`; then `list_for_run(\"run-a\")` and assert only one row, Success, with StaticPassTimeout gone. The existing test `upsert_overwrites_existing_row` (run_repo_outcome.rs:154-170) already confirms the overwrite — that test currently encodes the bug as the desired behaviour and should be renamed / inverted once the writer is fixed."
}

