record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/main.rs",
  "line": 1311,
  "cap": "AUDIT_BLOAT_AND_LEAK",
  "endpoint": "internal scan-driver path: every `nyctos scan` / POST /api/v1/projects/:id/scan that produces a per-repo RepoOutcome::Failed",
  "rationale": "`persist_run_results` (main.rs:1302-1361) writes `RepoOutcome::Failed(msg)` straight into `run_repo_outcomes.reason` via `Some(msg.clone())` at line 1311. The upstream constructor at nyctos-nyx/src/lane.rs:56 is `Err(other) => Err(ScanLaneError::Failed(other.to_string()))`, where `other` is `NyxError` and the `Display` impl for `NonZeroExit { status, stderr }` is `\"nyx exited with status {status}: {stderr}\"` (error.rs:21-22). `stderr` is the verbatim, unbounded stderr buffer of the embedded `nyx` subprocess — no truncation, no redaction, no allowlist. Three concrete failure modes drop out of the absence:\n\n(a) **DB bloat / amplification via hostile repo** — an attacker who controls a repo under scan (the model nyctos targets — operator points the daemon at a third-party repo for security review) can make the embedded `nyx` engine print arbitrary megabytes to stderr by crafting source files that crash its parser (recursive macros, pathological regex backtracking, oversized literal arrays — any of which surface in the parser's panic-with-context output). The resulting multi-MB string lands in a single SQLite TEXT cell. SQLite has no row-size limit short of the file-size limit; the cell can carry hundreds of MB. A single hostile repo per run + repeated `nyctos scan` invocations on the same project (operator retries, scheduled scans) blow up the SQLite db.sqlite indefinitely. The schema (0006 migration :19-30) has no `CHECK (length(reason) < N)` constraint and the writer has no truncation; no defence in depth.\n\n(b) **secrets in scanner stderr persisted unredacted** — `nyx` is the embedded engine wrapping a tokio::process::Command, and stderr commonly captures: (i) the resolved env block (when a panic dumps environ for diagnostics — current versions don't, but the *contract* the persist path codifies is 'trust nyx stderr forever'), (ii) absolute filesystem paths of the workspace snapshot (which, post sentinel #52 SANDBOX_ESCAPE finding on local.rs:228, may include attacker-controlled symlink targets like `/etc/passwd` that the scanner read into a diag's source_excerpt then printed to stderr on a panic), (iii) any operator-set passthrough env vars echoed by the embedded `nyx --debug` paths nyctos may invoke. The migration comment at 0006 :1-17 documents what `outcome` and `reason` are FOR — historical run rendering when the WebSocket is gone — but does not document that `reason` is operator-readable in perpetuity (until run delete cascades). Sentinel #35 covers the JSONL retention angle for AI traces; this is the parallel anti-pattern for scanner stderr.\n\n(c) **cross-tenant leakage on shared daemons** — a security service running nyctos against multiple customer repos under a single daemon: customer-X's hostile-repo-induced stderr (which can include lines from customer-X's source files quoted into nyx's diag context) is persisted in the same SQLite as customer-Y's runs; an operator with read access to either customer's runs sees both via direct SQLite read (no row-level auth on the store layer). The Failed-outcome rationale-string carries source-line excerpts the dispatcher never intended to keep beyond the WebSocket stream.\n\nDistinct from hook-appended #53 (AUDIT_LOG_INTEGRITY on upsert overwrite) — that one is about losing prior outcome rows on retry; this one is about what the surviving row carries. Distinct from sentinel #35 (agent_traces retention — different table, different lifecycle, different sensitive payload class). Static pass missed because the offending line is a single `.clone()` of a `String` field — taint analysis flags injection at SQL/HTML boundaries, not at audit-table boundaries, and SQLite's parameter binding (which the writer correctly uses at run_repo_outcome.rs:62-66) prevents SQL injection but does nothing about content-as-payload. The bug is the absence of a size/redaction policy on a freshly-introduced TEXT column whose contract is 'short label-class string' (Success/Inconclusive/scanner-crashed) but whose writer treats it as 'whatever the scanner said'. Schema-evolution + writer-contract drift class.\n\nFix (any one + (4) closes the primitive; recommend 1+2+4): (1) truncate at the writer: `let reason = msg.chars().take(2048).collect::<String>();` at main.rs:1311 with a sentinel suffix `… [truncated, full stderr in audit log <path>]` if truncation fired — bounded blast radius for a hostile repo; (2) redact known-secret patterns before persistence — a tiny allowlist regex sweep for `(?i)(token|key|password|secret|bearer)[=:]\\s*\\S+` and `sk-[A-Za-z0-9]{20,}` replacing the value with `<REDACTED>` keeps grep-discoverable secrets out of the persistent layer (the right place for the full text is the per-run JSONL audit, not the indexed SQLite table that the API surfaces); (3) add a `CHECK (length(reason) <= 4096)` constraint to the migration and bump CURRENT_SCHEMA_VERSION accordingly — defence in depth at the schema layer in case a future writer forgets the truncation; (4) document the column's contract in 0006_run_repo_outcomes.sql's leading comment: `reason` is for short label-class strings, never raw scanner stderr; route full stderr to the per-run trace JSONL via a new `nyctos_core::store::trace` writer path.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Black-box verifier seed: stage a hostile repo under tests/fixtures/repos/with_giant_stderr/ containing a source file the embedded nyx engine will fail to parse with a multi-MB diagnostic — e.g. one .py file with a single 8MB string literal full of unbalanced quotes, or a generated 4MB regex that triggers a stack-overflow panic in nyx's parser. Invoke `nyctos scan --project demo` (the CLI path that ultimately calls persist_run_results), then `sqlite3 <state>/db.sqlite \"SELECT length(reason) FROM run_repo_outcomes WHERE outcome='Failed'\"` — assert the length is > 1MB (the bug) and that the value contains verbatim source-file bytes (proving leak). Mitigation regression test: after applying fix (1), repeat and assert `length(reason) <= 2048` and that the suffix is the truncation sentinel. For the secret-redaction leg, plant a fixture with a literal `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-canary-12345` line that nyx's stderr echoes (e.g. a panic-with-context that dumps a parsed env-loading line), confirm the canary lands in the column (the bug), then after fix (2) confirm `<REDACTED>`. Real-world consequence: a multi-tenant security-service deployment with daily scheduled scans on hostile fuzz-corpus repos accumulates GB-scale `reason` columns inside SQLite within weeks, and the operator's debug query `SELECT reason FROM run_repo_outcomes` returns multi-MB rows that lock the API thread (sqlx + tokio: a slow row read pins the connection from the pool, starving concurrent /api/v1/runs queries)."
}

