{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/main.rs",
  "line": 1302,
  "cap": "TXN_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "internal scan-driver path: persist_run_results invoked from every `nyctos scan` / POST /api/v1/projects/:id/scan",
  "rationale": "`persist_run_results` (main.rs:1302-1361) issues three independent SQLite awaits per repo with NO enclosing transaction: `repos().set_last_scan(...)` at :1305, `run_repo_outcomes().upsert(...)` at :1313-1322, and (when Success) `findings().upsert(&rec)` at :1356 inside the inner diag loop. Each is a separate connection-pool round trip with its own implicit auto-commit. If the daemon crashes (SIGKILL, OOM, panic in another task, sqlx pool exhaustion mid-loop) or if any single await fails with a transient error (`StoreError::Sqlx(...)`), the function returns Err immediately via `?` and leaves a **mixed-write partial-state** in the database that no other code path reconciles. Four concrete inconsistency states drop out:\n\n(a) **set_last_scan succeeded, upsert failed** — `repos.last_scan_run_id` points at a run id that has no row in `run_repo_outcomes` for this repo. The historical-run renderer (the migration 0006's stated purpose at :1-10) queries by run_id; for this repo it returns empty, but the *repos* table still claims the repo was last scanned in this run. The Repo detail UI shows 'last scanned: 2026-05-21' but the run-detail UI shows no outcome row — operator concludes the repo was skipped, or that the scanner silently completed without producing any signal. Either misreads the system state.\n\n(b) **upsert succeeded, findings loop failed on the 3rd diag of 10** — for a Success-outcome repo, the run_repo_outcomes row records `outcome=Success, reason=NULL, elapsed_ms=...` (a confident claim that the scan completed successfully) while only 2 of 10 findings landed in the `findings` table. The run-detail UI shows 'Success, 2 findings' instead of 'Success, 10 findings'. The 8 missing findings have no reconciliation path — `persist_run_results` is single-shot per run, no retry helper exists, no janitor compares run_findings rowcount to scanner output. Detection failure: the highest-severity diag of the 10 may have been one of the missing 8, and the operator never sees it.\n\n(c) **mid-loop crash between repos** — for a multi-repo project, `persist_run_results` iterates `bundle.per_repo` (main.rs:1304) sequentially with one repo's three awaits between the next repo's three awaits. A daemon kill between repo A's diag-loop finish and repo B's `set_last_scan` start leaves: A fully persisted, B with no `run_repo_outcomes` row AND no `findings` rows AND `repos.last_scan_run_id` still pointing at the PRIOR run. The dispatcher's RunEvent stream emitted `RepoFinished` for B (run/mod.rs:477-485) before persist_run_results ever ran (the bundle is fully assembled by RunDispatcher before persist_run_results sees it), so the WebSocket consumer thinks B's outcome was delivered, but the DB has no record of it.\n\n(d) **interaction with sentinel #35 (DATA_RETENTION on agent_traces)** — if persist_run_results fails after run_repo_outcomes.upsert but before findings.upsert for a Success run, and the operator later 'deletes the broken run', the run_repo_outcomes FK cascade fires (0006 :26) and the outcome row is gone, but any agent_traces written during the run (which has no FK to runs — #35) persists. The audit trail of 'something happened on this run, but findings are missing' is **erased**; the AI-call trail is **retained**. Inverse forensics direction.\n\nThe `Store` impl exposes a `pool: SqlitePool` (mod.rs:~30 area) but `persist_run_results` only uses the per-table accessors; sqlx supports `pool.begin().await?` returning a `Transaction` that can be threaded through each store helper if they accepted an `&mut Transaction<Sqlite>` instead of `&SqlitePool`. The fix is shape-changing (the store helpers currently take `&'a SqlitePool` per run_repo_outcome.rs:43 / repo.rs / finding.rs) but the **persist boundary** is the natural transaction boundary — every other writer in nyctos-core hits a single table at a time, but `persist_run_results` is precisely the cross-table coordinator that needs the unit of work.\n\nStatic pass missed because each individual `.await?` is correct in isolation (well-formed query, bound parameters, error propagation). The bug is in the call-site composition — no static rule fires on 'multiple writes to related tables in a function that does not call .begin()'. Cross-cutting transaction-discipline class catch. Distinct from sentinel #28 (apply_chain_outcome non-transactional partial writes — different writer, chain table, different schema) and #29 (PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY on COALESCE asymmetry).\n\nFix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) refactor `persist_run_results` to begin a transaction at entry, thread `&mut Transaction<Sqlite>` through new variants of `set_last_scan` / `upsert` / findings::upsert that take the txn, commit at end — atomic per-run persist; (2) lighter-touch: wrap the bundle.per_repo loop in `sqlx::query(\"BEGIN IMMEDIATE\").execute(...).await?; ... sqlx::query(\"COMMIT\").execute(...).await?;` with COMMIT in a guard struct whose Drop impl runs a synchronous rollback on unwind — coarser but no signature churn; (3) add a regression test that uses a `sqlx` fail-injection (or a custom SqlitePool wrapper that fails the Nth await) to drive `persist_run_results` to mid-loop failure, then asserts the post-condition: either ALL three writes for repo A landed, or NONE — currently fails (the test would observe set_last_scan landed but upsert did not); (4) extend the migration 0006 with a CHECK that `repos.last_scan_run_id` correlates with a matching run_repo_outcomes row — defence in depth, but cross-table CHECKs in SQLite require triggers, so this leg is heavier.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (rust test in crates/nyctos/tests/scan_cli.rs as a sibling to the new outcome assertion at :92-108): construct a Store whose SqlitePool is wrapped in a test double that injects an `io::Error` on the Nth executed statement, drive `persist_run_results` with a single-repo bundle and `outcome=RepoOutcome::Success(vec![diag1, diag2, diag3])` and N=2 (so set_last_scan + upsert succeed, the first finding insert fails); assert either (a) `runs[0]` rolls back and the DB shows no row in run_repo_outcomes for this run (the txn-fix path), or (b) currently — the bug — `set_last_scan` and `run_repo_outcomes.upsert` landed but `findings` has 0 of 3 rows. Black-box repro on a real daemon: SIGKILL the daemon during a 50-repo scheduled scan (after roughly N seconds of dispatching) and afterwards `sqlite3 <state>/db.sqlite \"SELECT repo FROM repos r WHERE r.last_scan_run_id = '<run>' AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM run_repo_outcomes o WHERE o.run_id = r.last_scan_run_id AND o.repo = r.name)\"` — every row returned is a half-persisted repo (the bug)."
}

