record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/migrations/0006_run_repo_outcomes.sql",
  "line": 22,
  "cap": "PROVENANCE_COLLISION",
  "endpoint": "internal store writer: RunRepoOutcomeStore::upsert (run_repo_outcome.rs:53) called from main.rs:1313 (today's writer) and any future per-pass writer keyed on (run_id, repo)",
  "rationale": "Migration 0006 declares `PRIMARY KEY (run_id, repo)` (sql:25) and the only writer issues `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(run_id, repo) DO UPDATE SET outcome = excluded.outcome, reason = excluded.reason, elapsed_ms = excluded.elapsed_ms` (run_repo_outcome.rs:55-60). Today this is correct because main.rs:1313 is the sole writer and writes once per (run_id, repo) tuple. But Nyctos is moving toward a **multi-pass** model — sentinel #45 (chain_runner.rs replay-stable concept), the `prompt_version` field on findings, and the ai_pipeline.rs hand-off all assume a static pass followed by an AI exploration / chain-replay pass. The migration's leading comment at sql:1-17 documents only the static-pass writer's needs; it does not pin which pass owns the row, and the schema does not carry a `pass` discriminator column. Three forward-compatibility primitives drop out:\n\n(a) **future chain-lane writer silently overwrites static-pass outcome** — a near-term writer that records the chain-replay verdict per repo (Inconclusive when the chain runner finishes with `ChainStepFailed { which }`, Failed on sandbox error, Success on confirmed exploit) will naturally key on (run_id, repo) since those are the only stable identifiers per scan unit. The existing UPSERT silently overwrites the static-pass row's `outcome`, `reason`, `elapsed_ms`. The operator opening the historical run sees the chain-pass outcome (which may be `Inconclusive` because the chain runner could not reproduce the static diag's flow) and concludes the repo failed — when in reality the static pass produced 12 high-severity findings that landed in the `findings` table. The findings table is correct; the outcome row is wrong. Detection regression: operators triage by outcome (which the UI surfaces prominently), so a Success static pass overwritten by an Inconclusive chain pass causes the operator to deprioritise a repo with 12 real findings. Compounds with hook-appended #53 (which already noted retry-overwriting-history on the same UPSERT verb — same primitive, different motivating scenario; the two findings together argue for the same schema fix).\n\n(b) **outcome column has no CHECK enum constraint** — `outcome TEXT NOT NULL` (sql:22) with no `CHECK (outcome IN ('Success','Inconclusive','Failed'))`. The `RepoOutcomeLabel::as_str` (run_repo_outcome.rs:24-30) produces exactly those three strings, but the column accepts ANYTHING a future writer or a careless test fixture inserts. The reader (`list_for_run` at :77-95, `get` at :104-120) returns `outcome: String` — type erasure at the boundary. A typo `Suceeded` (single c) lands silently. The migration comment justifies `repo TEXT` having no FK at sql:14-17 ('tolerates ad-hoc workspace names') but offers no justification for the analogous looseness on `outcome` — the dispatcher's enum has three values, period. The intent is enum-discrete; the schema is enum-non-binding. Sentinel #34 has the same shape on `agent_traces.task_kind` — same bug class, different table; fixing one without the other leaves the schema policy inconsistent.\n\n(c) **idx_run_repo_outcomes_outcome (sql:30) is a low-cardinality index that misleads the operator** — the index on a 3-value enum-encoded-as-text is by definition a tiny B-tree; it's there so the dispatcher / future janitor can `SELECT ... WHERE outcome = 'Failed'`. But the column being TEXT-unbounded means the index also indexes the garbage strings from (b), conflating typo'd 'Suceeded' rows with legitimate 'Success' rows under nothing (separate B-tree buckets). The presence of the index signals to a future query author 'this is a closed enum that's safe to filter on'; the schema does not enforce that signal.\n\nThe new file's `RepoOutcomeLabel` enum (run_repo_outcome.rs:16-21) is a `#[derive(...)]` Rust-only contract; it has no DB-side mirror. Static pass missed because the bug is a **future-facing schema design hole** — the existing single-writer is correct, no SQL injection, no concurrency bug today. A reviewer reading the migration in isolation can't see the second writer that hasn't been written yet; a reviewer reading the writer in isolation can't see that the PK shape will lock the pass discriminator out forever. Cross-file + cross-time review-class catch.\n\nFix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+2+3): (1) extend the PK to `(run_id, repo, pass)` where `pass TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Static'` — preserves today's writer (defaults Static), gives future chain/AI writers a distinct row, and the historical-run renderer aggregates by `MAX(elapsed_ms)` or surfaces per-pass detail; alternative shape per hook-appended #53's suggestion (iii): `observed_at INTEGER NOT NULL` discriminator achieves the same multi-row property and additionally addresses the retry-overwrite case in the same migration; (2) bind the `outcome` column with `CHECK (outcome IN ('Success','Inconclusive','Failed'))` in the same migration; (3) extend the reader API to return a typed enum: `pub async fn list_for_run(...) -> Result<Vec<RepoOutcomeLabel>, StoreError>` parsing the column via `RepoOutcomeLabel::from_str` and returning `StoreError::Schema` on any value outside the allowlist — turns 'silent garbage row' into 'visible deserialise failure'; (4) document the contract in run_repo_outcome.rs's module doc (currently at :1-6) and in the migration leading comment explicitly: 'one row per (run_id, repo, pass), outcome is the closed enum Success | Inconclusive | Failed, reason is a short label-class string (see also sentinel #54), elapsed_ms is non-negative wall-clock'.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed for (b) — outcome enum non-binding: in `crates/nyctos-core/src/store/run_repo_outcome.rs` tests after `upsert_overwrites_existing_row`, add: `let mut bad = sample_outcome(\"run-a\", \"repo-x\"); bad.outcome = \"Suceeded\".to_string(); s.run_repo_outcomes().upsert(&bad).await.expect(\"upsert\"); let got = s.run_repo_outcomes().get(\"run-a\", \"repo-x\").await.expect(\"get\").expect(\"row\"); assert_eq!(got.outcome, \"Suceeded\");` — currently passes (the bug); after CHECK constraint fix it fails with sqlx Constraint violation. Verifier seed for (a) — multi-pass overwrite: simulate a future chain-pass writer by directly issuing `s.run_repo_outcomes().upsert(&RunRepoOutcomeRecord { run_id: \"run-a\".into(), repo: \"repo-1\".into(), outcome: \"Inconclusive\".into(), reason: Some(\"ChainStepFailed{which:1}\".into()), elapsed_ms: 60_000 })` AFTER a Success outcome was written for the same (run_id, repo); read back and assert the Success is gone (the bug); after PK-extension fix, both rows coexist and the reader can return them per-pass. Real-world consequence: when the chain-replay pass lands in a near-term PR keyed on (run_id, repo), the upgrade silently corrupts the historical record of every repo that had a static-pass Success — the static-pass `findings` rows are still in the DB but the outcome column claims Inconclusive, so the run-detail UI shows '12 findings, but the repo was inconclusive' — an internally contradictory state the operator has to manually reconcile."
}

