{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1957,
  "cap": "SCOPE_FILTER_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/events?run_id=<x> (events_ws WebSocket subscription)",
  "rationale": "Uncommitted diff on router.rs:2167-2354 turns `POST /findings/:id/replay` into a *broadcaster* — every replay frame (ReplayStarted/Stdout/Stderr/Error/Finished) is now also pushed onto the global `s.events` broadcast::Sender as `AgentEvent::Repro { data: ReproEvent::* }` (nyctos-types/event.rs:230-266, new variants). The matching subscriber side is `events_ws` at router.rs:1867 which filters via `run_matches` at router.rs:1957. That filter only narrows when the event is `AgentEvent::Run { data }` (lines 1959-1973) and unconditionally `return true` for every other variant (line 1975 `else { true }`). Consequence: a WS subscriber that opened `/api/v1/events?run_id=run-A` to scope to *its* run still receives the Repro frames for replays of findings belonging to runs B, C, D, … — including the bundle path (which contains the operator's home-dir state path, see new ReplayStarted.bundle_path at event.rs:240) and the raw stdout/stderr of the bash replay (which re-runs the captured repro template — secrets, env, payload strings flow verbatim through ReplayStdout.line / ReplayStderr.line). The ReproEvent struct itself does carry `finding_id` so the *frontend* could filter, but the broadcast happens upstream and `run_matches` is the only server-side gate. The replay endpoint runs each repro as `bash -c <template>` (router.rs:2185-2200) inside the daemon's process — outputs are not redacted before being put on the global bus. Two breakages drop out:\n\n(a) **cross-run information leak** — operator A subscribed to their dashboard's `?run_id=run-A` filter watches operator B's replay-of-findings stream in real time. Even single-tenant nyctos deployments routinely have multiple operator browser tabs open for different runs; the run_id query param exists precisely so each tab gets only its own run's events (commit history shows it was added to stop cross-run heartbeat noise on the run-detail UI). The new Repro broadcast invalidates that scoping for an entire event family.\n\n(b) **filter looks correct in the test** — the newly added test `replay_endpoint_broadcasts_repro_events_for_websocket_subscribers` at tests/api.rs:1622-1716 uses `broadcast::channel::<AgentEvent>(64)` with a single subscriber and never sends a `run_id` filter, so the missing scoping is invisible at the test layer. Without an additional assertion that `run_matches(AgentEvent::Repro{..}, Some(\"other-run\"))` returns `false`, the regression cannot be caught by CI on this change.\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is a **policy boundary** that lives across two crates and one helper function: the new variant landed in nyctos-types, the writer landed in router.rs:2167-2354, the filter that needs updating is at router.rs:1957, and the per-variant identifier needed to filter (finding_id) sits on ReproEvent and *not* on AgentEvent — so the filter helper has no obvious place to switch on it without a store lookup (`findings::get(finding_id) -> run_id`). Cross-file design-discipline catch.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #11/#12 (events_ws auth-layer bypass via token-in-query) — that's a different boundary; here the auth is correct (auth_layer applies to /events), but post-auth filtering is the gap. Compounds with sentinel #29 (run_id propagation gaps in chain-finding cross-link): both findings describe Repro/Chain events whose `run_id` is not the source of truth the filter sees.\n\nFix (any one closes; recommend 1+2): (1) lift `run_id` onto `ReproEvent` itself (the replay handler at router.rs:2167 already has `finding.run_id` in scope via `s.store.findings().get(&id).await?.run_id`) and extend `run_matches` to match on `AgentEvent::Repro { data }` by deconstructing the new field — small schema add, deterministic filter; (2) alternative: pass `run_id` *and* `finding_id` filters on the WS query (`?run_id=A&finding_id=F`) and make `run_matches` consult both — preserves the `ReproEvent { finding_id }` shape but introduces a second filter dimension; (3) defence-in-depth: change `run_matches` to default-deny on unknown event families (`AgentEvent::Repro | AgentEvent::Sandbox | AgentEvent::Ai | AgentEvent::Finding | AgentEvent::Budget | AgentEvent::Quarantine if want.is_some() => false`) — forces every new event family added in the future to teach the filter how to scope itself, preventing the same class of bug on the next variant. (3) is the long-term shape change.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (add as a `#[tokio::test]` in nyctos-api/tests/api.rs next to the new replay-broadcast test): build two findings — finding_a on run_id=run-A, finding_b on run_id=run-B. Spawn the router, open a `tokio::sync::broadcast::Receiver` and call `run_matches(&AgentEvent::Repro { data: ReproEvent::ReplayStdout { finding_id: \"finding_b\".into(), line: \"leak\".into() } }, Some(\"run-A\"))` — currently returns `true` (the bug); after fix returns `false`. End-to-end black-box repro: spin two `wscat -c \"ws://127.0.0.1:<port>/api/v1/events?run_id=run-A\"` connections with the same bearer token, then `POST /findings/<finding_b's id>/replay` and observe the run-A connection receives stdout from finding_b's replay — should not. Severity escalates if the repro template includes secrets sourced from the original finding's environment (which it can, since the bundle was assembled from operator-supplied repro setup commands)."
}

