{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 2244,
  "cap": "INFO_DISCLOSURE",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/findings/:id/replay → AgentEvent::Repro broadcast → every WS subscriber on /api/v1/events",
  "rationale": "The diff at router.rs:2244-2295 lifts every `stdout_lines.next_line()` and `stderr_lines.next_line()` result of the replay subprocess and re-emits it verbatim as `ReproEvent::ReplayStdout { finding_id, line }` / `ReproEvent::ReplayStderr { finding_id, line }` via `s.events.send(...)`. The original SSE-only handler delivered those bytes only to the HTTP caller who initiated the replay (request-scoped — the operator already had the bearer token + actively requested the finding). The new code path additionally pushes the same bytes onto the **global** `broadcast::Sender<AgentEvent>` (capacity 256 in production at crates/nyctos/src/main.rs:954; 16 on the CLI scan path at :455). Every authenticated WS client on `/api/v1/events` — regardless of run_id, regardless of finding_id, regardless of whether that client has any business knowing the replay was triggered — now receives:\n\n(a) the absolute filesystem path of the bundle (`ReplayStarted.bundle_path`, populated from `bundle_path.display().to_string()` at router.rs:2174, which is `s.state_bundles_dir.join(<finding_id>)/<sha-or-uuid>.tar` per `create_repro_bundle` at :2018-2105) — leaks the operator's `$HOME` and the on-disk layout of the state-dir;\n\n(b) every line of stdout the replay bash script writes — for findings whose repro template hits a SQL injection, this is the *vulnerable SQL with the injected payload*; for findings whose template hits a credential-handling path, this is whatever the template printed to stdout (commonly the leaked secret itself, since the whole point of a repro is to demonstrate the disclosure); for shell-command-injection repros, this includes the attacker-controlled command output;\n\n(c) every line of stderr — Rust panic backtraces (which leak source file paths and line numbers from the operator's build), `sqlite3` lock errors that reveal the state-dir path, `cargo` invocations that leak the build cache layout, env-variable dump traces from poorly-isolated repro templates.\n\nThis content was already in the SSE stream — but the SSE stream is **request-scoped** to the caller that POSTed the replay (one operator, one stream). The new broadcast turns request-scoped data into pub-sub data with a much wider audience (every connected dashboard, every CI tail-the-events scraper, every long-lived `wscat` session opened for debugging). Compounded by sentinel-finding above (#57: SCOPE_FILTER_BYPASS) — even a subscriber that *tried* to scope to a single run_id sees all replay output globally. The broadcast also has no per-line size cap (`bytes::next_line` returns whatever the child wrote before \\n) — a single replay that produces a 4MB single line floods every subscriber's send queue, escalating into the next finding (DoS). Replay timeout is 60s wall-clock at router.rs:2227-2233 — at the kernel's typical pipe-write rate that is hundreds of MB of broadcast traffic, multiplied by N subscribers, fan-out unbounded.\n\nStatic pass missed because the change *looks* like a faithful mirror of the SSE frames (the comment on the new ReproEvent in event.rs:230-236 literally says 'mirrors the SSE frames'). The mirror is *bytes-faithful* but *audience-unfaithful*: the SSE caller already authenticated for this finding-id with a POST; the WS subscriber authenticated only for /events globally. A defender reading the diff sees identical String fields and assumes identical surface; the actual surface is N× larger and reaches subscribers who never asked for this finding.\n\nDistinct from #57 (which is the missing filter); this finding is that the content itself is sensitive and should be redacted/gated even with the filter fixed. Compounds with sentinel #34 (agent_traces missing run scope) — same class of pattern: subprocess output flowed out of its original audience boundary.\n\nFix (any one helps; (1)+(2) recommended): (1) **do not broadcast stdout/stderr lines at all** — broadcast only the lifecycle events (Started / Finished / Error). The body of the replay should remain SSE-only since the SSE caller is the one who needs the live tail; subscribers that want post-mortem access can fetch a stored transcript via a separate authenticated `GET /findings/:id/replay/:run_id/log` endpoint that re-checks per-finding ACL; (2) if (1) is unacceptable for the UX (e.g. you want operators to keep watching after they navigate away), gate the broadcast on a per-WS subscription opt-in: `?include_repro=1` and require a separate role-check before flipping it on, plus per-line redaction (truncate >4KB lines, scrub against the daemon's known-secrets allowlist used by sentinel-finding-redaction in the AI-output path); (3) at minimum truncate `ReplayStdout.line` / `ReplayStderr.line` to a hard cap (the per-line cap inherits from `tokio::io::BufReader::next_line` which is unbounded). Cap to e.g. 8KB and replace overflow with a `…(truncated)` marker; (4) replace `bundle_path: String` (absolute path) with `bundle_id: String` (the sha or uuid component) so subscribers can correlate without leaking on-disk layout — operator-facing UI never needs the absolute path, only the bundle's stable identifier.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: extend the new test `replay_endpoint_broadcasts_repro_events_for_websocket_subscribers` (tests/api.rs:1622-1716) — before invoking POST /replay, write the repro template to include a fake secret (e.g. `echo \"NYX_TEST_LEAK=$(cat <bundle_dir>/sentinel-marker)\"` where sentinel-marker is a per-test random token written outside the bundle root and then mounted in via env). Open a second WS subscriber on `/api/v1/events?run_id=other-run`. After the POST, assert that the second subscriber received zero `ReplayStdout` frames carrying the sentinel-marker — currently fails (subscriber receives every stdout line because of #57 + this finding's broadcast scope). After fix (1) the assertion passes because no stdout frames are broadcast at all. Black-box repro on a running daemon: `wscat -c \"ws://localhost:<port>/api/v1/events?run_id=zzz\" -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\"` in one terminal, then `curl -X POST -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" \"http://localhost:<port>/api/v1/findings/<any-fid>/replay\"` in another — every line the repro template prints lands in the first terminal's WS stream despite the `?run_id=zzz` scoping."
}

