record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 2247,
  "cap": "BROADCAST_FLOOD_DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/findings/:id/replay (effect on every other subscriber on /api/v1/events)",
  "rationale": "Production `s.events` is a `broadcast::channel::<AgentEvent>(256)` (crates/nyctos/src/main.rs:954) — the CLI scan path at :455 is even smaller at 16. Tokio's broadcast channel holds at most `cap` in-flight items per receiver; a slow receiver triggers `RecvError::Lagged(skipped)` (handled at router.rs:1941-1948 by sending a single Lagged warning) and silently *drops* events the slow receiver hadn't yet pulled. The new diff at router.rs:2244-2295 emits one broadcast send per stdout line and one per stderr line of the replay subprocess, with no rate limiting, no per-frame size cap, and no coalescing. The replay is `bash -c <template>` (router.rs:2185) running for up to `REPLAY_WALL_CLOCK_TIMEOUT_SECS` (60s at router.rs:2227). A repro template that prints rapidly — `yes | head -n 100000` or any normal verbose CLI tool — produces tens of thousands of ReplayStdout frames per second. Three concrete failure modes drop out:\n\n(a) **subscriber starvation cascade** — a single replay producing N>256 stdout lines faster than the slowest WS subscriber can drain the channel causes every other subscriber's queue to overflow. Each victim receives `Lagged(skipped)` (router.rs:1941) and *loses the events between snapshot and now* — for the run-detail UI those losses are `RunEvent::RepoFinished`, `FindingEvent::FindingPersisted`, etc. The UI's optimistic-state machine (per the comment at router.rs:1872-1876 about idempotent folds) re-converges on the next event of the same key, but **terminal events** (RunFinished, RepoFinished) are emitted once per key per run — once dropped, the operator's dashboard sticks forever showing 'Run-A still running' even though the run finished, until the operator manually refreshes. Detection regression: the operator does not realise a run finished, and does not triage the resulting findings.\n\n(b) **self-inflicted on the replay's own SSE caller** — `handle_events_ws` is single-threaded per socket (router.rs:1887-1955) but the replay handler is *also* yielding SSE frames to the original POST caller while pushing the same content onto the broadcast. The replay handler does `let _ = events.send(...)` then `yield Ok(SseEvent::...)` in sequence — the send-then-yield ordering means if the broadcast send blocks awaiting capacity (it doesn't — broadcast::send is non-blocking) — wait — broadcast::send is non-blocking but the *receiver* falls behind; the receiver's lag is bounded by the channel cap, so the slowest receiver effectively determines whether every other receiver gets Lagged. Even though `send` returns immediately, the **cap is shared across all receivers** — a single backed-up receiver pushes the head index forward and the cap is consumed by old, unread events. Net effect: one slow subscriber causes Lagged on all the others.\n\n(c) **DoS amplification from any caller who can POST replay** — `auth_layer` at router.rs:101 admits any caller with the bearer token to POST /findings/:id/replay. A compromised or curious operator account can trigger replay-spam by submitting a finding whose repro template prints aggressively, knocking every dashboard offline (lost terminal events per (a)). The replay endpoint enforces sha-256 bundle integrity (router.rs:2125-2160 via sentinel-#5 ensure_bundle_path_inside_root path) but does not gate on *content* — a hostile bundle that prints 1GB to stdout in 60s is structurally identical to a benign one.\n\nThe pre-diff design did not have this property: replay output flowed only on the SSE channel back to the original caller, a unicast pipe with its own backpressure semantics (axum's SSE body is per-connection). Adding the broadcast turns a unicast workload into a multicast amplifier without adding the per-frame rate cap that multicast requires.\n\nStatic pass missed because each individual `events.send(...)` call is well-formed and well-typed; the bug is the *aggregate rate* on a shared bounded channel — a class of bug no static rule will fire on. Cross-cutting capacity-discipline catch.\n\nDistinct from #57/#58: #57 is missing per-event filtering, #58 is content sensitivity, this one is throughput/capacity. All three should be fixed; (1) below also mitigates #58.\n\nFix (any one helps; (1) is the minimal, (3) is the long-term shape): (1) **drop stdout/stderr from the broadcast entirely** — only broadcast lifecycle events (Started / Finished / Error). The SSE stream remains the line-by-line surface. This is also the fix recommended for #58 — single change closes two findings; (2) coalesce: buffer stdout/stderr lines on a per-finding aside-buffer and emit at most one `ReplayProgress { lines_seen, last_line_excerpt }` event per second per replay — bounds the broadcast rate independent of replay throughput; (3) bump the channel capacity to a much larger number (e.g. 4096) and switch slow consumers to a per-subscriber bounded mpsc forwarded by a per-WS task that drops on its own queue, not on the shared broadcast — turns Lagged from a global property into a per-subscriber property, isolating noisy replays from quiet runs.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (extend tests/api.rs:1622-1716): replace the test's repro-template setup with one that writes `for i in $(seq 1 5000); do echo \"line $i\"; done` (well under the 60s wall-clock but ~5000 broadcast sends in <2s). Spin a second subscriber on a *separate* WS connection that intentionally never calls `rx.recv()` for the first second — assert that real RunEvent::RepoFinished frames sent by an unrelated `s.events.send` after the replay still reach a *third* subscriber. Currently fails with `RecvError::Lagged` because the channel's shared cap is consumed by stdout frames; after fix (1) or (3) the third subscriber receives all RunEvent frames intact. Black-box repro: open two `wscat` subscribers, then POST a replay whose template runs `yes | head -n 100000`; observe the second subscriber receives one `{\"kind\":\"Lagged\",\"skipped\":N}` warning at router.rs:1942-1948 and *misses* the RunFinished event that would have closed out an unrelated run that completed during the replay window."
}

