record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 1527,
  "cap": "ATTACKER_CONTROLS_SCAN_SCOPE",
  "endpoint": "internal: walk_source_files driving NovelFindingDiscovery batch construction for every /api/v1/runs against an attacker-controlled repo",
  "rationale": "Uncommitted diff rewrites `walk_source_files` to use `ignore::WalkBuilder::new(root).standard_filters(true).hidden(true).parents(false).require_git(false)` (ai_pipeline.rs:1527-1535). `standard_filters(true)` per the `ignore` crate docs enables in-tree `.gitignore`, in-tree `.ignore`, AND `.git/info/exclude` parsing — even with `require_git(false)`, the walker reads `.git/info/exclude` whenever the `.git` directory is present (which it always is, since LocalRepo::snapshot at local.rs copies symlinks/dirs verbatim per sentinel #52 and ingest_git pipes through `git clone`). Net: every byte of the attacker-controlled repo's `.gitignore` / `.ignore` / `.git/info/exclude` is parsed as a positive-authority directive that the novel-discovery walker honours. The static nyx pass and the per-finding AI passes use other walkers (or operate over the diag list directly), so the asymmetry is sharper than just 'walker honours gitignore' — only the NovelFindingDiscovery surface narrows on the attacker's gitignore, while the static pass still sees the suppressed files. Three concrete primitives drop out:\n\n(a) **selective hiding of backdoor source from AI review** — an attacker who plants a backdoor in `src/utils/helper.py` (which static nyx might fire a generic taint warning on, or might not — many backdoors are designed to evade pattern matchers) adds `src/utils/helper.py` to `.gitignore` (or, more subtly, `.ignore` since that file does not appear in `git diff` output and reviewers rarely audit it). The static pass walks via its own crate-internal walker that has no `ignore::WalkBuilder` and still scans the file (so the operator sees a clean static-pass report if the static rules don't fire); the novel-discovery AI pass — the surface DESIGNED to catch what static missed — skips the file entirely. The post-scan report shows zero AI-side coverage of the backdoor with no warning that the file was suppressed.\n\n(b) **steering AI budget onto a single attacker-controlled poisoning file** — combined with finding #61 below, the attacker can `.gitignore` every legitimate file in a repo (`*.py`, `*.js`, `!evil.py`) so the walker emits exactly one file. The novel-discovery batches reduce to a single batch over evil.py; the AI burns its entire per-run budget reasoning about attacker-controlled content (which is exactly the prompt-injection vector the chain-lane sandbox is supposed to bound). The walker has no minimum-coverage assertion that would refuse to proceed when the gitignore eliminates most of the repo.\n\n(c) **`.git/info/exclude` is invisible to git diff / GitHub UI** — `.git/info/exclude` is per-clone, not under version control, but `ignore::WalkBuilder` with `standard_filters(true)` honours it. A repo whose clone tarball (the bundle delivered to nyctos via `LocalRepo::snapshot`) includes `.git/info/exclude` carries the suppression directives without ever appearing in any GitHub diff, PR review, or `git log`. Defender-side auditability gap: a security-review operator examining the repo before scanning sees nothing suspicious in tracked files; the suppression lives in an untracked file that nyctos faithfully honours.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #52 (SANDBOX_ESCAPE via copy_recursive symlinks — different file class, different sink) and sentinel #20 (PATH_TRAVERSAL via infer_lang_for_file — different traversal direction). The static pass missed this because the bug is a *trust-boundary mismatch* between (i) the `ignore` crate's documented semantics (operator-friendly: honour the repo's own filters), (ii) nyctos's threat model (attacker-controlled repo content), and (iii) the absence of a `.gitignore`-parser hardening at the workspace-boundary. There is no tainted-flow sink; the dataflow rule sees a well-formed walker.\n\nMitigations (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) replace `standard_filters(true)` with `standard_filters(false)` and re-enable only the operator-trusted defaults explicitly (`.git_global(true).git_ignore(false).git_exclude(false).ignore(false)`), so in-tree directives are NOT trusted; (2) keep the in-tree filters but log a per-run summary `walker: suppressed N paths via .gitignore / M via .ignore / K via .git/info/exclude` to the operator-visible event stream — operator can spot the case where a repo suppresses most of its own files; (3) at minimum, assert at walker entry that the resulting file count is at least 10% of the unfiltered file count (call the walker twice — once with filters off, once with filters on — and refuse to emit batches when the ratio collapses below the floor); (4) emit a quarantine row with `cap=SCAN_SCOPE_NARROWED` when any of `.gitignore`/`.ignore`/`.git/info/exclude` suppresses more than 50 unique files, so the operator triages whether the suppression is legitimate (e.g. a `vendor/` dir not in SKIP_DIRS) or hostile.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Hostile-repo recipe: `mkdir -p src && for i in $(seq 1 50); do echo 'def safe():\\n    pass' > src/file_$i.py; done && echo 'def backdoor(): __import__(\"os\").system(\"id\")' > evil.py && printf 'src/\\n' > .gitignore && git init -q && git add -A && git commit -qm init`. Operator runs `nyctos scan --project demo` against the clone. Verifier-side: assert the novel-discovery walker emits only `evil.py` (the static-pass walker emits all 51 files). Real-world consequence: AI budget reasoning about evil.py is 100% of the AI cost for the run, evil.py's content is operator-supplied prompt context that flows into the Anthropic API request body (compounds with sentinel #34's verifier_blob retention if a confirmed finding lands on evil.py). Regression test: extend the new `walk_source_files_respects_repo_gitignore` test at ai_pipeline.rs:4051-4072 with a `walk_source_files_warns_when_gitignore_suppresses_most_files` test that creates 100 files + a `.gitignore` listing 95 of them and asserts the walker either (a) refuses to proceed, (b) logs at warn-level, or (c) the caller in drive_novel_finding_pass surfaces a quarantine-class signal."
}

