record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/store/finding.rs",
  "line": 506,
  "cap": "PROMOTION_RATE_POISONING_LOOP",
  "endpoint": "internal: FindingStore::per_path_promotion_rate feeds priority_for boost in drive_novel_finding_pass (ai_pipeline.rs:1356-1369, :1581) on every subsequent /api/v1/runs",
  "rationale": "The new helper at finding.rs:499-525 computes a per-path AI-promotion rate from `findings` rows where `attack_provenance IN ('AiExploration','LlmSynthesised') AND status IN ('Open','Verified')`. The rate is fed back into `priority_for` via `PROMOTION_RATE_WEIGHT = 10.0` (ai_pipeline.rs:1259) — sized explicitly to outrank the strongest keyword hit (`route`/`controller`/`handler` at +6). The intent (documented in docs/ai-runtime.md:367-381) is that paths the verifier historically confirmed get more AI budget. The intent is operator-friendly; the security consequence is a feedback loop an attacker can drive. Three orthogonal primitives drop out:\n\n(a) **prompt-injection-driven path concentration** — an attacker who controls a repo under scan plants prompt-injection in source comments/strings that get the AI to emit an `LlmSynthesised` candidate for an attacker-chosen path (e.g. `src/evil.py`). If the verifier confirms the candidate (the verifier itself is a Claude-class agent — same prompt-injection surface; sentinel #34's verifier_blob exposes the verdict to the attacker who can observe `/api/v1/events` per #57/#58, so the attacker knows when their injection succeeds), the row lands at `status='Open' or 'Verified', attack_provenance='LlmSynthesised'`. Next run: `per_path_promotion_rate` returns `1.0/(1.0+5.0) = 0.167` for src/evil.py → +2 boost. After 10 confirmed AI-side findings on src/evil.py: `10/(10+5) = 0.667` → +7 boost (enough to outrank a plain keyword hit). After 50: `50/55 = 0.909` → +9 boost. The attacker need not have ANY of these be real vulns — the AI's confirmation under prompt-injection is sufficient, and the verifier echoes the AI's verdict back per the existing #28 vector. Result: the AI's per-run budget concentrates on attacker-chosen files run-over-run, starving genuine signal elsewhere in the repo.\n\n(b) **rate is repo-name-keyed, not project-keyed or commit-keyed** — the WHERE clause filters on `repo = ?` (finding.rs:510). Two different projects that happen to ingest a repo with the same name (`api`, `web`, `core`, `lib`) share a single promotion-rate table. An attacker who controls a single nyctos installation's repo named `api` can poison the rate map; if the operator later adds a legitimate `api` repo (different project, different URL, same name), the legitimate scan inherits the poisoned rates. Compounds sentinel #29 (cross-run repo leak) — same scoping gap, different sink.\n\n(c) **no recency decay** — `per_path_promotion_rate` aggregates over ALL historical AI rows on the path with equal weight. A repo that legitimately had a high promotion rate two years ago (because of a then-real vuln class) keeps the boost forever, even after the codebase refactor that fixed the vuln class. The boost outliving its signal is mild for the legitimate operator; it is severe for the attacker, because once the rate is poisoned high, no clean scan reduces it — every clean scan with no new findings on src/evil.py leaves the denominator constant (no new total) and the numerator constant (no new promotions), so the rate is sticky. The only path to recovery is operator-manual `manual_dismiss` of each historical row (which flips `status` to `Closed` and provenance to `ManualDismiss`, removing the row from the AI-rate numerator AND denominator), and the operator has no UI signal that the rate is poisoned.\n\nFurthermore: a single SELECT covers ALL paths in the repo with no per-row authentication beyond the daemon's pool access; the HashMap returned has unbounded cardinality (`HashMap::with_capacity(rows.len())` at finding.rs:520), so a repo with 10k+ paths under findings receives 10k+ entries on every novel-discovery run. The current SqlitePool acquire + scan is per-repo per-run, so the cost is bounded but the cache shape grows linearly with finding history; no LRU, no cap. Combined with sentinel #30 (DOS_AMPLIFICATION on findings_for_run's N+1 fetch), this introduces a second cardinality scaling axis for memory.\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is a *trust feedback path* — the AI's output is fed back into the AI's input prioritisation, and a static analyser has no concept of 'an AI's confirmation is not a trust upgrade'. The two existing tests (per_path_promotion_rate_groups_ai_rows_by_path_and_applies_prior at finding.rs:1053-1090 and per_path_promotion_rate_scopes_to_repo at :1092-1110) cover the math but not the threat model. Distinct from sentinel #28 (PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY on set_verify_result overwrite) and sentinel #34 (SCOPE_INVARIANT_BYPASS on list_for_candidate) — those describe how the verifier echo flows into the row; this finding describes how the row's status flows back into prioritisation. Together with #28 and #57/#58, the chain is: attacker plants prompt-injection -> AI confirms candidate -> verifier_blob broadcast lets attacker observe verdict -> next run prioritises attacker-controlled path -> bigger AI budget reasoning about attacker content -> larger prompt-injection surface.\n\nMitigations (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+2+3): (1) **scope promotion-rate signal to operator-confirmed rows only** — change the WHERE clause to `attack_provenance IN ('ManualPromote')` so only operator-asserted (not AI-asserted) confirmations boost the rate. The AI's verifier echo is no longer self-reinforcing. The keyword + size heuristic still produces the bulk of the prioritisation; the rate boost reduces to an operator-curated signal; (2) **cap the boost at +3** rather than +10 — bring the maximum boost under the strongest keyword hit (+6) so the rate alone cannot outrank the static keyword heuristic; the feedback loop's per-step amplification is reduced even if the source data is poisoned; (3) **add recency decay** — change the SELECT to weight rows by `exp(-(now - created_at) / 90_days)` or similar so old confirmations decay; combined with (1) this drains poisoned rates over time even if past confirmations were attacker-driven; (4) **emit a quarantine row when any single path's rate exceeds a threshold** (e.g. `rate >= 0.8` with `total >= 5`) — flags 'this path is unusually concentrated on AI findings', operator triages whether the concentration is legitimate; (5) **scope to (project_id, repo)** rather than (repo,) to close the name-collision angle.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: regression test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module — seed 20 candidate rows on path `src/evil.py` via the existing `apply_novel_outcome` writer + `set_verify_result` calls with attack_provenance='LlmSynthesised' / status='Verified' (simulating verifier-confirmed AI candidates), then call `per_path_promotion_rate(\"repo-1\")` and assert `rates.get(\"src/evil.py\").unwrap() > 0.7`; then call `build_novel_inputs_for_repo` with the rates; assert `inputs[0].files[0].path == \"src/evil.py\"` even though src/evil.py scores 0 on the keyword heuristic. Real-world consequence: an operator who scans a hostile repo and the AI confirms one synthetic candidate per run will, within ~5 scans, see src/evil.py rise to the top of every subsequent novel-discovery batch; the AI is now exclusively reasoning about attacker-controlled context, and any prompt-injection in src/evil.py's content (string literals, comments, docstrings) lands in the AI's request body with maximum amplification. Mitigation test: after fix (1), repeat with the same seed and assert the rate is 0.0 (no ManualPromote rows present) — the boost no longer fires, and the prioritisation degrades to keywords+size as if the feedback loop never existed."
}

