  "rationale": "Neither resolved getter (config.rs:391-405) nor any caller validates the ordering invariant `soft_cap <= run_cap`. Both fields parse independently; both fall back independently; the only filter is `v > 0`. An operator (or a config-templating tool) can set `exploration_soft_cap_usd_micros = 10_000_000` and `exploration_run_cap_usd_micros = 5_000_000` — or, more commonly, omit one and override the other so the runtime default for the unset field violates the ordering (e.g. operator sets a low soft cap of 500_000 to get an early warning but leaves the hard cap at the default 10_000_000; works as intended. Inverse: operator sets a high hard cap of 50_000_000 to allow a big single run but leaves the soft cap at the default 5_000_000; the soft cap still fires at $5 which is fine — but if the operator sets `exploration_soft_cap_usd_micros = 20_000_000` to silence noise and forgets to also raise the hard cap, the run aborts at $10 before the operator's chosen soft signal ever fires). Concrete primitive: the soft cap's documented purpose — `Crossing the cap emits a single operator warning but does not halt the run; the hard cap below is the only ceiling that aborts an in-progress exploration` (config.rs:269-271) — is silently nullified whenever soft >= run. The exploration.rs:307 check `result.cost_usd_micros >= scope.soft_cap_usd_micros` is post-hoc per task; if the run aborts at the hard cap mid-task, the post-hoc check never runs for that task and the operator sees a hard-cap abort with NO preceding soft-cap warning, defeating the early-warning design. Distinct from any prior sentinel — sentinel #26 covers `allowed_hosts = Vec::new()` (missing-enforcement on a different surface); this is missing-cross-field-validation on a brand-new config surface. Mitigations: (1) add `Config::validate` rule (or extend AiConfig::validate, since AiConfig already has the parsing path through Config::parse) that rejects load when `soft_cap_resolved > run_cap_resolved` with a