  "endpoint": "operator-facing: `nyctos doctor` output line `ai exploration caps: $X.XX soft [origin], $Y.YY run [origin]`",
  "rationale": "`report_ai` (main.rs:1887-1905) decides the `[configured]` vs `[default]` suffix by `config.ai.exploration_soft_cap_usd_micros.is_some()` (main.rs:1895) and the symmetric run-cap check at :1897. The `_resolved` getters in config.rs:391-405 fall back to the caller-default whenever the parsed value satisfies `v <= 0`, but `is_some()` is true for `Some(0)` and `Some(-1)` — the very values the resolver discards. Concrete primitive: an operator who sets `exploration_soft_cap_usd_micros = 0` (intending — based on common cap-disabling conventions — to disable the soft cap) sees `doctor` print `ai exploration caps: $5.00 soft [configured]`. They trust the `[configured]` label, conclude their override applied with value $5 (because that is what `report_ai` printed), and assume the engine respects their intent. The engine actually used the crate-default $5 (per exploration.rs:60 `DEFAULT_EXPLORATION_SOFT_CAP_USD_MICROS = 5_000_000`) — same number coincidentally, but for a different reason. If the crate-default changes in a future release (very plausible — these defaults are tagged 'Sized for Claude Opus pricing on a Phase-23 exploration loop' in config.rs:279-280 and will move with model pricing), the operator's soft cap silently moves with it while `doctor` keeps reporting `[configured]`. Inverse harm: operator sets `exploration_run_cap_usd_micros = -1` intending to bypass the cap; doctor reports `[configured]` for the resolved default; operator believes they have unlimited budget; the actual hard cap fires at the default and aborts production runs. The static pass missed this because the bug is a *display/state divergence* across two independent code paths (the `is_some()` boolean and the resolver's `v > 0` filter) — no taint flow, no obvious sink. Distinct from any prior sentinel finding. Mitigations: (1) replace the `is_some()` predicate with a parallel `is_positive()` helper or use `is_some_and(|v| *v > 0)` so the label matches the resolver's accepted range; (2) introduce a single `enum CapSource { Default, Configured(i64), InvalidFellBack(i64) }` returned by a new `cap_with_source(default) -> (i64, CapSource)` and have `report_ai` print `[default]`, `[configured]`, or `[invalid:-1 -> default]` so the operator sees the bad input explicitly; (3) when the resolver falls back for a Some(_) input, log a warn line at config-load time `[ai] exploration_soft_cap_usd_micros = -1 is non-positive; using default $5.00`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Operator-misconfig reproducer: write `~/.config/nyctos/config.toml` with `[ai]\\nexploration_soft_cap_usd_micros = 0\\nexploration_run_cap_usd_micros = -1\\n`. Run `nyctos doctor`. Observe output line `ai exploration caps: $5.00 soft [configured], $10.00 run [configured]`. Regression test in main.rs's tests (or a new integration test under crates/nyctos/tests): parse the same TOML, capture `report_ai`'s stdout, assert the suffix is `[invalid -> default]` (or whichever mitigation lands) — not `[configured]`."
}

