record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/config.rs",
  "line": 393,
  "cap": "BUDGET_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "internal: AiConfig::exploration_run_cap_usd_micros_resolved drives BudgetStoreTracker::new(store, run_cap_usd_micros) at ai_pipeline.rs:2585 — this is the SOLE ceiling on AI Exploration LLM spend per docs/config.md:91-92",
  "rationale": "`exploration_run_cap_usd_micros_resolved` (config.rs:400-405) accepts any positive i64. There is no upper-bound clamp, no sanity check against an absolute ceiling, and no warning when the configured value exceeds the documented Phase-23 default by more than e.g. 10x. Concrete primitives: (1) **operator typo** — TOML supports `_` digit separators, so `9_000_000` ($9) and `9_000_000_000` ($9000) and `9_000_000_000_000` ($9_000_000) all parse without complaint; one extra zero elevates a $9 hard cap into a $9-million hard cap that effectively never trips on any realistic run. The doctor display will print `$9000000000.00 run [configured]` (16 chars before the dot) which is visually distinct but `f64`-lossy past 2^53 (about 9e15); inputs near i64::MAX print as `$9223372036854.78` which an operator scanning a terminal may misread as `$9223.37`. (2) **malicious config push** — an attacker who lands a config-file write (a separate primitive, but realistic in the supply-chain model — e.g. a tampered ansible role, a git-pulled config template, a compromised k8s ConfigMap) can set `exploration_run_cap_usd_micros = 9223372036854775807` (i64::MAX) and the cap is silently neutralised. The doctor surface is the only place an operator might catch it; per the OBSERVABILITY_MISMATCH finding above, that surface labels the value `[configured]` with no anomaly flag. (3) **interaction with shared budget tracker** — `BudgetStoreTracker::new(store, run_cap_usd_micros)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2585) is the single point of enforcement; the tracker has no fallback hard ceiling baked into the crate. So if `run_cap_usd_micros` is bogus-large, every per-task call accumulates against an effectively unbounded budget until the API key's billing trips externally — which on Anthropic's billing has a much higher latency than a local cap. Distinct from sentinel #26 (host-enforcement missing; a different missing-control on the same exploration surface). Mitigations (recommend 1+3): (1) clamp `_resolved` to an absolute ceiling — e.g. `min(v, ABSOLUTE_MAX_RUN_CAP_USD_MICROS)` where ABSOLUTE_MAX is a documented per-crate constant (e.g. 100_000_000 = $100/run; matches the docs' framing that exploration is bounded); (2) make `Config::validate` (or AiConfig::validate) reject load when run_cap exceeds 10x the default with a clear error, requiring the operator to acknowledge by setting a second `[ai] allow_high_caps = true` flag; (3) log at config-load time a warn line when run_cap > 10x default `[ai] exploration_run_cap_usd_micros = $X is N× the default; verify intentional`; (4) in `report_ai`, decorate the line with a `[!HIGH]` tag when the configured value exceeds 10x default.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier-seed test in crates/nyctos-core/src/config.rs::tests: add `ai_exploration_run_cap_rejects_absurd_value` — `Config::parse(\"[ai]\\nexploration_run_cap_usd_micros = 9223372036854775807\\n\", ...)` should either error or be clamped (`assert_eq!(cfg.ai.exploration_run_cap_usd_micros_resolved(10_000_000), ABSOLUTE_MAX_RUN_CAP_USD_MICROS)`). End-to-end: configure run_cap=i64::MAX, drive `drive_ai_exploration_pass` with a runtime that returns 1_000_000 micros per call across 1000 calls, assert `BudgetStoreTracker` rejects at the ABSOLUTE_MAX threshold (not at i64::MAX). Real-world consequence (no clamp): an operator who fat-fingers `1_000_000` as `1_000_000_000` (extra zero) at config rollout sees no error, no warning, and on the next runaway agent loop the API bill is 1000x the intent before the run completes."
}

