record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2159,
  "cap": "VERIFIER_COVERAGE_BIAS",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_harness_for_cap(\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\") drives run_payload_verification_pass for every candidate row with cap=PATH_TRAVERSAL emitted by NovelFindingDiscovery",
  "rationale": "The harness invoke is exactly `cat -- safe_dir/@PAYLOAD 2>/dev/null || true`. The oracle is `OutputContains{ \"TOP_SECRET_TRAV\" }` against a root-level `oracle_secret.txt`. The harness can therefore ONLY fire on payloads where (a) the byte sequence, prefixed by the literal `safe_dir/` and used as a POSIX filename, resolves to a file containing the substring `TOP_SECRET_TRAV`, AND (b) `cat` succeeds (no NUL truncation, no length cap, no sandbox-blocked syscall). In practice that narrows confirmation to literal POSIX `../`-style traversal walking up one or more directories to land on `oracle_secret.txt`. Real-world PATH_TRAVERSAL classes the harness CANNOT confirm — every one of which is an LLM-novel-discovery sweet spot the static pass also misses — include: (1) URL-decoded traversal (`%2e%2e%2f`, `%2e%2e%5c`) — the verifier sees the encoded literal bytes, `cat` opens a file named `%2e%2e%2foracle_secret.txt` which does not exist, oracle no-fires; (2) double-encoded / overlong UTF-8 (`%252e%252e%252f`, `..%c0%af`) — same path; (3) Windows-style separators (`..\\..\\oracle_secret.txt`) — POSIX `cat` treats backslash as a literal filename byte; (4) null-byte truncation (`legit.txt\\x00../oracle_secret.txt`) — POSIX strncpy semantics that some vulnerable apps still exhibit; the verifier's `printf '%b'` may or may not honour `\\000` and shell-arg passing truncates at NUL anyway; (5) archive-extraction (`zip-slip` / `tar-slip`) traversal via `os.path.join(extracted, member.filename)` — the harness never invokes any zip/tar parser; (6) template-loader traversal (Jinja `{% include %}`, Twig `include`) — the harness never invokes any template engine; (7) log-rotation / log-path traversal via `logging.handlers.RotatingFileHandler(user_input)` — the harness has no Python runtime; (8) symlink-following traversal where the vuln is `open(user_input)` with a symlink planted via a separate write primitive — the harness setup creates no symlinks; (9) NFD/NFC Unicode normalisation traversal (`..%C0%2F` and friends); (10) container-mount escapes via `/proc/self/root/etc/passwd`-style absolute paths — the harness's `safe_dir/` prefix prepends, so `safe_dir//proc/...` does not resolve. **Every one of these candidates the LLM correctly emits as PATH_TRAVERSAL will be DISMISSED by the verifier**, with the candidate's row landing at `status='Dismissed'` and the per-path promotion-rate signal (finding.rs:506, sentinel #65) ratcheting DOWN for files that contain these higher-quality classes. Net systemic effect: the verifier acts as a *selective-promotion filter* that confirms only the lowest-effort PATH_TRAVERSAL class while suppressing the harder classes — exactly inverting the AI pipeline's stated value of catching what static missed. Distinct from sentinel #65 (which describes the rate-feedback amplification on positive confirmations); this finding describes the *negative* side — the dismissals systematically bias the rate against the highest-value LLM emissions. Two reinforcing observations: the harness's `2>/dev/null || true` masks every non-success exit (a sandbox-blocked open, an EACCES, an ENAMETOOLONG, an EINVAL on a `\\0`-truncated arg) into a clean `oracle_fired=false`, so the verifier cannot distinguish 'payload was wrong' from 'payload was right but the synthetic env could not exercise it'; and the test at ai_pipeline.rs:4774 hard-codes `suggested_payload_hint = \"../oracle_secret.txt\"` which is the ONLY shape the harness can confirm — locking the regression suite to that single shape and rewarding any future LLM that emits the same naive shape over a more accurate URL-encoded or archive-extraction hint. Mitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) emit a per-candidate `verifier.coverage_class` label (e.g. `posix_dot_dot_to_root_marker`) alongside the verdict so the per-path promotion rate can be scoped to *the class the harness actually exercises*, not all PATH_TRAVERSAL; downstream consumers (PR comments, scan reports) can flag 'confirmed only against the posix-cat class — other PATH_TRAVERSAL classes were NOT exercised'; (2) stop dismissing candidates the harness cannot exercise — when the oracle does not fire AND the payload contained an encoding indicator (`%2e`, backslash, NUL byte, `.zip`/`.tar` substring, an absolute path starting with `/proc` or `/etc`) the verdict should be `Inconclusive`, not `Dismissed`, so the rate signal is not negatively biased; (3) add at least one extra invoke that exercises a Python `pathlib.Path('safe_dir') / payload` resolver under a `cap_lang=python` harness — different sink than `cat`, catches the encoding/normalisation classes #1-4 above; (4) replace `2>/dev/null || true` with `2>verifier_stderr.log; cat verifier_stderr.log` captured to the trace so the verifier can post-hoc distinguish failure modes.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Regression test (negative-side) in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module: extend the new path-traversal e2e test with a sibling test `verifier_does_not_dismiss_encoded_path_traversal_candidate` that inserts the same CandidateFindingRecord with `suggested_payload_hint = Some(\"%2e%2e%2foracle_secret.txt\".to_string())` and asserts the resulting candidate row is `status='Inconclusive'` (NOT `'Dismissed'`). Mitigation-side test: insert 5 candidates with hints {\"../oracle_secret.txt\", \"%2e%2e%2foracle_secret.txt\", \"..\\\\oracle_secret.txt\", \"legit.txt\\x00../oracle_secret.txt\", \"/proc/self/root/oracle_secret.txt\"} and assert the per-path promotion-rate update divides candidate dismissals into a separate counter (`dismissed_by_coverage`) versus genuine dismissals (`dismissed_by_evidence`)."
}

