record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 4803,
  "cap": "EVIDENCE_PROVENANCE_GAP",
  "endpoint": "operator-facing: findings table row written by run_payload_verification_pass with finding_origin=\"AiExploration\", status=\"Verified\", cap=\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\", path=<candidate.path>, line=<candidate.line> — surfaced in scan reports, PR comments (cmd/pr_comment.rs), the per-path promotion rate (finding.rs:506) and operator triage UI",
  "rationale": "The new e2e test `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_path_traversal_cap` (ai_pipeline.rs:4742-4806) asserts that a Verified PATH_TRAVERSAL finding is written to the findings table at `app/serve_file.py:42` — but the synthetic builtin harness *never opens, reads, or executes* `app/serve_file.py`. The harness creates an in-tempdir `safe_dir/innocent.txt` + `oracle_secret.txt`, runs `cat -- safe_dir/<payload>`, and observes whether stdout contains `TOP_SECRET_TRAV`. The success condition proves only that *the generic POSIX-shell PATH_TRAVERSAL primitive exists in the synthetic environment* — a tautology, since it was hand-constructed to demonstrate that primitive. It does NOT prove that the candidate code path (`app/serve_file.py:42`, a hypothetical `flask.send_file(request.args['name'])`) actually exhibits the bug. The same pattern exists for SQLi/CMDi builtin harnesses (sentinel #34's verifier_blob discussion), but the asymmetry for PATH_TRAVERSAL is sharper because: (a) the generic primitive is trivially satisfiable — any LLM payload starting with `../` and the literal filename `oracle_secret.txt` fires the oracle, regardless of whether the candidate code path can actually be reached; (b) downstream consumers treat `finding_origin='AiExploration', status='Verified'` as 'this specific file:line has the vuln' — PR comments quote the candidate's `path:line` directly (per cmd/pr_comment.rs's row rendering), scan reports list the path, the per-path promotion rate (sentinel #65) boosts future AI budget on that path; (c) once `cap=PATH_TRAVERSAL` is in the findings table, the chain-reasoning surface (finding.rs:395 set_chain, sentinel #27) can cross-link the row to genuinely-confirmed unrelated findings, laundering the evidence further. Concrete attacker primitive (compound with sentinel #34, #57, #58, #65): an adversary who controls a repo's contents and lands ANY candidate with `cap=PATH_TRAVERSAL` and `suggested_payload_hint=\"../oracle_secret.txt\"` (the most natural hint a prompt-injected or naive LLM emits — and the one the test hard-codes as the canonical shape) gets a Verified finding written against a path of their choice. The path field is taken verbatim from the candidate, which the LLM emits from attacker-controlled source content. An attacker who plants prompt-injection in their repo's comments steering the LLM to emit `path: \"../../legitimate_repo/critical.py\"` (compound with sentinel #20 path traversal in infer_lang_for_file) lands a Verified finding that operator triage will interpret as 'the AI confirmed legitimate_repo/critical.py has a path-traversal bug' — even though the verifier exercised an unrelated `safe_dir/../oracle_secret.txt` synthetic. Distinct from sentinel #28 (PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY on set_verify_result overwrite, attacker-controlled verifier output) — this finding describes a built-in, not-attacker-controlled verifier that still produces evidence-overstating rows because the harness was never bound to the candidate. Distinct from sentinel #34 (SCOPE_INVARIANT_BYPASS on list_for_candidate's row reuse). Mitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) stamp every promoted finding with a `verifier_evidence_class` field — `Synthetic` for builtin-harness confirmations, `Bound` only when the harness actually exercised the candidate's source path; downstream consumers (PR comments, reports, promotion-rate boost) must gate on `Bound`; (2) refuse to write `status='Verified'` for builtin-harness promotions — write `status='SyntheticConfirmed'` instead, a third bucket between Verified and Dismissed; the operator UI distinguishes them visually; (3) include the harness's setup+invoke+oracle bytes in the finding's `attack_provenance_blob` so the operator can inspect WHAT primitive was actually exercised — the current row carries only the cap label, which is misleading.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: extend the new path-traversal e2e test with `verifier_records_synthetic_evidence_class_for_builtin_harness` that asserts the promoted findings row has `verifier_evidence_class='Synthetic'` (or whichever field name mitigation #1 lands on) NOT just `status='Verified'`. End-to-end attacker reproducer: seed a candidate with `path=\"crates/nyctos-core/src/security_critical.rs\"`, `line=Some(1)`, `cap=\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\"`, `suggested_payload_hint=Some(\"../oracle_secret.txt\".to_string())`; assert that without the mitigation the resulting findings row's `(path, line, cap, status, finding_origin)` matches the inserted candidate verbatim despite the harness never opening `security_critical.rs`. The PR-comment rendering side (cmd/pr_comment.rs) should be exercised in a regression test to confirm the synthetic-vs-bound distinction surfaces in operator-visible output."
}

