record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2177,
  "cap": "ORACLE_MARKER_COLLISION",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_oracle_for_cap(\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\") returns OutputContains{ \"TOP_SECRET_TRAV\" }; sibling builtin_oracle_for_cap(\"SQL_QUERY\"|\"SQLi\") returns OutputContains{ \"TOP_SECRET\" } at the same call site (ai_pipeline.rs:2173)",
  "rationale": "The new PATH_TRAVERSAL marker `TOP_SECRET_TRAV` (15 ASCII bytes) STARTS with the SQLi marker `TOP_SECRET` (10 ASCII bytes). The substring relationship matters across two surfaces: (1) **cross-cap false positive on the SQLi oracle**: if any future harness or replay scenario produces output where a PATH_TRAVERSAL-style sink leaks the longer marker (e.g. a composite harness covering multiple caps in one invoke, a verifier-replay that bleeds workspace state between caps, or an AI-derived spec-derivation harness for a new cap that reuses the PATH_TRAVERSAL setup) and that output reaches a `SQL_QUERY` oracle evaluation, `OutputContains.is_match` (substring search) WILL fire on the `TOP_SECRET` prefix and the SQLi oracle promotes a non-SQLi finding. The reverse — PATH_TRAVERSAL oracle false-firing on SQLi output `'alice:pw1\\nbob:pw2\\nadmin:TOP_SECRET'` — does NOT happen because `TOP_SECRET_TRAV` is not a substring of `TOP_SECRET`. The asymmetry means the SQLi oracle is the one with the foot-gun. (2) **operator confusion in finding rationales and PR comments**: the marker strings are surfaced in verifier traces (per persist_verifier_trace at ai_pipeline.rs:2101-2110) and may appear in rationale text the LLM consumes on subsequent runs as scoring context; an operator reading a verifier trace that contains `TOP_SECRET_TRAV` may misread it as a generic 'top secret' label and conclude the harness exercised real secret data, when in fact it exercised a synthetic 15-byte marker. (3) **maintenance hazard for the marker namespace**: there is no central registry of oracle markers. The next cap added to `builtin_oracle_for_cap` (XSS, SSRF, XXE per the comment at ai_pipeline.rs:2118-2122) is by precedent likely to be named `TOP_SECRET_XSS` or `TOP_SECRET_SSRF` — extending the substring-prefix collision. The first author to introduce two markers where one is a substring of the other has now set the convention. Specific concrete primitive: an attacker-controlled candidate that triggers BOTH a PATH_TRAVERSAL row AND a SQL_QUERY row on the same line (the LLM may emit two candidate rows from one prompt-injected source comment — sentinel #65 path); the PATH_TRAVERSAL row promotes via cat-reads-secret, AND the SQLi row's verifier executes its own `printf | grep -E <payload>` harness with a payload designed to also print `TOP_SECRET` (e.g. payload regex `T[OP]+_SECRET.*`); without proper namespacing the SQLi oracle's substring search makes it cheaper to satisfy. Distinct from sentinel #28 / #34 (verifier-output integrity) — those concern attacker-controlled output reaching the oracle. This finding concerns *the oracle's marker namespace itself being substring-prone*, a passive-defense gap rather than an active-attack gap. Static pass missed because the bug is a *string-namespace mismatch* across two `match` arms that no analyser models as related. Mitigations (recommend 1+2): (1) make markers explicitly non-substring-related — change PATH_TRAVERSAL marker to `NYX_TRAV_ORACLE_FIRED_8e1f` (random-suffix + cap-prefix, no shared substring with SQLi's marker); apply the same convention forward to every new cap; (2) add a const-time assertion in a unit test that the markers across `builtin_oracle_for_cap` are pairwise non-substring (a 30-line test that iterates caps, collects markers, and asserts `!a.contains(b) && !b.contains(a)` for every pair); (3) replace `OutputContains` with `OutputMatchesRegex` anchored to word boundaries (`\\bTOP_SECRET\\b` instead of substring), so the SQLi oracle does not match `TOP_SECRET_TRAV` even if it leaks cross-cap.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: unit test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module `builtin_oracle_markers_are_pairwise_non_substring`: collect markers from `builtin_oracle_for_cap` over the covered cap set {SQL_QUERY, SQLi, OS_COMMAND, CMDi, PATH_TRAVERSAL}, extract `OutputContains.marker` values (SinkProbe caps skip), and assert for every (a, b) pair with a != b that neither marker is a substring of the other. The test fails today because `\"TOP_SECRET_TRAV\".contains(\"TOP_SECRET\")` is true. End-to-end: construct a synthetic PayloadRun with cap=SQL_QUERY but invoke template `printf 'TOP_SECRET_TRAV\\n'` (no payload splice), assert the SQLi oracle fires — demonstrating that a PATH_TRAVERSAL-shape output can promote a SQLi candidate."
}

