  "line": 2158,
  "cap": "HARNESS_FAILURE_INDISTINGUISHABILITY",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_harness_for_cap(\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\") setup is concatenated raw into the synthesised shell script that render_synthesised emits at nyctos-sandbox/src/payload_runner.rs:435-463 — the script prelude is exactly `#!/bin/sh\\n# auto-generated by nyctos-sandbox::payload_runner\\nset -u\\n` (payload_runner.rs:450), then each setup line, then the invoke, then teardown.",
  "rationale": "The synthesised harness runs under `set -u` only — `set -e` is NOT enabled (payload_runner.rs:450). The PATH_TRAVERSAL setup has three commands that can silently fail without aborting the script: (1) `mkdir -p safe_dir` (EACCES if the per-call COW snapshot's effective UID lacks write on the workspace root — possible in seccomp-constrained lanes, or under a future read-only-rootfs sandbox profile, or simply ENOSPC on a near-full tempdir partition the snapshot is layered on); (2) `printf 'workspace\\n' > safe_dir/innocent.txt` (depends on step 1 succeeding — if mkdir silently failed, this fails ENOENT); (3) `printf 'TOP_SECRET_TRAV\\n' > oracle_secret.txt` (independent of step 1 — writes to workspace root regardless, so this one usually succeeds even if step 1 fails, except under root-FS readonly). When any of (1)-(3) fails the script continues. The subsequent invoke `cat -- safe_dir/@PAYLOAD 2>/dev/null || true` is *deliberately* engineered to mask ALL failure modes: stderr is redirected to /dev/null, AND the `|| true` swallows any nonzero exit so the script always exits 0 with empty stdout. The oracle `OutputContains{ \"TOP_SECRET_TRAV\" }` sees empty bytes, returns `oracle_fired=false`, and the candidate row is recorded as a clean *negative confirmation* — the same byte-for-byte verdict a TRUE no-vuln payload would produce. There is no distinguishability between `verifier-env-broken` and `payload-was-wrong`. Concrete primitives this enables in production: (a) **CI flakiness laundering**: a transient ENOSPC, a sandbox configuration regression, or a backend-specific umask change permanently moves a class of PATH_TRAVERSAL candidates from `Promoted` to `Dismissed` on the affected CI host, the per-path promotion rate (finding.rs:506, sentinel #65) ratchets down for those paths, and the AI exploration budget for them is starved — with NO operator-visible signal that any verification ever ran broken; (b) **defender-side false negative**: a real PATH_TRAVERSAL bug in a candidate's actual code path is dismissed because the harness env was broken, the operator triages on the basis that the verifier said no, and ships the vulnerable code; (c) **dishonest-attacker primitive (sandbox poisoning)**: an attacker who lands ANY primitive that causes setup to fail (e.g. a poisoned umask in shell init read by the sandbox, a deliberately-malformed `safe_dir` symlink already present in workspace root that makes `mkdir -p safe_dir` race-fail) silently disables the PATH_TRAVERSAL verifier for the entire run while every operator-visible surface still reports normal candidate processing. Distinct from sentinel #65 (which is about the harness lacking coverage for *valid* alternate payload shapes — the harness logically cannot match them); this finding is about the harness lacking distinguishability for *invalid harness environments* — the harness fails to run and silently reports the wrong verdict. The `2>/dev/null || true` pattern is the architectural fork that conflates the two; both #65's coverage classes and #68's failure modes fold into a single `oracle_fired=false` bit. Static pass missed because the bug is the *absence* of `set -e` plus the *presence* of error suppression — there is no tainted-flow sink, just a missing safety setting. Mitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) prepend `set -eu` to the shell prelude in render_synthesised (payload_runner.rs:450) so any setup failure aborts the script; the invoke can still suppress its OWN failure via `2>/dev/null || true` (the per-cap policy) but setup failure now distinguishes; (2) capture the script's exit code into the VerifyResult — currently the verifier only inspects stdout-vs-oracle, so a nonzero exit is ignored; on nonzero exit while the oracle did not fire, return `VerifyVerdict::Errored` (with the captured exit code in `error_message`) instead of `NotConfirmed`, so the candidate row lands `Inconclusive` and the promotion-rate signal is not biased; (3) for the specific PATH_TRAVERSAL harness, restructure setup as `mkdir -p safe_dir && printf 'workspace\\n' > safe_dir/innocent.txt && printf 'TOP_SECRET_TRAV\\n' > oracle_secret.txt || { echo SETUP_FAILED >&2 ; exit 73 ; }` so a single chained-and-failure surfaces a unique exit code distinct from `cat`'s exit modes; (4) add a per-cap `setup_verification` step the runner executes *before* the payload run — for PATH_TRAVERSAL, `test -f oracle_secret.txt && test -d safe_dir && test -f safe_dir/innocent.txt`; a false verdict on setup_verification fails the whole verify call as `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessSetupFailed }`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-sandbox/src/payload_runner.rs tests module): construct a `PayloadRun` whose `spec.setup = vec![\"exit 17\".to_string()]` and whose `spec.invoke = \"echo TOP_SECRET_TRAV\".to_string()` with `Oracle::OutputContains{ marker: \"TOP_SECRET_TRAV\".to_string() }`. Today the verifier returns `VerifyVerdict::Confirmed` because the script aborts before reaching invoke under set -e, OR returns Confirmed because without set -e the `exit 17` runs, the `echo` never executes, output is empty, oracle does not fire → NotConfirmed. The desired post-mitigation verdict is `VerifyVerdict::Errored` with `error_message` containing the exit code 17. End-to-end reproducer for the production primitive: chmod the workspace root to 0500 between snapshot and harness exec (or, simpler, replace the workspace dir with a read-only bind mount), run the existing `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_path_traversal_cap` test (ai_pipeline.rs:4742): today the test would flip from `confirmed == 1` to `confirmed == 0` with the candidate row landing `Dismissed`; under the mitigation it should land `Inconclusive` (or whichever bucket the runner chooses for harness-setup-failed) — never `Dismissed`."
}

