record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2118,
  "cap": "GOVERNANCE_OPT_OUT_GAP",
  "endpoint": "operator-policy: builtin_harness_for_cap / builtin_oracle_for_cap / builtin_benign_for_cap form a hard-coded per-cap policy table that decides whether an AI-Exploration candidate is verified via synthetic generic-template harness or routed through the candidate-confirmation pipeline; the diff promotes PATH_TRAVERSAL from the latter to the former with no config-side flag.",
  "rationale": "Prior to this diff, the sentinel test at ai_pipeline.rs:4828-4833 asserted that PATH_TRAVERSAL `must return None so the verifier skips it instead of confirming on a generic template that has no chance of matching the real sink` (the comment at :4815-4817, still verbatim in the post-diff source). The diff moves PATH_TRAVERSAL across that line into the covered set (:4818) by registering a hand-written harness/oracle/benign triple at :2144-2161 / :2177 / :2190. The covered-set membership is a *compile-time policy decision*. There is no operator-side surface that:\n\n(a) **enumerates which caps go through synthetic auto-promotion vs which require operator review** — `nyctos doctor` (main.rs:1887-1905 per the recent `report_ai` addition tracked in sentinel #62-#64) prints budget/cap caps but does NOT print the per-cap verifier-mode table. An operator cannot run `nyctos doctor` and learn that PATH_TRAVERSAL now auto-promotes via a hand-written synthetic harness whereas XSS/SSRF/XXE/DESERIALISATION (the other entries on the formerly-skipped list at :4828) still route through the candidate-confirmation pipeline. The asymmetry is invisible at runtime.\n\n(b) **lets an operator opt out per cap** — a security-policy-driven operator (e.g. one whose risk policy says \"the AI's PATH_TRAVERSAL confirmations require human triage because the synthetic primitive cannot prove the candidate's actual code path is reachable — sentinel #66\") has no way to refuse the auto-promotion short of forking the source. Config (`AiConfig` in crates/nyctos-core/src/config.rs) has no `disabled_synthetic_caps: Vec<String>` field; CLI has no `--no-synthetic-cap PATH_TRAVERSAL` switch; the per-run `RunConfig` has no per-cap override. The only structural escape is at the candidate-row level via `manual_dismiss`, but that's REACTIVE (after the row lands as Verified) not PROACTIVE (gating the auto-promotion path).\n\n(c) **logs the per-cap routing decision so an auditor can reconstruct it post-hoc** — when the verifier promotes a PATH_TRAVERSAL candidate today the finding row's `attack_provenance` is `AiExploration` (per the e2e test's assertion at ai_pipeline.rs:4799) — identical to a PATH_TRAVERSAL promotion that came from a fully-AI-emitted (LlmSynthesised) harness via the candidate-confirmation pipeline. The provenance field cannot distinguish \"the AI emitted both candidate AND spec, and a separate verifier exercised the AI's spec\" (high-trust signal) from \"the AI emitted a candidate, and the verifier ran a hand-coded generic template with no semantic relationship to the candidate's source code\" (low-trust signal, sentinel #66). A compliance auditor reading the findings table six months from now cannot reconstruct which route any given Verified row came from.\n\nConcrete primitives the gap enables: (1) **silent policy drift**: a future maintainer who adds XSS to the covered-cap list (via the same 3-line pattern — register harness, register oracle, register benign) flips the verifier's behaviour for every operator across every deployment with no config-side migration step, no doctor-side warning, no row-level provenance distinction. Operators who set policy based on \"AI Exploration treats XSS the same as it treats SSRF\" silently lose that property. (2) **policy-vs-implementation contradiction**: an organisation that has a written policy of \"synthetic harness confirmations need operator sign-off\" can write that policy and believe nyctos enforces it; nyctos in fact enforces only the budget caps (sentinel #62-#64); the synthetic-vs-bound boundary (sentinel #66) and the per-cap routing decision (this finding) are both invisible to policy. (3) **rollback impossibility under incident**: if a deployed nyctos instance starts mass-producing false-positive PATH_TRAVERSAL Verified rows (e.g. because of a per-path promotion-rate poisoning loop per sentinel #65), the operator's only mitigation today is to disable AI Exploration entirely (a sledgehammer) or to manually dismiss each row (a treadmill). The granular knob — \"disable synthetic auto-promotion for PATH_TRAVERSAL while I investigate\" — does not exist.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #62-#64 (budget-cap config-validation gaps — a different config surface), #65 (coverage bias on payload shape — verifier-internal), #66 (evidence-provenance gap on the finding row — schema-level), #67 (marker collision — namespace gap), #68 (failure indistinguishability — runtime semantics), #69 (regression-test coverage — meta-suite), #70 (workspace-layout pollution — harness mechanics). This finding is about the *governance layer* — the policy that decides which caps go through which verifier mode — being entirely compile-time and entirely opaque to operators.\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is the *absence of a config field* and the *absence of a doctor-surface line* — there is no taint flow, no missing escape, no insecure default. The bug is a missing surface area for operator policy enforcement.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+3): (1) add `synthetic_harness_caps_disabled: Vec<String>` to `AiConfig` (config.rs alongside the new exploration_*_cap_usd_micros fields per sentinel #62-#64); have `builtin_harness_for_cap` return `None` whenever the queried cap appears in this list — preserving the auto-promotion default but giving operators a per-cap opt-out; (2) extend `report_ai` (main.rs:1887) to print the per-cap verifier-routing table: `ai exploration verifier routing: SQL_QUERY [synthetic], OS_COMMAND [synthetic], PATH_TRAVERSAL [synthetic], XSS [candidate-pipeline], SSRF [candidate-pipeline], ...` with `[synthetic-disabled]` shown when the operator-config opt-out is in effect; (3) stamp every finding row with `verifier_route: SyntheticAutoPromote | CandidatePipelineConfirmed | ManualPromote` (or extend `attack_provenance` with `LlmSynthesised(Synthetic)` vs `LlmSynthesised(CandidatePipeline)`) so a post-hoc audit can reconstruct which route the row came from; (4) at startup-time and at every `cargo build`-time the maintainer who edits the covered-cap list must also update a `CHANGELOG.md` entry documenting the routing change — enforced via a CI check that fails when `builtin_harness_for_cap`'s match arms change without a corresponding changelog/migration entry; (5) emit an operator-visible warn-level `AgentEvent` on first run after a covered-cap-list expansion: `synthetic_cap_routing_changed { added: [\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\"], removed: [] }` so existing operators see the change in their event stream.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module): `synthetic_caps_can_be_disabled_per_cap_via_config` — construct `AiConfig { synthetic_harness_caps_disabled: vec![\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\".to_string()], ..Default::default() }`, then call `builtin_harness_for_cap(\"PATH_TRAVERSAL\")` THROUGH a config-aware accessor (the mitigation introduces `harness_for_cap(cfg, cap)` that consults the disabled list); assert the result is `None`. Drive the existing e2e `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_path_traversal_cap` flow with the disabled-list set; assert `report.candidates_promoted == 0` and the candidate row's `status` is `Pending` (left for the candidate-pipeline / manual review) — NOT `Promoted`. Doctor-surface test (in crates/nyctos/src/main.rs tests or an integration test): with `synthetic_harness_caps_disabled = []`, capture `report_ai` stdout, assert it contains a line `ai exploration verifier routing: ... PATH_TRAVERSAL [synthetic]`; with the disabled-list set, assert the line reads `PATH_TRAVERSAL [synthetic-disabled]`. Provenance test: with mitigation (3) landed, drive the existing e2e and assert the promoted findings row's `verifier_route == \"SyntheticAutoPromote\"` (or whatever field name lands); operator triage UI then renders the synthetic-route rows distinctly from candidate-pipeline-confirmed rows."
