  "cap": "VERIFIER_ARBITRARY_CODE_EXEC",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_harness_for_cap(\"DESERIALISATION\") emits a python harness whose invoke is `pickle.loads(@PAYLOAD)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2188). `@PAYLOAD` resolves to the candidate's `suggested_payload_hint` bytes via `python_literal` (payload_runner.rs:468-482) wrapped in a `b\"...\"` literal and spliced verbatim into the script; the script runs inside the per-call COW sandbox under whatever lane the verifier picked (process / birdcage / firecracker / libkrun).",
  "rationale": "Every other covered cap exercises a *bounded primitive*: SQL_QUERY pipes the payload as a regex to `grep -E` (regex engine, no syscalls beyond stdio); OS_COMMAND splices the payload into a shell argv against the OSCMD_SENTINEL probe (shell parser, but the only sink the oracle observes is one write to a sentinel file); PATH_TRAVERSAL hands the payload as a filename to `cat` (open/read syscalls only). The DESERIALISATION harness is *categorically different*: `pickle.loads(bytes)` is, by Python language semantics, **arbitrary callable invocation** — the `REDUCE` opcode (`R`) pops a tuple of args and a callable from the stack and invokes `callable(*args)`. The canonical vuln payload the test uses (`cbuiltins\\nprint\\n(VTOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\ntR.`, ai_pipeline.rs:4929) pushes `builtins.print` and `(\"TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\",)` then executes `print(\"TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\")`. The SAME opcode shape (`c<module>\\n<name>\\n(...t R.`) substituting `os.system` / `subprocess.Popen` / `socket.socket` / `__import__('ctypes').CDLL('libc.so.6').syscall` / `open('/etc/passwd').read` invokes arbitrary code. The oracle `OutputContains{TOP_SECRET_PICKLE}` (ai_pipeline.rs:2208) is satisfied by ANY payload whose execution path also writes the marker to stdout — and the marker is 17 ASCII bytes the attacker fully controls in their candidate row.\n\nConcrete primitives the harness enables (each presupposes only that an attacker influences a candidate row's `suggested_payload_hint` — which, per sentinel #66 and the LLM's role in emitting candidates, is reachable by any prompt-injection on repo contents the AI Exploration pass reads):\n\n(1) **Workspace exfiltration**: pickle that REDUCEs `builtins.print` with `open('/proc/self/cwd/.git/config').read() + 'TOP_SECRET_PICKLE'` — the read happens, the bytes land on stdout (captured into the verifier trace per persist_verifier_trace at ai_pipeline.rs:2101-2110), the marker substring matches, oracle fires, candidate promotes to Verified, AND the .git/config (potentially with embedded credentials per sentinel #10) reaches the verifier trace blob the LLM consumes on subsequent runs as scoring context.\n\n(2) **Host-state probe** (subject to sandbox lane gating): a REDUCE of `socket.gethostbyname` against an attacker-controlled hostname yields a DNS lookup from the sandbox to attacker-controlled infrastructure; the resolved IP returned is concatenated with the marker and printed. Confirms reachability of the sandbox's resolver to the public internet. Repeats with `socket.create_connection` against `('169.254.169.254', 80)` probe cloud metadata (chains with sentinel #6 — which was downgraded to no-op because no AI base_url consumer existed; this finding re-introduces the IMDS-reach primitive through a different channel — the verifier's python interpreter).\n\n(3) **Fork-and-fork-bomb / runtime exhaustion**: REDUCE `os.fork` in a loop emitted by an outer REDUCE chain — the harness has no python-side wall-clock or fork-cap; the sandbox lane's process limits gate this (per backend), but on the `process` lane the only limit is whatever rlimit the runner applies. Sentinel #62-#64 documented budget caps that are USD-denominated and apply to LLM spend, NOT to verifier runtime.\n\n(4) **Sandbox-escape probe**: even where the lane's seccomp / cgroup / namespaces hold, pickle's REDUCE → `ctypes.CDLL(libc).syscall(arbitrary_nr, ...)` lets an attacker enumerate which syscalls the sandbox blocks vs allows. The exit code + stderr capture (today suppressed by the `try/except` at :2188) determines surface visibility, but the act of issuing the syscall is itself reconnaissance: the sandbox's seccomp policy bitmap is recoverable by binary-searching the syscall number space across multiple candidate rows.\n\n(5) **Persistence-to-trace channel**: the script's stdout goes into the verifier trace JSONL row (ai_pipeline.rs:2101-2110) which is persisted under `<state>/traces/<run_id>/<task_id>.jsonl` (sentinel #21-#23). An attacker who lands a candidate with a pickle that emits `B<KB-sized-attacker-controlled-blob>TOP_SECRET_PICKLE` writes attacker-controlled bytes to the operator's persistent state directory — a write primitive into operator-visible storage with no operator opt-in.\n\nThe benign-vs-vuln differential the table sentinel test relies on (sentinel #69) is a CATEGORY ERROR for this cap. `N.` (NONE + STOP) does NOT exercise `REDUCE` at all — it tests \"did the unpickler reject malformed bytes\". The vuln payload exercises REDUCE → arbitrary invocation. The two payloads do not span \"safe vs unsafe\" along the same axis: they span \"empty execution vs full Turing-complete execution\". Every payload between them — including every payload an attacker might craft — sits on the unsafe side of the boundary. This is not a verifier; it is an execution harness that confirms the cap is present *in the harness itself*. The harness IS the vulnerability.\n\nCompare to a sound DESERIALISATION verifier shape: (a) instrument pickle via `pickle.Unpickler.find_class` override that records every (module, name) tuple the payload requests and returns a dummy callable; the harness then asserts the set of requested classes is non-empty AND contains a sink-class (`os.*`, `subprocess.*`, `builtins.eval`, etc.); the oracle fires on REQUESTED classes, not on EXECUTED side effects. (b) statically introspect the pickle bytes via `pickletools.dis(payload)` and search for `GLOBAL` / `STACK_GLOBAL` / `REDUCE` opcodes pointing at dangerous classes. Either shape proves the primitive WITHOUT invoking arbitrary code. The current implementation chose (c): invoke arbitrary code and trust the sandbox lane to contain the blast radius. (c) is correct ONLY IF the verifier process is treated as a hostile-code execution surface equivalent to running the candidate code itself — which the current sandbox lane defaults (per SandboxConfig::default in crates/nyctos-sandbox) are not necessarily configured for. Notably the `process` backend's default seccomp profile permits `connect(2)`, `open(2)`, `read(2)` against the workspace and `/tmp`, none of which are bounded against attacker-controlled REDUCE chains.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL coverage classes the harness CANNOT exercise — this finding is the opposite axis: a harness that exercises FAR MORE than the cap's actual scope), #66 (PATH_TRAVERSAL evidence-provenance gap — bound-vs-synthetic — applies here too but is secondary to the RCE primitive), #67 (marker collision — does not apply since `TOP_SECRET_PICKLE` is not a substring of any other marker), #68 (failure indistinguishability — the `try/except` at :2188 swallows ExpatError / pickle.UnpicklingError into a `deserialise-error:` stdout line; oracle on stderr-vs-stdout distinction is lost here too, but the bigger issue is what the SUCCESS path can do).\n\nStatic pass missed this because the bug is *the choice of pickle.loads as the verifier sink* — a single-token decision with no taint flow, no missing escape, no insecure default. The choice is unsafe under the harness's threat model (LLM-emitted, attacker-influenceable payloads).\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+3+5; 2 is the long-term fix): (1) **revert this cap's harness entry to `None`** — `builtin_harness_for_cap(\"DESERIALISATION\") => None` — and let DESERIALISATION candidates flow through the candidate-confirmation pipeline (LLM-emitted full spec, reviewer triage) instead of synthetic auto-promotion; the cap's per-path promotion-rate signal (sentinel #65) is reset to whatever the candidate-pipeline rate is. (2) **replace pickle.loads with a static-introspection harness** — `import pickletools; ops = list(pickletools.genops(payload)); print('TOP_SECRET_PICKLE' if any(op[0].name in ('REDUCE','BUILD','INST','OBJ','NEWOBJ','NEWOBJ_EX','STACK_GLOBAL','GLOBAL') for op in ops) else 'safe')`; the oracle fires on dangerous-opcode presence, NOT on execution; the script never calls into arbitrary code. (3) **gate the python lang behind an additional sandbox lane assertion** — refuse to run a python harness on the `process` backend; require `birdcage` or stricter; the runner's `pick_lang` (payload_runner.rs:422) already maps `python` → `python3`, extend `payload_runner::verify` to error when `lang == Python && backend == Process`. (4) **wrap `pickle.loads` in a `RestrictedUnpickler` subclass with `find_class` denying all globals** — but this defeats the harness's purpose since `print` is the canonical vuln callable; a coherent boundary is hard to draw without sliding into (2). (5) **emit a loud warn-level AgentEvent on every DESERIALISATION verifier invocation** — `verifier_executes_attacker_influenced_pickle { candidate_id, payload_byte_count, harness_backend }` — so the operator's event stream surfaces this risk surface even when the lane contains the blast radius.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module): `pickle_harness_does_not_execute_redactable_callables` — drive `run_payload_verification_pass` with a candidate row whose `suggested_payload_hint = Some(\"cposix\\nsystem\\n(Vecho NYX_HARNESS_OWNED > /tmp/nyx_owned.flag\\ntR.\".to_string())` and `cap = \"DESERIALISATION\"`; under mitigation (1) assert the row's status is `Pending` (cap not in synthetic set); under mitigation (2) assert the script's stdout contains the dangerous-opcode marker but the file `/tmp/nyx_owned.flag` is NOT created (verified via post-call statfs). End-to-end attacker reproducer: insert a CandidateFindingRecord with `path = \"app/legitimate_lib.py\"`, `line = Some(1)`, `cap = \"DESERIALISATION\"`, `suggested_payload_hint = Some(\"cbuiltins\\nopen\\n(V/etc/hostname\\ntRcbuiltins\\nprint\\n(eVRESULT: TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\ntR.\".to_string())`; today the verifier reads `/etc/hostname` from the host (subject to sandbox lane mounts), prints it before the marker, and promotes the candidate to Verified — confirming the host-file read primitive. Mitigation (2) prevents the read entirely; mitigation (3) refuses the run on the process backend and surfaces an error event."
}

