record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2176,
  "cap": "ORACLE_LITERAL_REFLECTION_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "internal: the XXE harness (ai_pipeline.rs:2162-2178) and the DESERIALISATION harness (:2179-2190) both pair an `OutputContains{marker}` oracle with an invoke that prints either the parsed element text (XXE) or the unpickled side-effect output (DESERIALISATION) AND, in the exception branch, the Python exception's `__str__` (`print('parse-error:', e)` and `print('deserialise-error:', e)`).",
  "rationale": "The oracle for both caps is a substring search on the harness's stdout (ai_pipeline.rs:2207-2208). The harness cannot distinguish three classes of marker-bearing output:\n\n**Class A — *intended* confirmation**: the marker text appears in stdout because the cap's primitive actually fired. For XXE: an internal general entity expanded to the marker (`<!ENTITY x \"TOP_SECRET_XXE\">` + `<r>&x;</r>`). For DESERIALISATION: a REDUCE opcode invoked `builtins.print('TOP_SECRET_PICKLE')`.\n\n**Class B — *literal reflection***: the marker text appears in stdout because the payload BYTES CONTAIN THE MARKER LITERAL and the harness's normal text-processing path echoes them. For XXE, the payload `<r>TOP_SECRET_XXE</r>` is well-formed XML with NO DOCTYPE, NO `<!ENTITY>`, NO `<!ELEMENT>` — expat parses it, CharacterDataHandler fires on the text node and appends `\"TOP_SECRET_XXE\"` to `out`, `print(''.join(out))` emits the marker, oracle fires, candidate promotes to Verified. The candidate's `cap=XXE` is registered DESPITE the payload never invoking any XML-external-entity feature — it is just a plain text node. For DESERIALISATION, the equivalent class: a pickle payload that pushes a STRING containing the marker onto the stack and then RAISES an UnpicklingError (e.g. truncated stream after the STRING op): `VTOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\n` followed by an invalid opcode → the `except` clause prints `deserialise-error: <msg-containing-stack-state>`. Pickle's exception messages on malformed streams sometimes include partial stack contents in Python 3.x debug builds; even where they do not, the LLM can engineer a payload whose error message contains the marker: e.g. `b'(S\"TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\"\\n.'` — wait, that parses cleanly (puts a tuple on the stack with one string, STOP); stdout stays empty in the success path. But `b'(S\"TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\"\\n<INVALID>'` raises `UnpicklingError: unknown opcode '<'`; the exception's `__str__` is `'unknown opcode '<''`, which does NOT contain the marker. However: `pickle.loads(b'cTOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\nNOT_A_MODULE\\n.')` raises `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'TOP_SECRET_PICKLE'` — the marker IS in the exception message, the `except` clause prints `'deserialise-error: No module named 'TOP_SECRET_PICKLE''`, oracle fires, candidate promotes. The harness has confirmed that pickle can be coerced into emitting attacker-controlled text in an error message — NOT that the candidate code has a deserialisation vulnerability.\n\n**Class C — *cross-cap reflection***: payload bytes contain markers for OTHER caps that bleed into this oracle. The current XXE marker `TOP_SECRET_XXE` and DESERIALISATION marker `TOP_SECRET_PICKLE` do not collide with SQLi's `TOP_SECRET` in the substring sense the way PATH_TRAVERSAL's `TOP_SECRET_TRAV` does (sentinel #67) — both new markers are strict supersets of `TOP_SECRET`. So a stdout containing `TOP_SECRET_XXE` ALSO satisfies the SQLi oracle's substring search for `TOP_SECRET`. If a future cross-cap harness or replay or chain-reasoning surface evaluates multiple oracles against the same stdout (e.g. the candidate row's `cap` field is mutated after the run via set_chain / overwrite — sentinel #27), an XXE-confirmation stdout becomes a SQLi-confirmation stdout too. Sentinel #67's recommended mitigation (`builtin_oracle_markers_are_pairwise_non_substring`) was NOT implemented in this diff; the new markers worsen the collision graph (SQLi's `TOP_SECRET` is now a substring of THREE other markers: `TOP_SECRET_TRAV`, `TOP_SECRET_XXE`, `TOP_SECRET_PICKLE`).\n\nThe practical consequence: an LLM-emitted suggested_payload_hint that *literally contains the marker text anywhere in its bytes* — including as a benign XML text node, an unrelated string in a pickle stream, or a comment-like token the harness happens to surface in an error message — promotes any candidate row of the matching cap to Verified, with zero exploitation actually occurring. The candidate-row authorship surface (the LLM prompted on attacker-controlled repo content) is a known weak link (sentinel #66); this finding describes how the VERIFIER converts that weak link into a Verified row without the harness's protection mechanism interposing. The benign-control mechanism does not catch this because the benign control is a fixed string that does NOT contain the marker; the test verifies `benign_oracle_fired == false` against a SPECIFIC benign string, not against ALL strings-without-side-effects.\n\nThe XXE harness is structurally MORE vulnerable to Class B than DESERIALISATION because the canonical XXE shape is literally `<r>TOP_SECRET_XXE</r>` — which is what the candidate's `suggested_payload_hint` will look like for any LLM that does not understand the difference between \"text containing the marker\" and \"text causing entity expansion to the marker\". DESERIALISATION is structurally MORE vulnerable to Class A's RCE primitive (finding #72), but Class B applies to both: the harness output is text, the oracle is substring, the payload is attacker-influenced bytes.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #65 (coverage-class bias on intent — payloads the harness logically cannot exercise); this finding describes the opposite — payloads the harness CAN superficially exercise but that DO NOT prove the cap's primitive. Distinct from sentinel #67 (marker collision across caps) — this finding describes collision WITHIN a single cap between intended-fire and literal-reflection.\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is the *semantic gap* between \"oracle matches X\" and \"primitive fired\" — a property of the oracle/harness pair, not a code-flow sink.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) **require the marker to appear in the harness's INTENDED output channel, not in stdout indiscriminately**: for XXE, split `print(''.join(out))` from the exception branch and use a structured stdout — `print('PARSED:' + ''.join(out))` in the success branch and `print('ERROR:' + str(e))` in the exception branch; have the oracle match `\\nPARSED:<...>TOP_SECRET_XXE` (a regex anchored after the PARSED tag), so an error message containing the marker does not fire. For DESERIALISATION, the success branch is `pickle.loads(@PAYLOAD)` with NO `print()` — the marker must come from inside the REDUCE call's invoked callable, not from the harness wrapper; that distinction is preserved naturally because the REDUCE-derived print writes BEFORE the harness emits anything. Add `print('END_HARNESS')` after `pickle.loads`; have the oracle match `TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\nEND_HARNESS` — a marker that only appears in an error message will lack the `END_HARNESS` suffix and not fire.\n\n(2) **strip the marker from the payload's literal bytes before invoking the oracle**: in `Oracle::OutputContains::is_match`, search `stdout - payload_bytes` (i.e., redact any byte run from stdout that matches a substring of payload); if the only marker hit is inside the redacted region, the oracle does not fire. Implementation: search the stdout for `payload_bytes` substring(s); if found, replace those regions with `\\x00`s before searching for the marker. Catches Class B reflections in O(n) without changing the harness shape.\n\n(3) **assert in the table sentinel test (sentinel #69 mitigation #1) that a payload of `payload_byte_string = marker.as_bytes().to_vec()` does NOT fire the oracle** — i.e., explicitly verify that literal-reflection cannot promote. The unit test today does not enumerate this case; the e2e tests use a hand-engineered Class A payload that exercises entity expansion.\n\n(4) **for DESERIALISATION specifically, distinguish opcodes statically via `pickletools.genops` and have the oracle fire on opcode-class, not on stdout substring** (the alternative harness shape from finding #72 mitigation 2 also addresses this).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit tests in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module). `xxe_harness_does_not_promote_on_literal_marker_text` — insert a CandidateFindingRecord with `cap=\"XXE\"` and `suggested_payload_hint=Some(\"<r>TOP_SECRET_XXE</r>\".to_string())`; today the harness's CharacterDataHandler emits the marker and the oracle fires → `report.candidates_promoted == 1` → candidate Verified. Under mitigation (2) (literal-stripping in `OutputContains::is_match`) or mitigation (1) (structured stdout tag), assert `report.candidates_promoted == 0` and the row's status is `Dismissed` (or `Inconclusive` per finding #68's mitigation). `pickle_harness_does_not_promote_on_error_message_marker_reflection` — insert candidate with `suggested_payload_hint=Some(\"cTOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\n.\".to_string())` — pickle interprets `c<module>\\n<name>\\n` as GLOBAL but `<name>` is empty after the newline; the exception message is `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'TOP_SECRET_PICKLE'`; the `except` clause prints it; oracle fires today; assert it does NOT fire under mitigation (1)."
}

