record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/payload_runner.rs",
  "line": 414,
  "cap": "VERIFIER_DEPLOY_RUNTIME_SKEW",
  "endpoint": "internal: HarnessLang::argv (payload_runner.rs:411-417) hard-codes `python3` as argv[0] for python harnesses; pick_lang (:420-426) accepts python/python3/py → HarnessLang::Python; render_synthesised (:435-463) emits a `.py` file the runner then spawns under the sandbox lane. The new diff routes XXE (ai_pipeline.rs:2162-2178) and DESERIALISATION (:2179-2190) through this path; previously every covered cap was shell-only.",
  "rationale": "The diff is the first time the synthetic-auto-promote pipeline depends on a non-shell runtime. Before the diff, every covered cap rendered to `.sh` and spawned via `sh` (HarnessLang::Shell, argv[0]=\"sh\"); POSIX `sh` is present on every supported host. After the diff, XXE and DESERIALISATION candidates require `python3` ON THE SAME HOST AS THE VERIFIER LANE — not in the candidate's repo, not declared in the candidate row, not gated by `nyctos doctor`. Operator deployments without `python3` in `$PATH` (Alpine without the `python3` apk, distroless containers, minimal CI images that pin to busybox, BSDs with python at `/usr/local/bin/python3` outside the sandbox PATH, hosts where python3 is namespaced under `/opt/python` and not symlinked) will observe SandboxError::Spawn for every XXE / DESERIALISATION verify attempt.\n\nThree concrete primitives the gap enables:\n\n(1) **Silent coverage degradation tied to host environment**: a deployment on host A (python3 present) confirms XXE / DESERIALISATION candidates and grows `findings_by_cap` for those caps; the same nyctos build on host B (python3 absent) Dismisses every such candidate via spawn-failure. Two operators looking at the same repo through nyctos see different results based on a host-runtime quirk that is invisible at the config and audit-log layer. Compare to shell harnesses, which are deterministic across hosts.\n\n(2) **Per-path promotion-rate bias** (chains with sentinel #65): the per-path promotion rate is computed from (Promoted vs (Promoted + Dismissed)). Spawn-failure for a python harness lands as Dismissed (no oracle, no marker hit). On python3-less hosts, EVERY XXE / DESERIALISATION candidate's source path ratchets toward rate=0 → future AI budget is starved from that path. The bias is not a property of the code under test but a property of the OPERATOR'S HOST, which the AI exploration loop has no introspection into. Operators on python3-less hosts unwittingly bias the AI scheduler away from python-heavy repositories (where XXE / pickle.loads bugs concentrate).\n\n(3) **Doctor-surface silence**: `nyctos doctor` (main.rs:1887-1905 per sentinel #62-#64 / #71) prints budget caps, sandbox backend availability, and recent failure counts — but no entry for \"python3 runtime detected for builtin-cap harnesses XXE / DESERIALISATION\". An operator running `nyctos doctor` on a python3-less host gets a green check while the verifier silently no-ops on two caps. The asymmetry between (i) operator-visible capability claim — `builtin_harness_for_cap` returns Some for XXE / DESERIALISATION → the verifier-routing table (sentinel #71) reports those caps as `[synthetic]` — and (ii) actual runtime behaviour — every spawn errors — is invisible.\n\nSecondary observations:\n\n(a) `argv` uses bare `python3` not `python3.X`. On hosts pinning a non-default minor version (`python3` → /usr/bin/python3.7 on RHEL7), the rendered harness's syntax matters. The new XXE / DESERIALISATION invokes use `try:\\n    parser.Parse(@PAYLOAD, True)\\n    print(''.join(out))\\nexcept Exception as e:\\n    print('parse-error:', e)` — multi-line strings as f-strings or walrus operators are absent, so Python 3.7+ should parse. But `print(...)` semantics and pickle protocol-0 stability across 3.7-3.12 have minor variants (e.g. pickle.loads of opcode `b'V...\\n'` in 3.12 may behave differently for certain malformed streams). The harness has no version assertion.\n\n(b) `pick_lang` accepts the aliases `python`, `python3`, `py` and maps all three to `HarnessLang::Python` whose argv is `python3` — so a future maintainer who registers `lang: \"python\"` for some cap silently gets `python3` invocation, not `python`. The aliasing is fine but masks the dependency: a grep for `python3` in the spec table returns no hits (the strings are `\"python\"` at ai_pipeline.rs:2164 / :2181), but the runtime requirement is python3.\n\n(c) No fallback to `python` (the older 2/3-bridge alias). On hosts where python3 is installed as `python` and python3 is absent (rare but exists — some custom builds), the spawn fails. argv could be `[\"sh\", \"-c\", \"command -v python3 >/dev/null && exec python3 ${SCRIPT} || exec python ${SCRIPT}\"]` to fall back, but isn't.\n\n(d) `RunCapture::error` field carries the spawn-failure string but `VerifyOutcome` (ai_pipeline.rs:2044+) collapses both Errored and Dismissed-by-oracle into the same downstream status. Sentinel #68 covered this conflation for the unrelated case of caught-exception-in-harness; this finding adds spawn-failure as a third class of \"looks like Dismissed but isn't\".\n\nDistinct from sentinel #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL coverage-class bias on payload SHAPE — same statistical effect but driven by harness logic, not host environment), #68 (harness-failure indistinguishability — same downstream conflation but a different upstream cause: caught exception vs spawn failure), #72/#73/#74 (the three findings emitted today on the same diff — RCE, oracle-FP, parser narrowness; none of those address the host-runtime dependency).\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is *a host-environment dependency introduced by a single string literal* (`\"python3\"` at payload_runner.rs:414) — no taint flow, no missing escape, no logic error. The bug is the absence of (1) a startup runtime probe, (2) an operator-visible doctor surface, (3) a typed Errored vs Dismissed distinction, and (4) a fallback path. None of those absences register as a code-flow sink.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+3): (1) **probe `python3` availability at runner construction** — `PayloadRunner::default` or `PayloadRunner::with_backend` calls `which python3` (or attempts a `python3 --version` spawn with a tiny timeout); cache the result on the runner; refuse to register python harnesses (downgrade to `Errored::PythonRuntimeMissing`) when the probe fails. The verifier loop on a python3-less host then surfaces a clear error rather than silently dismissing. (2) **add a doctor-surface line** — `nyctos doctor` reports `ai-exploration synthetic-cap harness runtimes: shell [ok], python3 [ok @ /usr/bin/python3.11 — Python 3.11.6]` or `python3 [MISSING — XXE/DESERIALISATION caps disabled]`. Operators see the dependency at install time. (3) **distinguish Errored from Dismissed in the candidate status** — extend the `status` enum (currently Pending / Promoted / Dismissed) with `Errored(reason)`; the per-path promotion-rate calculation should EXCLUDE Errored rows from both numerator and denominator (don't penalise a code path because the operator's host lacks a runtime). (4) **fallback argv** — `argv = [\"sh\", \"-c\", \"command -v python3 >/dev/null && exec python3 \\\"$0\\\" || exec python \\\"$0\\\"\", harness_path]` (sound shell quoting required); this preserves coverage on the python-not-python3 host class. (5) **mark python-using caps explicitly** — when the harness lang is `python`, the verifier-routing-table doctor surface (sentinel #71 mitigation 2) shows `[synthetic(python3)]` rather than `[synthetic]`, so the runtime dependency is operator-visible without running doctor probes.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in payload_runner.rs's tests module): `python_harness_errors_when_python3_missing` — set `PATH=/nonexistent` for the test's process scope, call `runner.verify(...)` with an XXE PayloadRun; today the result is `RunCapture { oracle_fired: false, error: Some(\"sandbox spawn failed: ...\"), ... }` and the caller's downstream collapses this to Dismissed; under mitigation (3), assert the returned VerifyOutcome is `Errored { reason: PythonRuntimeMissing }` and that the candidate row's per-path promotion-rate accounting EXCLUDES this run. Doctor-surface test: `doctor_reports_python3_runtime_status` — with python3 in PATH, capture `nyctos doctor` stdout and assert it contains a line matching `python3.*ok`; with PATH cleared, assert it contains `python3.*MISSING` and the synthetic-cap routing table downgrades XXE/DESERIALISATION to `[synthetic(python3-missing)]`. End-to-end host-skew reproducer: run the same `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_xxe_cap` e2e test on (i) a host with python3 → assert `report.candidates_promoted == 1`, (ii) a container without python3 (e.g. busybox `FROM busybox` with the nyctos binary copied in) → today the assertion fires `assert_eq!(report.candidates_promoted, 1, \"{report:?}\")` and the test FAILS with no actionable error message; under mitigation (1), the test should surface `PythonRuntimeMissing` in the report and the assertion should be conditional on a `host_supports_python3()` predicate."
