record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2187,
  "cap": "DESERIALISATION_FORMAT_MONOCULTURE",
  "endpoint": "internal: builtin_harness_for_cap(\"DESERIALISATION\") at ai_pipeline.rs:2179-2190 imports ONLY `pickle` and invokes ONLY `pickle.loads(@PAYLOAD)`. The cap label `DESERIALISATION` as emitted by NovelFindingDiscovery covers a category that is intentionally broader than any single deserialisation library — the rule-hint patterns the discovery prompt receives include `py.pickle.loads-userinput`, `py.yaml.load-userinput`, `py.marshal.loads-userinput`, and equivalents — and the cap name itself (no per-format suffix) signals the design intent that all formats route to the same cap.",
  "rationale": "The harness is a SINGLE-FORMAT verifier mapped to a MULTI-FORMAT cap label. Distinct from finding #72 (VERIFIER_ARBITRARY_CODE_EXEC — which is about pickle.loads being TOO POWERFUL, an over-coverage hazard) and orthogonal to finding #74 (XXE_COVERAGE_TUNNEL_VISION — which is the equivalent narrowness for XXE). This finding is about pickle.loads being TOO NARROW for the cap's named scope: an under-coverage hazard at the candidate-row level. Both axes (over-power + under-coverage) can hold simultaneously.\n\nCandidate sinks the cap label legitimately covers, none of which the harness can confirm:\n\n(1) **PyYAML `yaml.load(stream, Loader=yaml.Loader)` / `yaml.unsafe_load(stream)`** — historically the most-exploited Python deserialisation vector in production code. Canonical exploit payload: `!!python/object/apply:os.system ['echo TOP_SECRET_PICKLE']`. This is YAML text, not pickle bytes; pickle.loads raises `UnpicklingError(\"invalid load key, '!'.\")` on the first byte. The harness's `except Exception as e: print('deserialise-error:', e)` (ai_pipeline.rs:2188) prints the exception message which does NOT contain `TOP_SECRET_PICKLE` (the `!` byte echo from pickle errors does not span the full payload); oracle no-fires; candidate Dismissed.\n\n(2) **`marshal.loads`** — CPython's internal bytecode format; payload is a marshal-protocol-3 byte-stream with a different header magic than pickle. pickle.loads on marshal bytes raises a parse error; exception message does not contain the marker; oracle no-fires.\n\n(3) **`dill.loads`** — pickle superset with extended opcodes (CODE_PYCODE, OBJECT_BY_REF). Some dill payloads ARE valid pickle (the basic REDUCE chain in finding #72's discussion), but dill-specific opcodes crash plain pickle.loads with `UnpicklingError(\"unknown opcode '\\\\x91'\")` etc. Coverage matches only the subset where dill ≡ pickle.\n\n(4) **`jsonpickle.decode`** — JSON-textual with embedded `py/object` markers. Payload: `{\"py/object\": \"os.system\", \"args\": [\"echo TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\"]}`. pickle.loads on JSON bytes raises `UnpicklingError(\"invalid load key, '{'.\")`; no exploit.\n\n(5) **`shelve.open` followed by key access** — pickle-under-the-hood but file-based; requires the harness to write a shelve file FIRST and the candidate to read it second. The harness skips the file-stage step.\n\n(6) **`_pickle.Unpickler` with subclassed `find_class` allowlist** — same on-the-wire format but the candidate's vulnerable code wraps Unpickler with a partial-allowlist that the synthesised payload tries to bypass via opcode-level tricks (STACK_GLOBAL, INST). The plain `pickle.loads` harness does NOT exercise the subclassed Unpickler; the exploitability question (\"does the allowlist actually block this payload?\") is unanswered.\n\n(7) **Cross-language sinks if the discovery prompt is ever expanded to polyglot repos**: `ObjectInputStream.readObject` (Java), `Marshal.load` (Ruby), `unserialize` (PHP), `BinaryFormatter.Deserialize` (.NET), `node-serialize.unserialize` (Node). The cap label `DESERIALISATION` is language-neutral; the harness is python-only.\n\n(8) **Apache Avro / MessagePack / Protocol Buffers with unsafe schema-evolution** — protocol-buffer reflection sinks have a documented deserialisation gadget surface; the harness has no path.\n\nConsequence chain:\n\n- An LLM-emitted DESERIALISATION candidate at `yaml.unsafe_load(req.body)` in a Flask handler is REAL. PayloadSynthesis, conditioned on the candidate's actual sink code, emits the canonical yaml-object-apply payload. The verifier dispatches to the synthetic pickle harness. pickle.loads rejects. Candidate Dismissed. The per-path promotion rate (sentinel #65) ratchets DOWN for that path. Future AI exploration budget on that path is starved. Real yaml.load vulnerabilities hide in the noise.\n\n- Compounds with finding #73 (ORACLE_LITERAL_REFLECTION_BYPASS) — most non-pickle payloads will reach the exception branch, which prints the exception's `__str__`. A yaml payload whose first non-ASCII byte happens to be in the exception's bytes-echo region could LITERAL-REFLECT the marker into stdout and spuriously promote the candidate as a false positive — same architectural defect surfaces here at a different cap.\n\n- Compounds with finding #72 (VERIFIER_ARBITRARY_CODE_EXEC) — yaml-format candidates are not just rejected; they're rejected BEFORE the pickle.loads RCE primitive runs, which from a sandbox-safety angle is incidentally protective for yaml-shaped payloads. But this is a side effect, not a designed property.\n\nDistinct from #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL payload-shape coverage — different cap, same architectural pattern of one-to-many label mapped to one-to-one harness). Distinct from #66 (provenance gap — orthogonal). Distinct from #74 (XXE coverage-tunnel-vision — same pattern at a different cap). Static pass missed because the bug is in the *labelling-to-engine mapping*, not in any code-flow sink.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+3 minimum; 2 is the architectural fix):\n\n(1) **Split the cap label at the discovery layer** — emit `DESERIALISATION_PICKLE`, `DESERIALISATION_YAML`, `DESERIALISATION_MARSHAL`, etc., so the harness selection at `builtin_harness_for_cap` is per-format. The discovery prompt receives the candidate's import statements + sink-line and emits the precise sub-cap. Add per-sub-cap harness entries for yaml (import yaml; yaml.unsafe_load(@PAYLOAD)) and marshal (import marshal; marshal.loads(@PAYLOAD)); leave the others as `None` (route to candidate-pipeline).\n\n(2) **Make the harness POLYMORPHIC over a hint** — extend `CandidateFindingRecord` with `harness_format: Option<String>` (`\"pickle\" | \"yaml\" | \"marshal\" | \"dill\" | \"jsonpickle\"`); `builtin_harness_for_cap` consults the hint to pick the import + invoke; absent hint, return `None` so the row routes to candidate-pipeline. Preserves the single-cap label while letting the harness specialise.\n\n(3) **Emit `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessFormatMismatch }`** when the runner detects payload-bytes don't lex as the expected format. For pickle: `payload[0] not in valid_pickle_opcode_set` (the set is small and well-defined — see `pickletools.opcodes`); for yaml: first non-whitespace byte not in `{'-', '!', '?', '{', '['} ∪ ASCII-alpha`; etc. Bypasses finding #73's literal-reflection false-positive surface and ALSO bypasses finding #72's RCE primitive for malformed payloads.\n\n(4) **Document the format-monoculture explicitly** in the doc comment above `builtin_harness_for_cap(\"DESERIALISATION\")` at ai_pipeline.rs:2182-2186 — currently the comment says \"feed the payload bytes verbatim into `pickle.loads`\" which is correct mechanically but obscures the cap-vs-engine narrowness. A reviewer reading the comment cannot tell the cap label covers yaml/marshal/dill/etc.\n\n(5) **Add the behavioural regression test family** (sentinel #69 mitigation #1) with a yaml-payload test: `deserialisation_harness_does_not_promote_yaml_payload` — drives the runner with a canonical yaml-bomb hint and asserts the verdict is NOT `Confirmed` (today's behaviour by accident; tomorrow's behaviour by design under mitigations 3+5).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module): `deserialisation_harness_signals_format_mismatch_for_yaml_payload` — construct a CandidateFindingRecord with cap=\"DESERIALISATION\" and `suggested_payload_hint=Some(\"!!python/object/apply:builtins.print ['TOP_SECRET_PICKLE']\".to_string())`. Drive `run_payload_verification_pass` against a tempdir workspace. TODAY: the row lands `Dismissed` (pickle.loads raises UnpicklingError on the leading `!`; oracle no-fires). Under mitigation (3): assert the row lands `Inconclusive` with `reason == HarnessFormatMismatch` — NOT `Dismissed` — so the per-path promotion-rate signal is not biased against the candidate's path. Under mitigation (1) the discovery layer would emit `cap=DESERIALISATION_YAML`; assert `builtin_harness_for_cap(\"DESERIALISATION_YAML\")` returns a yaml-harness `Some(...)`. Production reproducer: write a Flask handler `@app.post('/load')\\ndef load(): return yaml.unsafe_load(request.data)`, scan via nyctos, observe NovelFindingDiscovery emits a DESERIALISATION candidate, observe the verifier ran the pickle harness and dismissed the candidate, observe the finding row never lands Verified — demonstrating the false-negative primitive. End-to-end mutation: under mitigation (1), repeat the scan; observe the candidate now lands Verified via the yaml-specific synthetic harness OR routes to the candidate-pipeline for LLM-spec verification."
}

