record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2171,
  "cap": "PYTHON_SETUP_FAILURE_INDISTINGUISHABILITY",
  "endpoint": "internal: both new python harnesses run their setup imports at MODULE TOP-LEVEL with NO try/except guard. XXE setup at ai_pipeline.rs:2170-2174: `import xml.parsers.expat`, `parser = xml.parsers.expat.ParserCreate()`, `out = []`, `parser.CharacterDataHandler = lambda d: out.append(d)`. DESERIALISATION setup at :2187: `import pickle`. The setup lines splice into the rendered script by `render_synthesised` at payload_runner.rs:453-456 verbatim; only the invoke body has try/except (ai_pipeline.rs:2176, :2188).",
  "rationale": "Python's top-level uncaught exception terminates the interpreter with exit code 1 AND writes the traceback to STDERR, NOT stdout. The oracle reads stdout (per `Oracle::OutputContains` dispatch in payload_runner.rs). Setup-time failure modes that produce empty-stdout + nonzero-exit indistinguishable from an honest \"the payload did not exhibit the bug\" verdict:\n\n(a) **minimal-stdlib lane**: a future sandbox lane built on `python:3.x-alpine` minimal or a security-hardened distro with `python3-minimal` (Debian's split) may ship the `xml` package but not `xml.parsers.expat` — Debian's `python3-minimal` does not include the `xml` namespace package at all; full `python3` is required. `import xml.parsers.expat` raises `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'xml'`. The script aborts before the invoke ever runs.\n\n(b) **expat C-library version mismatch**: `xml.parsers.expat` is a CPython C-extension that links against the system libexpat. If the lane's libexpat is absent or its `Expat_*` ABI mismatches the interpreter's expected ABI (libexpat ABI breaks between 2.4 and 2.5 around `XML_SetReparseDeferralEnabled`), import raises `ImportError: libexpat.so.1: cannot open shared object file` or `ImportError: undefined symbol: XML_SetReparseDeferralEnabled`.\n\n(c) **alternate interpreter**: if the runner ever runs python harnesses on PyPy (a future performance optimisation) — PyPy's `xml.parsers.expat` is reimplemented atop `_elementtree`; the `ParserCreate` symbol exists but `parser.CharacterDataHandler = ...` accepts only specific signatures that CPython's expat does not enforce as strictly. The setup line `parser.CharacterDataHandler = lambda d: out.append(d)` may raise `TypeError` on PyPy. Same indistinguishability path.\n\n(d) **sandbox seccomp filter**: a hardened sandbox profile blocks `openat` against the system library directory (`/usr/lib/python3.*/lib-dynload/`); the C-extension's `dlopen` call fails; import raises `ImportError`. Today's `process` lane permits this, but a future `firecracker` lane with a stricter seccomp profile (the sandbox's intended evolution per design docs) breaks the import.\n\n(e) **bytecode cache poisoning**: a stale `__pycache__` for `xml/parsers/expat.cpython-3X.pyc` on the lane image from a previous python interpreter version causes import to fail with `RuntimeError: bad magic number in '<path>': <bytes>` or silently succeed against the wrong implementation.\n\n(f) **pickle on stripped-down lane**: `import pickle` is rarely unavailable since pickle is pure-python with a `_pickle` C-extension fallback; but some hardened distributions strip `_pickle` AND ship `pickle.py` that fails to import the C accelerator with `ImportError` if `_pickle.Pickler` is missing. The DESERIALISATION harness's invoke calls `pickle.loads(@PAYLOAD)` — `pickle.loads` dispatches to either C or pure-python implementation; both should work even on the stripped lane, BUT if `pickle.py` itself has a top-of-module side-effect that fails (e.g. on a re-exec'd `cPickle`-emulating shim), `import pickle` aborts.\n\nFor every (a)-(f) failure mode the runner observes:\n- stdout: empty (top-of-script exception fires before any print)\n- stderr: traceback (\"Traceback (most recent call last):\\n File ...\\n ModuleNotFoundError ...\")\n- exit code: 1\n\nThe oracle's `OutputContains` check on stdout returns false. `classify_status` (payload_runner.rs:504-509) maps `Exited(1)` to `(1, false)`. The runner's verdict-emission logic (per the call sites the prior sentinel findings reference) does NOT distinguish `oracle_fired=false because the program ran cleanly and did not exhibit the bug` from `oracle_fired=false because the program never reached the invoke at all`. The candidate row lands `Dismissed` (or equivalent NotConfirmed).\n\n**This is the same architectural fork as sentinel #68 — but the mechanism is different**:\n\n- Sentinel #68 (HARNESS_FAILURE_INDISTINGUISHABILITY) is specifically about the SHELL prelude `set -u` without `set -e`, applied to PATH_TRAVERSAL / SQLi / OS_COMMAND / CMDi (lang=\"shell\"). #68's mitigation is `set -eu` + capture exit code + per-cap setup_verification.\n- THIS finding (#76) is about PYTHON top-level imports without try/except, applied to XXE / DESERIALISATION (lang=\"python\"). Python has NO equivalent of `set -e` — top-level exceptions ALREADY abort; the fix is the OPPOSITE direction: wrap imports in `try/except ImportError as e: sys.stderr.write('SETUP_IMPORT_FAILED:'+str(e)+'\\n'); sys.exit(73)` so the failure produces a DISTINGUISHABLE exit code, and have `classify_status` map exit code 73 to `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessSetupFailed }`.\n\nThe mitigation surface differs from #68 in three places:\n\n(i) the wrapping mechanism (try/except per-import vs `set -eu` prelude);\n(ii) the abort-signal channel (sys.exit(73) explicit vs shell `set -e` implicit-on-failure);\n(iii) the per-language uniformity surface — render_synthesised could install the python try/except boilerplate uniformly across all python harnesses by emitting an `import_module` helper at the top of the script and rewriting `import xml.parsers.expat` setup lines into `import_module('xml.parsers.expat', as_=\"xml_parsers_expat\")` — but this is invasive and changes the cap-table author's mental model. A lighter touch: render_synthesised wraps the ENTIRE script in `try: ... except (ImportError, ModuleNotFoundError) as e: sys.stderr.write('SETUP_IMPORT_FAILED:'+str(e)+'\\n'); sys.exit(73)` — but this also catches ImportError raised DURING the invoke (e.g. a REDUCE-chain in a DESERIALISATION payload that imports a missing module — which we WANT to count as an exploit attempt, not a setup failure). A precise fix requires distinguishing import-time vs run-time exceptions, which is a known-tricky python idiom.\n\nProduction primitives:\n\n(1) **CI-host-specific dismissal**: a deployment of nyctos on a build agent with a customised python image (`python:3.12-slim` retagged without `python3-xml`) silently dismisses every XXE candidate while operator-visible state shows the verifier ran. The operator sees the candidate as `Dismissed` and treats it as a verified-negative; the bug stays in the user's code. Distinct from #68's primitive because the failure mode is import-error rather than shell-mkdir EACCES; the SAME architectural fork swallows both.\n\n(2) **Dependency-on-stdlib poisoning**: an attacker who lands a PR adding `import xml.parsers.expat` to an unrelated module that gets shipped into the sandbox-runtime base image silently can change which modules the runtime has loaded (or not, since imports are cached). More directly, an attacker who CAN influence the lane image (supply-chain on the python base image: a backdoored `python3-xml` package) gains a primitive to silently dismiss the entire XXE cap class for that operator.\n\n(3) **Incident-time blind spot**: during a runtime upgrade of the lane's python interpreter (3.12 → 3.13), the C-extension ABI changes; the operator runs a nyctos batch; every XXE candidate dismisses; the operator interprets this as \"the codebase has no XXE issues today\" and ships; the actual signal was \"the verifier ran broken for an hour\". No surface today exposes this.\n\nDistinct from sentinel #68 (shell `set -e` indistinguishability — different lang, different mitigation). Distinct from sentinel #66 (provenance gap — same-shape problem at a different layer). Distinct from sentinel #73 (literal reflection — about invoke-time exception PRINTING; this is about setup-time exception ABORTING). Distinct from sentinel #74 (XXE coverage tunnel vision — that's about what the harness's parser CAN'T do when running cleanly; this is about the harness FAILING to run at all). Distinct from sentinel #72 (RCE primitive — that's the success-path concern; this is the setup-fail-path concern).\n\nStatic pass missed because (i) the bug is the *absence* of try/except around imports plus (ii) the runner's *failure to map nonzero exit + empty stdout to a distinct verdict*; neither half is a taint sink, and the pair only becomes a bug under composition.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2 minimum):\n\n(1) **Wrap python harness setup in a guard pattern at render time**. Concretely, prepend to the python script: `import sys` (always), then transform each `import X` setup line into `try: import X\\nexcept (ImportError, ModuleNotFoundError) as _e: sys.stderr.write('SETUP_IMPORT_FAILED:'+str(_e)+'\\n'); sys.exit(73)`. Implement at payload_runner.rs:447-456 in the `match lang { Python => ... }` arm so every python harness gets the wrap uniformly without each cap-table entry repeating the boilerplate. Non-import setup lines (e.g. `parser = xml.parsers.expat.ParserCreate()`) get wrapped in a separate `try/except Exception` with `sys.exit(74)` for non-import setup failure.\n\n(2) **Extend `classify_status` (payload_runner.rs:504)** to map exit code 73 → `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessSetupFailed { kind: \"import\" } }` and 74 → `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessSetupFailed { kind: \"init\" } }`. The runner's verdict-emission then routes the candidate row to `Pending` (left for re-examination) rather than `Dismissed`. The per-path promotion-rate signal (sentinel #65) is not biased; sentinel #62-#64's budget-cap mechanics are unaffected.\n\n(3) **Add a per-lane health probe** — before any python-lang harness runs on a new lane image, the runner executes a probe `python3 -c 'import sys, xml.parsers.expat, pickle; sys.stdout.write(\"ok\")'` and refuses to dispatch python-lang harnesses if the probe fails — surfacing the environment problem to the operator via an `AgentEvent::LaneHealthFailed` (a new event type to add to the AgentEvent enum). This is a more proactive variant of (1)+(2) and gates the failure at run-start instead of per-candidate.\n\n(4) **Add a behavioural regression test family** (sentinel #69 mitigation #1, analogous to the shell-side test for sentinel #68): `python_harness_signals_inconclusive_when_setup_import_fails` — construct a `HarnessSpecInput { cap: \"XXE\", lang: \"python\", setup: vec![\"import nonexistent_module_xxx\".to_string()], invoke: \"print('TOP_SECRET_XXE')\".to_string(), teardown: vec![] }`; drive `PayloadRunner::verify`; today assert the verdict is `NotConfirmed` (the bug); post-mitigation assert it is `Inconclusive` (the fix).\n\n(5) **Update the doc comments** above the python-lang harnesses at ai_pipeline.rs:2162 and :2179 to document the setup-import contract: \"imports MUST be wrapped in try/except by the runner-side helper; raw imports here will silently dismiss candidates on a degraded lane\".",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-sandbox's payload_runner.rs tests module): `python_harness_top_level_import_failure_signals_inconclusive` — construct `HarnessSpecInput { cap: \"XXE\".to_string(), lang: \"python\".to_string(), setup: vec![\"import nonexistent_module_xxx_xxx\".to_string()], invoke: \"print('TOP_SECRET_XXE')\".to_string(), teardown: vec![] }`. Drive `PayloadRunner::verify` with `vuln_payload = b\"<r></r>\"`, `benign_payload = b\"N.\"`, `oracle = Oracle::OutputContains { marker: \"TOP_SECRET_XXE\".to_string() }`. TODAY's behaviour: the import raises ModuleNotFoundError at top-level, python exits 1, stdout is empty, the verdict is `NotConfirmed` (the bug); assert `result.verdict == VerifyVerdict::NotConfirmed` to capture the today-state. Under mitigation (1)+(2): the rendered script catches the ImportError, exits with code 73, classify_status maps to `Inconclusive { reason: HarnessSetupFailed }`; assert `matches!(result.verdict, VerifyVerdict::Inconclusive { .. })`. End-to-end primitive on a real machine: build a minimal python image without expat (`docker run --rm python:3.12-alpine sh -c 'apk del expat-dev 2>/dev/null; python3 -c \"import xml.parsers.expat\"'` — observe ImportError); drive the existing `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_xxe_cap` e2e test on that environment; observe today's run dismisses the candidate with no operator-visible signal that the verifier was broken; under mitigation (1)+(2)+(3), the run instead surfaces a `LaneHealthFailed` event and the candidate row lands `Pending`. Combined-with-#68 reproducer: an integration test that uses BOTH a python-minimal lane (breaks XXE / DESERIALISATION harnesses via import) AND a chmod-0500-workspace condition (breaks PATH_TRAVERSAL / SQLi harnesses via mkdir EACCES); today all four caps silently dismiss; under combined mitigations from #68 + #76, all four route to `Inconclusive` with distinct reason codes."
}

