record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 4923,
  "cap": "PICKLE_PROTOCOL_COVERAGE_GAP",
  "endpoint": "internal: `verifier_promotes_quarantined_candidate_for_deserialisation_cap` (ai_pipeline.rs:4895-4936) seeds exactly one DESERIALISATION payload at :4923 — `\"cbuiltins\\nprint\\n(VTOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\ntR.\"` — which is a strict protocol-0 pickle (every byte is in 0x20..0x7E; only `c` GLOBAL, `(` MARK, `V` UNICODE, `t` TUPLE, `R` REDUCE, `.` STOP). The harness invoke at ai_pipeline.rs:2188 calls `pickle.loads(@PAYLOAD)` which CPython accepts for protocols 0 through 5; no test seeds a protocol-1+ payload. This is the *test-side* coverage gap orthogonal to #72 (the *harness-side* over-power), #75-FORMAT (cap-wide multi-format gap), and #76 (setup-time fail-fast gap).",
  "rationale": "Pickle's six protocol versions each add opcodes ABSENT from earlier protocols that can express the same REDUCE-callable RCE primitive (#72) under different on-the-wire encodings:\n\n- **Protocol 0** (ASCII; test coverage): `c<mod>\\n<name>\\n(V<unicode>\\nt R.` → ~30 bytes for `print('marker')` REDUCE.\n- **Protocol 1**: binary alternates (`K` BININT1, `q`/`r` BINPUT/LONG_BINPUT); `c` GLOBAL still available.\n- **Protocol 2**: `\\x80` PROTO header, `\\x81` NEWOBJ, `\\x85`/`\\x86`/`\\x87` TUPLE1/2/3 (replace `(...t` for small tuples), EXT1-4 (`\\x82`-`\\x84`).\n- **Protocol 3**: `B` BINBYTES, `C` SHORT_BINBYTES.\n- **Protocol 4**: `\\x8a`/`\\x8b` LONG1/4, `\\x8c` SHORT_BINUNICODE, `\\x93` STACK_GLOBAL (replaces `c<mod>\\n<name>\\n` with a stack-driven form), `\\x95` FRAME (8-byte len prefix wrapping the rest of the pickle for streaming), `\\x94` MEMOIZE.\n- **Protocol 5**: `\\x96` BYTEARRAY8, `\\x97` NEXT_BUFFER, `\\x98` READONLY_BUFFER (out-of-band buffers for zero-copy ML payloads).\n\nThe same `print('TOP_SECRET_PICKLE')` REDUCE expressed in protocol 4 reads `\\x80\\x04\\x95<8-byte-len>\\x8c\\x08builtins\\x94\\x8c\\x05print\\x94\\x93\\x94)\\x8c\\x11TOP_SECRET_PICKLE\\x94\\x85\\x94R\\x94.` — distinct opcode set, FRAME-wrapped, STACK_GLOBAL instead of GLOBAL, SHORT_BINUNICODE instead of UNICODE. `python_literal` (payload_runner.rs:468-482) preserves high bytes via `\\xHH`, so a protocol-4 payload reaches `pickle.loads` byte-identical via the synthesised harness; the harness will execute it correctly. The TEST will not.\n\nThree concrete consequences:\n\n(1) **#72 mitigation (2) — static-opcode scanner — silently uncovered for protocols 2-5**: that recommended mitigation introspects pickle bytes via `pickletools.genops` and fires on dangerous-opcode classes (REDUCE/BUILD/INST/OBJ/NEWOBJ/NEWOBJ_EX/STACK_GLOBAL). A correct implementation enumerates ALL six protocol opcode tables. A buggy implementation that only handles protocol-0 opcodes silently passes a protocol-5 REDUCE chain through. The regression test today seeds ONLY protocol 0, so a future test-driven implementation of the scanner can land protocol-0-only and the existing test passes; the bug ships.\n\n(2) **Production candidates skew toward protocol 2+**: CPython's `pickle.dumps` default protocol is `DEFAULT_PROTOCOL = 4` since Python 3.8 (was 3 in 3.0+, was 2 in 2.3+). An LLM trained on modern Python code (a) generally sees `pickle.dumps(obj)` calls — which produce protocol-4 output — far more often than literal protocol-0 byte sequences; (b) under output-token budget pressure (#62-#64 USD caps), prefers shorter binary payloads over verbose ASCII. The discovery prompt's emitted `suggested_payload_hint` for DESERIALISATION candidates will skew toward protocol-2+ binary; the test pins protocol-0. The test exercises an in-distribution-rare path.\n\n(3) **Benign control `N.` is also protocol-0**: ai_pipeline.rs:2228 emits `N.` as the DESERIALISATION benign (NONE + STOP). pickle.loads accepts it under any protocol (the implicit protocol-0 framing). A future hardening that requires `pickle.loads` callers to validate `payload[0] == \\x80` (the PROTO opcode introduced in protocol 2 — i.e. \"refuse pre-protocol-2 ancient pickles to reduce attack surface\") would break the benign too. Both halves of the vuln/benign differential collapse identically; the differential mechanism's signal collapses to noise. A protocol-2+ benign — `\\x80\\x02N.` for pickle.dumps(None, protocol=2) — would preserve the differential under that hardening.\n\nDistinct from #69 (sentinel test for builtin tables is shape-only, no behavioural pass) — #69 named the absence of any behavioural assertion; THIS finding adds the further requirement that the per-cap behavioural pass for DESERIALISATION MUST iterate the protocol space (0..=5). Distinct from #72 (pickle.loads is too powerful a verifier sink) — that's about what the harness CAN do; this is about what the TEST exercises about what the harness can do. Distinct from #73 (oracle literal reflection — applies orthogonally), #75-FORMAT (pickle-vs-yaml/marshal/dill — different format, this is intra-pickle protocol-version coverage), #76 (setup-import indistinguishability — fail-fast surface, not coverage surface).\n\nStatic pass missed because the bug is a *single-row regression test on a multi-dimensional input domain* — no taint flow, no missing escape.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+3): (1) **parametric protocol test** — `deserialisation_harness_promotes_across_all_pickle_protocols`: for protocol in 0..=5, generate `pickle.dumps((builtins.print, ('TOP_SECRET_PICKLE',)), protocol=protocol)` (via a build.rs-time helper script or a `python3 -c` subprocess), seed a candidate with the resulting bytes (escape-encoded for the suggested_payload_hint string), drive `run_payload_verification_pass`, assert each protocol promotes. Today runs green at runtime (the harness accepts all six); the value is failure-detection when a future #72-mitigation lands incomplete. (2) **placeholder behavioural test for the future static-opcode scanner** — even pre-mitigation, add `pickle_static_scanner_detects_dangerous_opcodes_across_all_protocols` as an `#[ignore]`-marked test that the #72-mitigation PR un-ignores; the test enumerates the same six protocols and asserts the scanner fires on each. (3) **document the protocol-coverage requirement in the cap-table doc-comment** at ai_pipeline.rs:2182-2186: one-line note `// pickle.loads accepts protocols 0-5; the canonical regression at :4895 seeds protocol-0 only — see sentinel #77 for the cross-protocol matrix`. (4) **add a protocol-2+ benign control** — replace `N.` at ai_pipeline.rs:2228 with `\\x80\\x02N.` (or co-exist as a second benign row); this preserves differential signal under future protocol-floor hardening.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (parametric test in ai_pipeline.rs's tests module): `deserialisation_harness_promotes_across_all_pickle_protocols` — `for protocol in 0..=5 { let payload_bytes = python_dumps_print_marker_via_subprocess(protocol); insert candidate with suggested_payload_hint=Some(escape_bytes_for_pickle_literal(&payload_bytes)); drive run_payload_verification_pass; assert report.candidates_promoted == 1 }`. The helper invokes `python3 -c \"import pickle, builtins, sys; sys.stdout.buffer.write(pickle.dumps((builtins.print, ('TOP_SECRET_PICKLE',)), protocol=int(sys.argv[1])))\" <protocol>` and captures raw bytes. Mutation reproducer for the #72-mitigation static-scanner: implement the scanner with a deliberately-buggy `if payload[0] in b'(cV(': scan_protocol_0()` — the parametric test fails on protocols 2-5, demonstrating the regression catches a real implementation bug. Cross-protocol-benign assertion: add `deserialisation_benign_protocol_2_does_not_fire_oracle` — `payload = b\"\\x80\\x02N.\"`; drive runner; assert `benign_run.oracle_fired == false` AND `result.verdict == VerifyVerdict::Confirmed` when paired with the protocol-2 vuln payload from above."
