record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-types/src/run.rs",
  "line": 21,
  "cap": "WIRE_SHAPE_FIELD_EXPANSION",
  "endpoint": "internal: `RunRecord` (nyctos-types/src/run.rs:21-36) `#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, TS)]` — no `#[serde(skip_serializing)]` on operator-internal columns; no `#[serde(deserialize_with)]` clamp on `started_at: i64` / `finished_at: Option<i64>` / `wall_clock_ms: Option<i64>` / `total_ai_spend_usd_micros: i64`; no allow-list on `status: String` / `triggered_by: String` (despite the doc comment at run.rs:9-12 noting that the runtime enums `RunStatus` and `TriggeredBy` deliberately live in `nyctos_core::store::run` because the wire form is `String`). Outbound sinks: `list_runs` (router.rs:1158-1162) → `GET /api/v1/runs?status=<raw>` returns `Vec<RunRecord>` with no project-scoping filter; `get_run` (router.rs:1164-1174) → `GET /api/v1/runs/:id` returns `RunRecord` by primary-key lookup with no project-membership check (the `runs` table at migrations/0001_v1.sql:41-52 deliberately has NO `project_id` column — a run is project-less in the schema). Inbound latent sinks (post-hoist Deserialize is reachable from any future axum handler): the `id: String` is the primary key the store reads/writes from at store/run.rs:103-119 (`SELECT ... WHERE status = ?`) and `core::store::run::insert` / `finish` (run.rs:122-145); `total_ai_spend_usd_micros: i64` is the per-run AI-budget ledger the verifier reads to enforce the per-run-USD cap referenced from sentinel #62-#64 (cost-cap discovery findings); `git_ref: Option<String>` is a refspec the daemon may pass into git CLI calls on replay paths (cf. #80's GIT_SSH_COMMAND sink and ai_pipeline.rs:3111-3120 RunRecord-construction sites that produce the same shape that flows into git pivot operations).",
  "rationale": "Two distinct security regressions ship in the same six-line type-hoist diff. Sentinel #78/#79/#80 named the architectural pattern (Deserialize hoist of a `nyctos-core` type into `nyctos-types` without per-field validators); this finding pins the *concrete recurrence* on `RunRecord` and adds the *outbound* field-widening half of the failure that #78-#80 did not have (`RepoSource`/`GitAuth` were never network-Serialised; `RunRecord` IS, and the hoist changed the Serialised shape).\n\n(A) **Outbound field expansion to all `/api/v1/runs` callers.** The OLD frontend hand-rolled interface (client.ts:109-118, now deleted by the diff) carried `{ id, started_at_ms, finished_at_ms, status, wall_clock_ms, succeeded, inconclusive, failed }` — seven fields, all summary statistics. The new wire shape (run.rs:22-36, types.gen.ts:162) drops the three counters (`succeeded`/`inconclusive`/`failed`) and ADDS three operator-internal columns: `triggered_by`, `git_ref`, `parent_run_id`. The router endpoints DID NOT change; they previously returned the SAME field set because the server-side type is the source of truth — meaning the old frontend interface was a *narrowing* the SPA imposed on the wire by typing the response weaker than the actual JSON. The hoist removes that narrowing. Concrete leakage classes:\n\n  (A1) **`git_ref` leakage**: a daemon scanning private repos sets `git_ref` to the branch or tag scanned. Branch names routinely carry vulnerability identifiers in industry practice — `fix/CVE-2026-12345`, `security/patch-RUSTSEC-2026-XYZ`, `cherry-pick/embargo-issue-4242`, `internal/customer-incident-acme`. Each such branch name is an *unpublished* signal of work-in-progress on undisclosed security issues. Before the diff: this column was already in the DB but never reached the wire (the SPA shape elided it). After the diff: `GET /api/v1/runs?status=Running` returns it. Any caller with the bearer (incl. an XSS payload that has hijacked an SPA tab — and the SPA renders cap-data into finding-detail panes which is a classic XSS surface; sentinel #57/#58 already noted Markdown-render escape paths) can enumerate every recently-scanned branch name across every project on the daemon.\n\n  (A2) **`parent_run_id` graph linkage**: the `parent_run_id FOREIGN KEY` (migrations/0001_v1.sql:51) encodes the daemon's automation cadence — rescan chains, retriggered-on-fix chains, replay-bundle ancestry. Exposing it lets a caller reconstruct the operator's CI graph (e.g. \"this manual run was triggered as a child of webhook run X which scanned PR #42\" — leaks PR-number-to-internal-run-id mapping). Combined with (A1), the graph + branch-name overlay tells an attacker exactly which fix attempts are still in-flight.\n\n  (A3) **`triggered_by` operator-cadence**: the strings `Manual`, `UI`, `Webhook`, `CI`, `Scheduled` (the `ScanTriggerSource::as_run_record_string` set referenced from router.rs:1143 and nyctos/src/main.rs:1223) reveal whether a scan was operator-driven or robot-driven, which is a classic side-channel for distinguishing \"is anyone home right now\" timing attacks against the operator (e.g. an attacker submitting a webhook payload that races a manual operator action wants to know when the operator is *not* watching).\n\n  (A4) **`total_ai_spend_usd_micros` financial side-channel**: the per-run AI spend is published. An attacker measuring per-run spend across many runs reconstructs (i) the model selection used (Opus vs Sonnet ratios are visible in micros-per-finding ratios), (ii) the per-run depth-of-exploration the operator funds (low-spend runs are likely cheap/early-tier customers; high-spend runs are likely paying enterprise customers), (iii) the cap configuration (spends cluster just below the cap, revealing the cap). The OLD shape elided this column.\n\n  None of #78-#80 had an outbound dimension; #66 (provenance gap) is the closest prior finding but addresses candidate-pipeline labels, NOT run-row column emission.\n\n(B) **Inbound Deserialise reaches three new latent sinks** (parallel to #78-#80's pattern, distinct sinks):\n\n  (B1) **Budget-bypass via negative `total_ai_spend_usd_micros`** — the moment any future handler accepts `Json<RunRecord>` (or `Json<{ run: RunRecord }>` — natural for an import/replay/clone-run endpoint, given that the doc comment at run.rs:3-5 explicitly says the type \"crosses both crate and wire boundaries\"), an attacker submits `{..., \"total_ai_spend_usd_micros\": -9223372036854775000}`. Two concrete consequences depending on how the budget enforcement composes: (i) **direct cap bypass** — the per-run cap check at the verifier reads `row.total_ai_spend_usd_micros + delta < CAP_MICROS`; with the attacker-supplied negative starting value, every subsequent delta keeps the running sum well below the cap, enabling unlimited LLM spend on the attacker's chosen payloads; (ii) **integer overflow → underflow wraparound** — `i64::MIN + 1` triggers no overflow check in Rust release builds (debug builds panic; release wraps). The verifier's `total + delta` arithmetic at the budget-check site uses checked-add only if explicit; the column is loaded raw via sqlx `as i64` so the Rust value carries no clamp. The OLD frontend hand-rolled interface did not include this field so the regression slot in any existing replay/import endpoint that took the old shape silently widens to the new shape on a `cargo update` of the shared types crate.\n\n  (B2) **Timestamp-arithmetic overflow via `started_at = i64::MAX` or `finished_at = i64::MIN`**. `wall_clock_ms = finished_at - started_at` is computed at multiple call sites (UI render, run summary, /runs/:id/summary handler at router.rs:1979+). With wire-injected extreme values, the subtraction underflows. In Rust release mode the wrap-around yields a plausible-looking i64 that downstream code uses to seed *time-bound budget caps* (e.g. \"no more than $X per minute\") — a wall_clock_ms wrap to a small positive value past i64::MAX overflow turns the per-minute cap into a per-decade cap.\n\n  (B3) **`status: String` is not enum-constrained**. The wire accepts any String; the SQL UPDATE at store/run.rs:128-145 stores it verbatim; the SELECT-by-status at store/run.rs:103-119 retrieves it verbatim. A wire-injected `status = \"Running\\u0000Promoted\"` (or any unicode-similar to a valid status — `Running` vs `Runnіng` with Cyrillic і U+0456) creates a row that filters under one query and not another, splitting the run from the operator's monitoring views without removing it. Multi-byte status strings also break the per-status row-counter UI widgets that aggregate via map-by-status. The runtime enum `RunStatus` referenced in the doc comment at run.rs:9-11 deliberately stays in `nyctos_core::store::run` as a convenience helper, but no Deserialize hook on `RunRecord` calls into `RunStatus::from_str`-style validation. The OLD frontend interface had `status: string` typed but the JSON came from the server's known-good enum; post-hoist the type IS the wire input and there's no parse-time refusal.\n\n  (B4) **`triggered_by: String` is also enum-free**. Same defect, sibling enum `TriggeredBy`. Audit-log forgery primitive: a wire-injected row with `triggered_by = \"Webhook\"` makes an attacker-driven action attribution-appear-as a CI trigger in operator dashboards. Sentinel #66 named the provenance-gap pattern at a different layer (candidate-pipeline labels); THIS is the same pattern at the runs-table layer.\n\n  (B5) **`id: String` is unbounded and unrestricted** — primary-key collision via wire-injected `id` that matches an existing run row will hit the SQL UNIQUE constraint at INSERT, but UPSERT-style endpoints (any future `PUT /api/v1/runs/:id` import handler) can replace fields of an existing run, including swapping out `git_ref` (poison the audit trail).\n\n(C) **Compounds with sentinel #62-#64 (cost-cap findings)**: those findings name budget-cap defenses that the verifier today enforces by reading `runs.total_ai_spend_usd_micros`. Their threat model assumed the column was DB-internal and only INSERTed/UPDATEd via the daemon's own audited spend-tracking path. This diff makes the column wire-reachable on the read side and wire-injectable on any future write-side endpoint. The mitigations in #62-#64 (\"add a cap check at LLM-call site\") need to be reread with the new threat: the cap check now must be against a value that may have been wire-supplied during the same request lifecycle (consider: `POST /api/v1/runs/import` followed by `POST /api/v1/runs/:id/scan` — the second call's cap check reads the value the first call set).\n\n(D) **Compounds with sentinel #66 (provenance gap)**: the run-row's `triggered_by` is THE provenance signal for who-initiated. The hoist's new wire-input surface allows wire-forgery of that signal, defeating #66's mitigation requirement (`provenance must be unforgeable`) before it lands.\n\n(E) **Compounds with sentinel #11 / #14 / #21 / #24 / #65 (PATH_TRAVERSAL family)**: `RunRecord::id` is used in `<state>/traces/<run_id>/...` audit-log paths (cf. #21 PATH_TRAVERSAL via operator-influenced run_id). A wire-injectable id widens the source of the operator-influenced run_id from \"operator-edited input\" to \"any bearer-holder\", strengthening #21 from latent to currently-exploitable the moment a Json<RunRecord> route lands.\n\n(F) **Distinct from #78/#79/#80**: those three address `nyctos-types::repo` (LocalPath / TokenEnv / SshKey). This is the FOURTH instance of the same architectural defect at `nyctos-types::run`. The sinks differ: LocalPath → filesystem read; TokenEnv → env-var read; SshKey → shell exec; RunRecord → budget ledger + audit-log provenance + timestamp arithmetic + status-enum bypass + primary-key state. The unifying meta-finding is: **every type hoisted from a per-crate internal module into `nyctos-types` should require an explicit security-review checklist before adding `#[derive(Deserialize)]`**, OR the hoist should split into a `*Wire` shape and an `impl TryFrom<*Wire>` policy-checked conversion. Without an architectural fix at the workspace level, this defect will recur on every subsequent hoist (ChainRecord, FindingRecord, the next type the SPA needs).\n\nStatic pass missed because (i) the type carries no taint annotation; (ii) the Deserialize derive is correct in isolation; (iii) no current handler takes `Json<RunRecord>` so reachability analysis sees no sink (the outbound expansion in (A) is invisible to taint analysis because there is no sink — it's a *over-disclosure*, not a *over-trust*); (iv) the OLD frontend interface acted as an implicit wire contract that no static check enforced. The bug is the *delta* between the OLD elided shape and the NEW full shape; static passes do not compare wire shapes across diffs.\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+5 minimum; 3+4 are architectural):\n\n(1) **Split `RunRecord` into `RunRecord` (internal, Serialize+Deserialize+TS) and `RunRecordWire` (only Serialize+TS, only the fields the SPA needs)**. The runs router returns `RunRecordWire` derived via `impl From<RunRecord>` that *explicitly opt-INs* each field. Today `RunRecordWire` is `{ id, started_at, finished_at, status, wall_clock_ms }` — matching the OLD frontend shape minus the elided counters. Adding `git_ref` / `triggered_by` / `parent_run_id` to the wire later becomes an explicit, reviewable change rather than a silent consequence of a TS-binding refactor.\n\n(2) **Add `#[serde(deserialize_with)]` clamps on every i64 field**: `total_ai_spend_usd_micros` must be `0 <= v <= MAX_REASONABLE_SPEND` (e.g. 1_000_000_000 micros = $1k per run); `started_at` / `finished_at` / `wall_clock_ms` must be `0 <= v <= now()+24h` and `wall_clock_ms < 30 days`. These bounds catch wire-injection of extreme values and integer-overflow primitives at the deserialise layer.\n\n(3) **Replace `status: String` / `triggered_by: String` with their respective enums** at the type-level — move `RunStatus` and `TriggeredBy` (currently in `nyctos_core::store::run` per the doc comment at run.rs:9-12) into `nyctos-types::run` and derive `Serialize + Deserialize + TS` on each enum. The wire form remains a string (serde enum tag = string) but the deserialiser refuses values outside the closed set. Today the doc comment explicitly explains why the enums stayed out of the wire type — the explanation is a structural defect, not a design rationale.\n\n(4) **Workspace-level lint**: same defense as the #78 mitigation (4) — a build.rs-time scan that fails the build for any new `#[derive(Deserialize)]` on a public item in `nyctos-types::*` unless the item carries a `#[nyctos_lint::wire_input_audited(reason = \"...\")]` annotation. Audited at the diff-review layer, not the runtime layer.\n\n(5) **Behavioural regression tests** (all in `nyctos-types/tests/run.rs`):\n  - `run_record_serialised_shape_matches_documented_wire_contract` — `serde_json::to_value(&record)` returns a Value whose key set equals the documented wire contract; FAIL if the set grows without an explicit contract bump (use a snapshot test against a checked-in JSON file at `nyctos-types/tests/snapshots/run_record_wire.json`).\n  - `run_record_deserialise_refuses_negative_spend` — under mitigation (2), `serde_json::from_str::<RunRecord>(r#\"{..., \"total_ai_spend_usd_micros\": -1, ...}\"#)` returns Err.\n  - `run_record_deserialise_refuses_unknown_status` — under mitigation (3), `... \"status\": \"PendingDelete\"` returns Err.\n  - `run_record_deserialise_refuses_overflowing_timestamps` — `started_at = i64::MAX` returns Err.\n\n(6) **Document the wire-contract risk** at run.rs:6-12 — currently the doc comment NOTES the design choice (\"runtime enums stay out\") without flagging the security trade-off. Add a one-line `// SECURITY: This type is on the deserialise path of any future Json<RunRecord> handler. See sentinel #81 / #78-80.`",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-types/tests/run.rs): `run_record_deserialise_accepts_negative_spend_today` — `let json = r#\"{\"id\":\"r-attack\",\"started_at\":0,\"finished_at\":null,\"status\":\"Running\",\"triggered_by\":\"Manual\",\"git_ref\":null,\"parent_run_id\":null,\"wall_clock_ms\":null,\"total_ai_spend_usd_micros\":-9000000000000000000}\"#; let parsed: nyctos_types::run::RunRecord = serde_json::from_str(json).expect(\"deserialise\"); assert_eq!(parsed.total_ai_spend_usd_micros, -9000000000000000000_i64)`. Today: passes — demonstrates the absent-validator gap. Under mitigation (2): assert `serde_json::from_str::<RunRecord>(json).is_err()` and the error references a `total_ai_spend_usd_micros must be >= 0` validation reason. Wire-shape-snapshot reproducer (test in nyctos-types/tests/run.rs): `run_record_wire_shape_snapshot` — `let r = RunRecord { id:\"r\".into(), started_at:0, finished_at:None, status:\"Running\".into(), triggered_by:\"Manual\".into(), git_ref:None, parent_run_id:None, wall_clock_ms:None, total_ai_spend_usd_micros:0 }; let v = serde_json::to_value(&r).unwrap(); let keys: std::collections::BTreeSet<_> = v.as_object().unwrap().keys().cloned().collect(); let expected: std::collections::BTreeSet<_> = [\"id\",\"started_at\",\"finished_at\",\"status\",\"wall_clock_ms\"].iter().map(|s| s.to_string()).collect(); assert_eq!(keys, expected, \"wire shape must match documented contract; new fields require explicit review per sentinel #81\")`. Today FAILS because three extra fields are emitted; under mitigation (1) PASSES because `RunRecordWire` elides them. Status-enum reproducer: `run_record_deserialise_accepts_unknown_status_today` — `{\"status\":\"PendingDelete\",...}` deserialises Ok today; under mitigation (3) returns Err. Cyrillic-status side-channel reproducer: `run_record_status_admits_unicode_lookalike` — `{\"status\":\"Runn\\u0456ng\",...}` (Cyrillic і U+0456 in place of ASCII i) deserialises Ok today and INSERTs a row that filters under neither `status=Running` nor `status=Failed` queries; under mitigation (3) returns Err. Outbound field-expansion reproducer (HTTP-level, in nyctos-api/tests/api.rs): `runs_endpoint_does_not_emit_internal_provenance_fields_after_mitigation_1` — `let resp: serde_json::Value = reqwest::get(format!(\"{}/api/v1/runs?status=Running\", srv.base())).await.unwrap().json().await.unwrap(); let row = &resp.as_array().unwrap()[0]; assert!(!row.as_object().unwrap().contains_key(\"git_ref\"), \"git_ref is operator-internal\"); assert!(!row.as_object().unwrap().contains_key(\"triggered_by\")); assert!(!row.as_object().unwrap().contains_key(\"parent_run_id\")); assert!(!row.as_object().unwrap().contains_key(\"total_ai_spend_usd_micros\"))`. Today: FAILS (the four asserts all hit; the diff ships those fields wire-side); under mitigation (1) PASSES."
