record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 521,
  "cap": "SECRET_DISCLOSURE",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/projects + GET /api/v1/projects/:project_id",
  "rationale": "Read-side complement to finding #89 (write-side env-injection): `list_projects` (router.rs:521) and `get_project` (router.rs:570) serialize the full `ProjectRecord` to JSON via `Json(rows)` / `Json(rec)`. The hoisted struct at `crates/nyctos-types/src/project.rs:54-65` carries `env_config_json: Option<String>` with NO `#[serde(skip_serializing)]`, NO `#[serde(serialize_with = redact)]`, and NO DTO split between storage and wire — the same struct sqlx hydrates from the row (store/project.rs:73-82, 121-129, 145-153, 170-179) is the struct axum hands to the JSON serializer. `env_config_json` is the opaque blob that #89 documents as carrying `LD_PRELOAD`/`GIT_SSH_COMMAND`/`NODE_OPTIONS`/`PYTHONSTARTUP` and every other env-clobber primitive; in any production install it ALSO carries the conventional secret payload that motivates a per-project env file in the first place — `DATABASE_URL`, `REDIS_URL`, `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`, `OPENAI_API_KEY`, GitHub PATs, AWS access keys, customer-tenant Postgres credentials, signed-webhook HMAC seeds, third-party SaaS bearer tokens. The auth gate in front (auth_layer at router.rs:100-120) is single-tier bearer-only with no per-project ACL, no role separation, and no read-only scope: every bearer-holder (operator, CI runner, MCP integration, anything the operator pasted the token into) reads every project's `env_config_json` in cleartext. This compounds three other sentinel findings into an immediate exploit chain: (1) #91-class (CRED_EXPOSURE, the existing finding about `?token=` URL-query auth at router.rs:141 → TraceLayer logs the bearer in cleartext to stderr/journald), (2) the DNS-rebind finding at main.rs:1035 (any malicious page the operator visits can pivot to loopback once a token has leaked anywhere), (3) finding #92 below (Deserialize-hoist mass-assignment lets a future endpoint accept a forged ProjectRecord whose `id` matches an existing project, lateral-moving the env_config_json across tenants). Concrete chain: TraceLayer logs a token → attacker scrapes it from a misconfigured log shipper → attacker calls `GET /api/v1/projects` once → harvests every project's complete env-secret set in a single response. The diff didn't introduce the cleartext exposure on its own (the field has been wire-serialised since the original projects API landed) but the diff CRYSTALLIZES the contract by writing `env_config_json: string | null` into the public TS surface at `frontend/src/api/types.gen.ts:174` — future server-side attempts to redact the field will now silently break the SPA's typed access (the TS compiler will let the SPA read `record.env_config_json` and expect a non-undefined optional-of-string), so the cleartext contract is now load-bearing on the frontend type system. Static pass missed because (i) serde_json::Serialize on a struct of `Option<String>` is correct in isolation; (ii) the secret labeling is semantic, not syntactic (no `password`/`secret`/`token` substring in the field name — `env_config_json` reads as 'configuration'); (iii) the trust boundary that determines whether disclosure is in-policy is the bearer-auth gate, which lives in middleware not in the handler. Mitigations: (1) split `ProjectRecord` into `ProjectRecordWire` (no `env_config_json`) and `ProjectRecordFull` (internal-only), return `ProjectRecordWire` from list/get and require a separate `GET /api/v1/projects/:id/env-config` route that gates on a distinct `env:read` scope; (2) at minimum add `#[serde(serialize_with = \"redact_env_config\")]` on the field so the wire form is `\"<redacted; N keys>\"` and the SPA only sees a sentinel; (3) add a behavioural regression test in `nyctos-api/tests/api.rs`: `get_projects_does_not_leak_env_config_json` — POST a project with `env_config: {\"DATABASE_URL\": \"postgres://user:pw@host/db\"}`, then `GET /api/v1/projects` and assert the response body does NOT contain `\"user:pw\"` or `\"DATABASE_URL\"`; today this test FAILS, under mitigation (1) or (2) it PASSES.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "curl -H 'Authorization: Bearer <leaked-token>' http://127.0.0.1:8088/api/v1/projects | jq '.[].env_config_json' — each entry is the cleartext serialised env JSON for that project, parseable in one line. Alt path: open the SPA's Projects page in a hijacked tab and read `window.__REACT_QUERY_CACHE__` for the cached response."
}

