record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-types/src/project.rs",
  "line": 63,
  "cap": "JS_NUMBER_PRECISION_DRIFT",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/projects + GET /api/v1/projects/:id (created_at, updated_at)",
  "rationale": "`ProjectRecord::created_at` / `updated_at` are `i64` in Rust (nyctos-types/src/project.rs:62-65) but the new `#[ts(type = \"number\")]` annotation (:62, :64) declares the wire-side shape as JS `number`. JS `Number` is IEEE-754 f64; `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` is 2^53-1 ≈ 9.007e15. Two distinct hazards land the moment the bridge is treated as authoritative by the SPA: (1) **Sort-order collapse on wire-injected extreme values** — the same Deserialize hoist that powers #92 means a future `Json<ProjectRecord>` handler accepts attacker-supplied `created_at: i64::MAX = 9223372036854775807`. The daemon round-trips that i64 through SQLite (the `created_at!: i64` annotation at store/project.rs:113,137,161 keeps it lossless server-side) but the SPA receives the JSON number and `JSON.parse` rounds it to the nearest f64, yielding `9223372036854776000` — three different i64 values (`...775807`, `...775808`, `...775809`) all collapse to the same JS Number, so the SPA's `list()` view sorted-by-created-at orders them non-deterministically and the operator's CLI-vs-UI views of the same row disagree on which project was created first. (2) **Round-trip lossiness across PATCH** — a SPA that reads ProjectRecord, mutates `description`, then re-POSTs the WHOLE record to a future `PUT /api/v1/projects/:id` round-trips `created_at` through f64; on store the i64 is now ROUNDED, silently overwriting the original create-time stamp with a value that drifts by up to 1023 ms (the f64 ULP at the year-2286 boundary; smaller today, but the contract has no clamp). The store's `created_at AS \"created_at!: i64\"` SELECT helper now reads back a rounded value. The `#[ts(type = \"number\")]` annotation's doc comment at nyctos-types/src/project.rs:50-53 says `serde_json` emits a JSON number for i64 which JS receives as `number` — TRUE today because epoch-ms ≈ 1.74e12 fits in f64, but the comment encodes a precision assumption that the type-deserialise layer has no way to enforce. A future migration to epoch-nanoseconds (1.74e18) immediately blows past `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` and the contract silently loses 9+ bits of precision on every read. Distinct from #81 (which names timestamp overflow on RunRecord) — that finding is about i64 arithmetic overflow at the server; THIS finding is about f64 precision loss at the SPA wire boundary, driven by the `#[ts(type = \"number\")]` choice. Static pass cannot see it because no Rust-side flow loses precision; the loss happens in the generated TS contract.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (frontend unit test, or nyctos-types/tests/project.rs after adding a JS-side equivalence harness): seed `created_at = 9223372036854775807` (i64::MAX) through any handler that returns ProjectRecord; assert `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify({created_at: 9223372036854775807n})).created_at !== 9223372036854775807n` and equals `9223372036854776000`. Sort-collapse reproducer: insert three project rows with `created_at` values `9007199254740993`, `9007199254740994`, `9007199254740995` (each above MAX_SAFE_INTEGER); fetch `GET /api/v1/projects`; in JS, observe all three deserialise to the same `Number` and the array's stable-sort by created_at returns rows in insertion order rather than created_at order. Mitigations: (a) change `#[ts(type = \"number\")]` to `#[ts(type = \"string\")]` and serialise as a string (`serde(serialize_with = \"i64_to_str\")` — same pattern other ts_rs users adopt for `bigint` on the wire); (b) add a `#[serde(deserialize_with)]` clamp asserting `0 <= v <= Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER = 9007199254740991` at the wire-deserialise layer so wire-injected extremes are refused before they reach the store."
}

