  "endpoint": "internal: `ProjectRecord` (nyctos-types/src/project.rs:57-65) `#[derive(Deserialize)]` post-hoist — fifth instance of the #78/#79/#80/#81 architectural pattern (Deserialize hoist of a core type into nyctos-types without per-field validators). Today no axum handler takes `Json<ProjectRecord>`; the moment one lands (a `PUT /api/v1/projects/:id` import, a `POST /api/v1/projects/bulk`, a replay-bundle ingester that walks projects from a tarball, the future `nyctos-cli project import` endpoint) the wire-injectable `id: String` reaches the store's UPDATE-by-id sink at nyctos-core/src/store/project.rs:199-216.",
  "rationale": "The well-known constant `DEFAULT_PROJECT_ID = \"default-project\"` (nyctos-core/src/store/project.rs:16) is the FK target for every legacy caller without an explicit project context (`ensure_default` at :88-106 is the bootstrap; the comment at :12-15 says legacy config files and legacy API consumers all attach repos to this id). The default row's `target_base_url` / `env_config_json` start as NULL on `ensure_default` but are mutable via the same `update()` sink that any wire payload would hit. Two attacks land the moment a `Json<ProjectRecord>`-style handler is added: (1) **Default-project hijack** — attacker submits `{\"id\": \"default-project\", \"name\": \"default\", \"description\": null, \"target_base_url\": \"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\", \"env_config_json\": \"{\\\"LD_PRELOAD\\\":\\\"/tmp/x.so\\\",\\\"GIT_SSH_COMMAND\\\":\\\"...\\\"}\", \"created_at\": 0, \"updated_at\": 0}`. The store's `update()` at store/project.rs:183-216 looks up the existing row by id, merges the patch, and writes back — every existing legacy caller that resolves \"the default project\" then inherits the attacker's `target_base_url` (compounds with #88 SSRF sink in compose.rs:231-234) and `env_config_json` (compounds with #89 env-injection sink in compose.rs:235-238). The hijack is persistent across daemon restarts because it lands in SQLite, not memory. (2) **Cross-project shadowing** — attacker enumerates project ids via `GET /api/v1/projects` (no auth check on the listing per pre-existing finding #2 / setup-window) then submits ProjectRecord payloads with each id, mass-pivoting every project's compose lane to attacker URLs in one bulk POST. (3) **Collision with uuid-derived id namespace** — the create-handler at router.rs:548 generates ids as `format!(\"proj-{}\", uuid_like(name, now_epoch_ms()))`. A wire-injected `id: \"proj-deadbeef...\"` that matches a future legitimate uuid_like output creates a row at the namespace the daemon expected to allocate next; the next `create_project` call hits a UNIQUE-constraint violation but the attacker's row remains. The `id: String` is unbounded — no length cap, no charset restriction, no must-match-uuid-shape constraint. (4) **`name: String` Default-project name collision** — same payload with `name: \"default\"` collides with `DEFAULT_PROJECT_NAME = \"default\"` (store/project.rs:17). `get_by_name` at store/project.rs:132-154 then returns whichever row sorts first; the `name` column has a UNIQUE constraint in the schema (migrations/0001_v1.sql, projects table) so the SECOND insert fails but the FIRST insert wins — race against `ensure_default` on a fresh daemon and the attacker's row IS the default project. (5) **`created_at` / `updated_at` wire-injection** drops `created_at` to 0, which sorts the row first in `list()` (store/project.rs:163's `ORDER BY name` is stable but other future sorts by created_at would float the attacker's row to the top of the SPA's project picker — typosquatting-style social-engineering primitive). Compounds with #91 (the f64-precision side of created_at wire-injection). Sentinel #78/#79/#80 (RepoSource / GitAuth) and #81 (RunRecord) name the SAME architectural pattern at four prior types; this is the FIFTH instance and the unifying meta-finding remains: hoisting a core-store type into nyctos-types with a `#[derive(Deserialize)]` derive should be gated behind a workspace-level audit (per #81 mitigation (4)). Without the architectural fix, expect this pattern to recur on ChainRecord / FindingRecord / the next type the SPA needs. Static pass cannot see it: no current axum handler is the sink (Reachability is `0`), but the Deserialize derive is the latent half of a two-step landmine that activates the moment a new handler is added in a future PR.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed (unit test in nyctos-types/tests/project.rs): `project_record_deserialise_admits_default_project_id_collision_today` — `let json = r#\"{\"id\":\"default-project\",\"name\":\"default\",\"description\":null,\"target_base_url\":\"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\",\"env_config_json\":\"{\\\"LD_PRELOAD\\\":\\\"/tmp/evil.so\\\"}\",\"created_at\":0,\"updated_at\":0}\"#; let parsed: nyctos_types::project::ProjectRecord = serde_json::from_str(json).expect(\"deserialise\"); assert_eq!(parsed.id, \"default-project\"); assert_eq!(parsed.target_base_url.as_deref(), Some(\"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\"))`. Today passes — demonstrates the absent-validator gap. Mitigation: split `ProjectRecord` (in-memory) from `ProjectRecordWire` (only `Serialize + TS`, no `Deserialize`) per #81 mitigation (1); for any new handler that imports projects, accept an explicit `ProjectImportRequest` DTO with a `#[serde(deserialize_with)]` that refuses `id` matching the `^default-project$` regex or any id whose CHARSET is not `^proj-[a-f0-9]{16}$`. End-to-end reproducer (requires a future Json<ProjectRecord> route — write the test, fail it, then ship the fix): drive the route with the above payload; today assert `s.store.projects().get(\"default-project\").await?.target_base_url.as_deref() == Some(\"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\")`; under mitigation assert route returns 400 BEFORE the store is touched."
